window.trendingPapers = {
    "today": [{"paper": {"id": "2606.29538", "authors": [{"_id": "6a599a716c2e371e6ca38125", "name": "Yijia Fan", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a599a716c2e371e6ca38126", "name": "Zonglin Di", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a599a716c2e371e6ca38127", "name": "Zimo Wen", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a599a716c2e371e6ca38128", "name": "Yifan Yang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a599a716c2e371e6ca38129", "name": "Mingxi Cheng", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a599a716c2e371e6ca3812a", "user": {"_id": "65115c00a588fdb36558b673", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/1f36263dc4bfaf696a4aa959a6aab1e1.svg", "isPro": false, "fullname": "Qi Dai", "user": "daiqi", "type": "user", "name": "daiqi"}, "name": "Qi Dai", "status": "claimed_verified", "statusLastChangedAt": "2026-07-20T16:05:41.351Z", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a599a716c2e371e6ca3812b", "name": "Bei Liu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a599a716c2e371e6ca3812c", "name": "Kai Qiu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a599a716c2e371e6ca3812d", "name": "Yue Dong", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a599a716c2e371e6ca3812e", "name": "Ji Li", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a599a716c2e371e6ca3812f", "name": "Chong Luo", "hidden": false}], "mediaUrls": ["https://cdn-uploads.huggingface.co/production/uploads/62d18eb81e36881a57f29bf4/aZPQHsZww6x3R9D_J7Si9.mp4"], "publishedAt": "2026-07-16T00:00:00.000Z", "submittedOnDailyAt": "2026-07-20T00:00:00.000Z", "title": "RESOURCE2SKILL: Distilling Executable Agent Skills from Human-Created Multimodal Resources", "submittedOnDailyBy": {"_id": "62d18eb81e36881a57f29bf4", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/104851421b4ee9641daaf15942fa7ea1.svg", "isPro": false, "fullname": "Yif Yang", "user": "Yif29", "type": "user", "name": "Yif29"}, "summary": "Skills are a useful abstraction for software agents, turning human and agent experience into reusable procedural knowledge. Yet existing skill libraries are mostly hand-written, text-centric, or derived from agent traces, leaving tutorial videos and other multimodal human resources largely underused. We present RESOURCE2SKILL, a framework that distills multimodal resources, including tutorial videos, repositories, articles, and reference artifacts, into executable skills for software agents. RESOURCE2SKILL organizes these skills as a hierarchical multimodal Skill Wiki, where each entry combines structured text, code, visual examples, metadata, and provenance. This design preserves complementary signals from different resources: videos capture temporal operations and visual effects, code captures executable tool patterns, and articles or artifacts provide conceptual and stylistic grounding. At inference time, agents retrieve and compose relevant skills from the wiki; when coverage is insufficient, the same construction operator can acquire new skills online. Across seven practical authoring domains, RESOURCE2SKILL improves average overall score by +11.9 percentage points over no-skill agents and outperforms strong harness baselines in 26 of 28 main-aggregate model-domain cells. Ablations confirm the value of multimodal skill format, hierarchical organization, source diversity, selection strategy, and online acquisition.", "upvotes": 113, "discussionId": "6a599a726c2e371e6ca38130", "projectPage": "https://aka.ms/Resources2Skill", "githubRepo": "https://github.com/microsoft/Resource2Skill", "githubRepoAddedBy": "user", "githubStars": 64, "organization": {"_id": "68151d0f51add3813f3f7d1b", "name": "MicrosoftResearch", "fullname": "Microsoft Research", "avatar": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/6529a4f2f1205983224fa513/PeuVr7jSuJflmDBBGxoDX.png"}, "summary_zh": "<ul>\n    <li>RESOURCE2SKILL\u662f\u4e00\u4e2a\u5c06\u591a\u79cd\u8d44\u6e90\uff08\u5982\u6559\u7a0b\u89c6\u9891\u3001\u6587\u7ae0\u7b49\uff09\u8f6c\u5316\u4e3a\u8f6f\u4ef6\u4ee3\u7406\u53ef\u6267\u884c\u6280\u80fd\u7684\u6846\u67b6\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u8be5\u6846\u67b6\u5c06\u6280\u80fd\u7ec4\u7ec7\u6210\u4e00\u4e2a\u5c42\u6b21\u5316\u7684\u591a\u6a21\u6001\u6280\u80fd\u7ef4\u57fa\uff0c\u7ed3\u5408\u4e86\u6587\u672c\u3001\u4ee3\u7801\u3001\u89c6\u89c9\u793a\u4f8b\u7b49\u4fe1\u606f\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u901a\u8fc7\u591a\u79cd\u8d44\u6e90\u7684\u7ed3\u5408\uff0c\u4fdd\u7559\u4e86\u89c6\u9891\u7684\u65f6\u95f4\u64cd\u4f5c\u3001\u4ee3\u7801\u7684\u53ef\u6267\u884c\u6a21\u5f0f\u548c\u6587\u7ae0\u7684\u6982\u5ff5\u57fa\u7840\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u5728\u4e03\u4e2a\u5b9e\u9645\u5e94\u7528\u9886\u57df\u4e2d\uff0cRESOURCE2SKILL\u4f7f\u5e73\u5747\u5206\u6570\u63d0\u9ad8\u4e8611.9%\uff0c\u5e76\u572826\u4e2a\u6a21\u578b\u57df\u4e2d\u8d85\u8fc7\u4e86\u5f3a\u57fa\u7ebf\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u5b9e\u9a8c\u7ed3\u679c\u8868\u660e\uff0c\u6280\u80fd\u7684\u591a\u6a21\u6001\u683c\u5f0f\u548c\u5c42\u6b21\u5316\u7ec4\u7ec7\u5177\u6709\u91cd\u8981\u4ef7\u503c\u3002 </li>\n</ul>", "summary_simple": "<ul>\n    <li>RESOURCE2SKILL is a new system that helps software agents learn skills from various resources, like tutorial videos and articles.</li>\n    <li>The system organizes these skills in a hierarchical Skill Wiki, combining text, code, visuals, and metadata.</li>\n    <li>This approach uses different types of resources effectively; videos show how things work over time, while code provides practical examples.</li>\n    <li>When agents need new skills, they can find and create them using this system, improving their performance significantly.</li>\n    <li>Tests show RESOURCE2SKILL improves agent performance by an average of 11.9 percentage points compared to agents without skills.</li>\n</ul>"}, "publishedAt": "2026-07-15T20:00:00.000Z", "title": "RESOURCE2SKILL: Distilling Executable Agent Skills from Human-Created Multimodal Resources", "summary": "Skills are a useful abstraction for software agents, turning human and agent experience into reusable procedural knowledge. Yet existing skill libraries are mostly hand-written, text-centric, or derived from agent traces, leaving tutorial videos and other multimodal human resources largely underused. We present RESOURCE2SKILL, a framework that distills multimodal resources, including tutorial videos, repositories, articles, and reference artifacts, into executable skills for software agents. RESOURCE2SKILL organizes these skills as a hierarchical multimodal Skill Wiki, where each entry combines structured text, code, visual examples, metadata, and provenance. This design preserves complementary signals from different resources: videos capture temporal operations and visual effects, code captures executable tool patterns, and articles or artifacts provide conceptual and stylistic grounding. At inference time, agents retrieve and compose relevant skills from the wiki; when coverage is insufficient, the same construction operator can acquire new skills online. Across seven practical authoring domains, RESOURCE2SKILL improves average overall score by +11.9 percentage points over no-skill agents and outperforms strong harness baselines in 26 of 28 main-aggregate model-domain cells. Ablations confirm the value of multimodal skill format, hierarchical organization, source diversity, selection strategy, and online acquisition.", "mediaUrls": ["https://cdn-uploads.huggingface.co/production/uploads/62d18eb81e36881a57f29bf4/aZPQHsZww6x3R9D_J7Si9.mp4"], "thumbnail": "https://cdn-thumbnails.huggingface.co/social-thumbnails/papers/2606.29538.png", "numComments": 1, "submittedBy": {"_id": "62d18eb81e36881a57f29bf4", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/104851421b4ee9641daaf15942fa7ea1.svg", "fullname": "Yif Yang", "name": "Yif29", "type": "user", "isPro": false, "isHf": false, "isHfAdmin": false, "isMod": false, "followerCount": 5, "isUserFollowing": false}, "organization": {"_id": "68151d0f51add3813f3f7d1b", "name": "MicrosoftResearch", "fullname": "Microsoft Research", "avatar": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/6529a4f2f1205983224fa513/PeuVr7jSuJflmDBBGxoDX.png"}, "isAuthorParticipating": false}, {"paper": {"id": "2607.11683", "authors": [{"_id": "6a55e685a9d74d6e65bbd8f3", "user": {"_id": "668bdbf4db71d9daf74909ec", "avatarUrl": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/668bdbf4db71d9daf74909ec/HspmqM3ITYR4vn59z1hxt.jpeg", "isPro": false, "fullname": "Mikhail Komarov", "user": "AsphodelRem", "type": "user", "name": "AsphodelRem"}, "name": "Mikhail Komarov", "status": "claimed_verified", "statusLastChangedAt": "2026-07-20T16:04:58.625Z", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a55e685a9d74d6e65bbd8f4", "name": "Ivan Bondarenko", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a55e685a9d74d6e65bbd8f5", "name": "Stanislav Shtuka", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a55e685a9d74d6e65bbd8f6", "name": "Oleg Sedukhin", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a55e685a9d74d6e65bbd8f7", "name": "Roman Shuvalov", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a55e685a9d74d6e65bbd8f8", "user": {"_id": "65de080d7b8cd1aab189a284", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/b9e84281959004689c5be6401801c408.svg", "isPro": false, "fullname": "Yana Dementyeva", "user": "YanaDementyeva", "type": "user", "name": "YanaDementyeva"}, "name": "Yana Dementyeva", "status": "claimed_verified", "statusLastChangedAt": "2026-07-20T16:04:59.255Z", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a55e685a9d74d6e65bbd8f9", "name": "Matvey Solovyov", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a55e685a9d74d6e65bbd8fa", "name": "Nikolay O. Nikitin", "hidden": false}], "publishedAt": "2026-07-13T00:00:00.000Z", "submittedOnDailyAt": "2026-07-20T00:00:00.000Z", "title": "RAGU: A Multi-Step GraphRAG Engine with a Compact Domain-Adapted LLM", "submittedOnDailyBy": {"_id": "62b1e0f76a5435fd9a60a8dc", "avatarUrl": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/1655824626110-noauth.png", "isPro": true, "fullname": "Ivan Bondarenko", "user": "bond005", "type": "user", "name": "bond005"}, "summary": "Graph retrieval-augmented generation (GraphRAG) enhances large language models with structured knowledge, yet existing systems construct knowledge graphs in a single extraction pass, producing noisy entities and brittle retrieval. RAGU, an open-source modular GraphRAG engine, addresses this by separating extraction from consolidation: entities and relations pass through two-stage typed extraction, DBSCAN-backed deduplication, LLM summarization, and Leiden community detection. A key insight motivates a compact extractor: the skills an in-pipeline LLM needs - comprehension, extraction, reasoning over context - are language skills that grow only weakly with model size, unlike factual world knowledge. Accordingly, we train Meno-Lite-0.1, a 7B model optimized for language skills, which outperforms Qwen2.5-32B on knowledge-graph construction (+12.5% relative harmonic mean) and matches it on English GraphRAG tasks. On GraphRAG-Bench (Medical), RAGU retrieves the most complete context at every factoid level (evidence recall up to 0.84 vs. leq0.76) and overtakes HippoRAG2 on synthesis tasks; on multi-hop factoid QA, the apparent HippoRAG2 advantage is shown to be largely an answer-format artifact. RAGU is installable via pip install graph_ragu, runs on a single GPU, and is released under MIT. The source code is publicly available at https://github.com/RaguTeam/RAGU, and the Meno-Lite-0.1 model can be obtained from https://huggingface.co/bond005/meno-lite-0.1.", "upvotes": 111, "discussionId": "6a55e686a9d74d6e65bbd8fb", "githubRepo": "https://github.com/RaguTeam/RAGU", "githubRepoAddedBy": "user", "githubStars": 77, "organization": {"_id": "62b1e262f4a72794188b6757", "name": "NSU", "fullname": "Novosibirsk State University", "avatar": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/1655825086683-62b1e0f76a5435fd9a60a8dc.png"}, "summary_zh": "<ul>\n    <li>GraphRAG\u901a\u8fc7\u7ed3\u6784\u5316\u77e5\u8bc6\u589e\u5f3a\u5927\u578b\u8bed\u8a00\u6a21\u578b\uff0c\u4f46\u73b0\u6709\u7cfb\u7edf\u5728\u77e5\u8bc6\u56fe\u8c31\u6784\u5efa\u4e2d\u5b58\u5728\u566a\u58f0\u548c\u8106\u5f31\u6027\u3002</li>\n    <li>RAGU\u662f\u4e00\u4e2a\u5f00\u6e90\u7684\u6a21\u5757\u5316GraphRAG\u5f15\u64ce\uff0c\u901a\u8fc7\u5206\u79bb\u63d0\u53d6\u548c\u6574\u5408\u6765\u89e3\u51b3\u8fd9\u4e9b\u95ee\u9898\u3002</li>\n    <li>RAGU\u4f7f\u7528\u4e24\u9636\u6bb5\u7c7b\u578b\u63d0\u53d6\u3001\u53bb\u91cd\u3001\u603b\u7ed3\u548c\u793e\u533a\u68c0\u6d4b\u6765\u63d0\u9ad8\u77e5\u8bc6\u56fe\u8c31\u7684\u8d28\u91cf\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u8bad\u7ec3\u7684Meno-Lite-0.1\u6a21\u578b\u5728\u77e5\u8bc6\u56fe\u8c31\u6784\u5efa\u4e0a\u8868\u73b0\u4f18\u4e8e\u66f4\u5927\u7684Qwen2.5-32B\u6a21\u578b\u3002</li>\n    <li>RAGU\u53ef\u901a\u8fc7pip\u5b89\u88c5\uff0c\u652f\u6301\u5355GPU\u8fd0\u884c\uff0c\u6e90\u4ee3\u7801\u548c\u6a21\u578b\u53ef\u5728GitHub\u548cHugging Face\u4e0a\u83b7\u53d6\u3002</li>\n</ul>", "summary_simple": "<ul>\n    <li>GraphRAG improves language models by using structured knowledge but often produces noisy results.</li>\n    <li>RAGU is a new open-source tool that improves knowledge graph creation by separating the extraction and consolidation processes.</li>\n    <li>It uses advanced techniques like deduplication and community detection to enhance the quality of the graphs.</li>\n    <li>The Meno-Lite-0.1 model, designed for better language skills, performs better than larger models on knowledge graph tasks.</li>\n    <li>RAGU can be easily installed, runs on a single GPU, and its code and model are available online.</li>\n</ul>"}, "publishedAt": "2026-07-12T20:00:00.000Z", "title": "RAGU: A Multi-Step GraphRAG Engine with a Compact Domain-Adapted LLM", "summary": "Graph retrieval-augmented generation (GraphRAG) enhances large language models with structured knowledge, yet existing systems construct knowledge graphs in a single extraction pass, producing noisy entities and brittle retrieval. RAGU, an open-source modular GraphRAG engine, addresses this by separating extraction from consolidation: entities and relations pass through two-stage typed extraction, DBSCAN-backed deduplication, LLM summarization, and Leiden community detection. A key insight motivates a compact extractor: the skills an in-pipeline LLM needs - comprehension, extraction, reasoning over context - are language skills that grow only weakly with model size, unlike factual world knowledge. Accordingly, we train Meno-Lite-0.1, a 7B model optimized for language skills, which outperforms Qwen2.5-32B on knowledge-graph construction (+12.5% relative harmonic mean) and matches it on English GraphRAG tasks. On GraphRAG-Bench (Medical), RAGU retrieves the most complete context at every factoid level (evidence recall up to 0.84 vs. leq0.76) and overtakes HippoRAG2 on synthesis tasks; on multi-hop factoid QA, the apparent HippoRAG2 advantage is shown to be largely an answer-format artifact. RAGU is installable via pip install graph_ragu, runs on a single GPU, and is released under MIT. The source code is publicly available at https://github.com/RaguTeam/RAGU, and the Meno-Lite-0.1 model can be obtained from https://huggingface.co/bond005/meno-lite-0.1.", "thumbnail": "https://cdn-thumbnails.huggingface.co/social-thumbnails/papers/2607.11683.png", "numComments": 3, "submittedBy": {"_id": "62b1e0f76a5435fd9a60a8dc", "avatarUrl": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/1655824626110-noauth.png", "fullname": "Ivan Bondarenko", "name": "bond005", "type": "user", "isPro": true, "isHf": false, "isHfAdmin": false, "isMod": false, "followerCount": 88, "isUserFollowing": false}, "organization": {"_id": "62b1e262f4a72794188b6757", "name": "NSU", "fullname": "Novosibirsk State University", "avatar": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/1655825086683-62b1e0f76a5435fd9a60a8dc.png"}, "isAuthorParticipating": false}, {"paper": {"id": "2607.16051", "authors": [{"_id": "6a5d835d6a69ce099f4d6d79", "user": {"_id": "641ddac5be3bd3a5a06ed4a4", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/14969dff861d53b0a75305606495eca7.svg", "isPro": false, "fullname": "Zitian Gao", "user": "zgao3186", "type": "user", "name": "zgao3186"}, "name": "Zitian Gao", "status": "claimed_verified", "statusLastChangedAt": "2026-07-20T16:06:01.598Z", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d835d6a69ce099f4d6d7a", "name": "Yilong Chen", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d835d6a69ce099f4d6d7b", "name": "Yihao Xiao", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d835d6a69ce099f4d6d7c", "name": "Xinyu Yang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d835d6a69ce099f4d6d7d", "name": "Ran Tao", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d835d6a69ce099f4d6d7e", "name": "Joey Zhou", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d835d6a69ce099f4d6d7f", "name": "Bryan Dai", "hidden": false}], "publishedAt": "2026-07-17T00:00:00.000Z", "submittedOnDailyAt": "2026-07-20T00:00:00.000Z", "title": "Loop the Loopies!", "submittedOnDailyBy": {"_id": "6039478ab3ecf716b1a5fd4d", "avatarUrl": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/6039478ab3ecf716b1a5fd4d/_Thy4E7taiSYBLKxEKJbT.jpeg", "isPro": true, "fullname": "taesiri", "user": "taesiri", "type": "user", "name": "taesiri"}, "summary": "We present Loopie, the most powerful looped Transformer to date. The Loopie series consists of two Mixture-of-Experts (MoE) models: a 20B-parameter model with 2B active parameters and a 6Bparameter model with 0.6B active parameters. Looped Transformers have long faced a challenge: given an N-fold increase in pre-training compute, increasing the parameter count by a factor of N usually outperforms looping a model N times. Loopie addresses this challenge. Extensive ablation studies, including comparisons with a vanilla 30B-A3B model, show that Loopie substantially outperforms vanilla Transformer baselines trained with the same compute budget. Our novel post-training pipeline equips Loopie with strong reasoning abilities. At the 2025 IMO and IPhO, Loopie achieves gold-medal performance without tools.", "upvotes": 55, "discussionId": "6a5d835d6a69ce099f4d6d80", "organization": {"_id": "6937e1578cd2568ba4c9d3f9", "name": "IQuestLab", "fullname": "IQuest", "avatar": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/68c80cc3a1ca9a73c17d29f7/pjOEigZuk_UQ4dqyS482V.png"}, "summary_zh": "<ul>\n    <li>Loopie\u662f\u76ee\u524d\u6700\u5f3a\u5927\u7684\u5faa\u73af\u53d8\u6362\u5668\uff0c\u5305\u542b\u4e24\u4e2a\u6df7\u5408\u4e13\u5bb6\u6a21\u578b\u3002</li>\n    <li>20B\u53c2\u6570\u6a21\u578b\u67092B\u6d3b\u8dc3\u53c2\u6570\uff0c6B\u53c2\u6570\u6a21\u578b\u67090.6B\u6d3b\u8dc3\u53c2\u6570\u3002</li>\n    <li>Loopie\u89e3\u51b3\u4e86\u5faa\u73af\u53d8\u6362\u5668\u5728\u9884\u8bad\u7ec3\u8ba1\u7b97\u589e\u957f\u65f6\u7684\u6027\u80fd\u6311\u6218\u3002</li>\n    <li>Loopie\u5728\u4e0e\u4f20\u7edf30B-A3B\u6a21\u578b\u7684\u6bd4\u8f83\u4e2d\u8868\u73b0\u4f18\u8d8a\u3002</li>\n    <li>Loopie\u5177\u5907\u5f3a\u5927\u7684\u63a8\u7406\u80fd\u529b\uff0c\u5e76\u57282025\u5e74IMO\u548cIPhO\u4e2d\u8868\u73b0\u51fa\u8272\u3002</li>\n</ul>", "summary_simple": "<ul>\n  <li>Loopie is a new and powerful looped Transformer model.</li>\n  <li>It includes two versions: a 20 billion parameter model and a 6 billion parameter model.</li>\n  <li>Loopie improves performance by handling increased computational power better than traditional models.</li>\n  <li>It has been tested extensively and outperforms standard Transformer models with the same resources.</li>\n  <li>Loopie shows excellent reasoning skills and achieved top results in competitions without using tools.</li>\n</ul>"}, "publishedAt": "2026-07-16T20:00:00.000Z", "title": "Loop the Loopies!", "summary": "We present Loopie, the most powerful looped Transformer to date. The Loopie series consists of two Mixture-of-Experts (MoE) models: a 20B-parameter model with 2B active parameters and a 6Bparameter model with 0.6B active parameters. Looped Transformers have long faced a challenge: given an N-fold increase in pre-training compute, increasing the parameter count by a factor of N usually outperforms looping a model N times. Loopie addresses this challenge. Extensive ablation studies, including comparisons with a vanilla 30B-A3B model, show that Loopie substantially outperforms vanilla Transformer baselines trained with the same compute budget. Our novel post-training pipeline equips Loopie with strong reasoning abilities. At the 2025 IMO and IPhO, Loopie achieves gold-medal performance without tools.", "thumbnail": "https://cdn-thumbnails.huggingface.co/social-thumbnails/papers/2607.16051.png", "numComments": 0, "submittedBy": {"_id": "6039478ab3ecf716b1a5fd4d", "avatarUrl": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/6039478ab3ecf716b1a5fd4d/_Thy4E7taiSYBLKxEKJbT.jpeg", "fullname": "taesiri", "name": "taesiri", "type": "user", "isPro": true, "isHf": false, "isHfAdmin": false, "isMod": false, "followerCount": 338, "isUserFollowing": false}, "organization": {"_id": "6937e1578cd2568ba4c9d3f9", "name": "IQuestLab", "fullname": "IQuest", "avatar": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/68c80cc3a1ca9a73c17d29f7/pjOEigZuk_UQ4dqyS482V.png"}, "isAuthorParticipating": false}, {"paper": {"id": "2607.15330", "authors": [{"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6de9", "name": "Xiaomi Robotics Team", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6dea", "name": "Jun Guo", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6deb", "name": "Piaopiao Jin", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6dec", "name": "Jason Li", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6ded", "user": {"_id": "6337e04b171879571956212f", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/aa69142bf92e4c50b192463490251ed9.svg", "isPro": false, "fullname": "Li Peiyan", "user": "LPY", "type": "user", "name": "LPY"}, "name": "Peiyan Li", "status": "claimed_verified", "statusLastChangedAt": "2026-07-20T16:06:02.904Z", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6dee", "name": "Yingyan Li", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6def", "name": "Futeng Liu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6df0", "name": "Wanli Peng", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6df1", "name": "Optimus Qin", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6df2", "name": "Yifei Su", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6df3", "name": "Nan Sun", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6df4", "name": "Qiao Sun", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6df5", "name": "Runze Suo", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6df6", "name": "Heyun Wang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6df7", "name": "Yunhong Wang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6df8", "name": "Rujie Wu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6df9", "name": "Caoyu Xia", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6dfa", "name": "Lina Zhang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6dfb", "name": "Jack Zhao", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6dfc", "name": "Guoliang Chen", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6dfd", "name": "Wenlong Chen", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6dfe", "name": "Xinze He", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6dff", "name": "Bin Li", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6e00", "name": "Qing Li", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6e01", "name": "Zhuorong Li", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6e02", "name": "Heng Qu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6e03", "name": "Wenxuan Song", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6e04", "name": "Diyun Xiang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6e05", "name": "Yifan Xie", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6e06", "name": "Peiran Xu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6e07", "name": "Hangjun Ye", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6e08", "name": "Wen Ye", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6e09", "name": "Han Zhao", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6e0a", "name": "Quanyun Zhou", "hidden": false}], "mediaUrls": ["https://cdn-uploads.huggingface.co/production/uploads/670bd33ec9c7e01d3dbaf59d/WMsV90grYxbmZgQDMBn8a.mp4"], "publishedAt": "2026-07-16T00:00:00.000Z", "submittedOnDailyAt": "2026-07-20T00:00:00.000Z", "title": "Xiaomi-Robotics-1: Scaling Vision-Language-Action Models with over 100K Hours of Real-World Trajectories", "submittedOnDailyBy": {"_id": "670bd33ec9c7e01d3dbaf59d", "avatarUrl": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/noauth/PCL5O0f3DXjKrc_EvdAgb.png", "isPro": false, "fullname": "yewen", "user": "YeWen27", "type": "user", "name": "YeWen27"}, "summary": "We present Xiaomi-Robotics-1, a foundational vision-language-action (VLA) model capable of (1) following diverse language instructions to perform a wide range of mobile manipulation tasks in unseen environments out-of-the-box, and (2) efficiently adapting to novel downstream tasks with minimal fine-tuning data. We propose a two-stage training recipe consisting of pre-training and post-training. During pre-training, we imbue the model with broad and generalizable action-generation capabilities by training on over 100k hours of real-world manipulation trajectories collected via UMI devices. Crucially, we develop a scalable auto-labeling pipeline that annotates trajectory clips with natural languages describing scene state transitions, providing rich and precise conditioning for action learning. During post-training, we aim to align these capabilities with robot embodiments and imperative instructions that humans naturally use to prompt robots. Extensive experiments demonstrate strong scaling behavior. Xiaomi-Robotics-1 consistently improves with increased data scales and model sizes during pre-training. This scaling behavior directly transfers to post-training, where a stronger pre-training model yields better out-of-the-box real-robot performance in unseen environments. Furthermore, Xiaomi-Robotics-1 serves as a strong robot foundation policy that can be efficiently fine-tuned on complex, dexterous tasks with high data efficiency. Across multiple simulation benchmarks, Xiaomi-Robotics-1 outperforms state-of-the-art methods. Notably, it establishes a new state-of-the-art with a 57.6% success rate on RoboCasa365, surpassing the previous best of 46.6%. Furthermore, it achieves an average score of 20.07 on RoboDojo, significantly outperforming the prior state-of-the-art (13.07). Code and model checkpoints will be released. Project page: https://robotics.xiaomi.com/xiaomi-robotics-1.html", "upvotes": 54, "discussionId": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6e0b", "projectPage": "https://robotics.xiaomi.com/xiaomi-robotics-1.html", "githubRepo": "https://github.com/XiaomiRobotics/Xiaomi-Robotics-1", "githubRepoAddedBy": "user", "githubStars": 143, "organization": {"_id": "697ad5f82057bf915ef24446", "name": "XiaomiRobotics", "fullname": "Xiaomi Robotics", "avatar": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/697ad78bb8e83c3ded37b2c7/gox0VlsrikZeJ_10vxe0A.png"}, "summary_zh": "<ul>\n    <li>\u5c0f\u7c73\u673a\u5668\u4eba1\u662f\u4e00\u4e2a\u57fa\u7840\u7684\u89c6\u89c9-\u8bed\u8a00-\u52a8\u4f5c\u6a21\u578b\uff0c\u80fd\u591f\u6839\u636e\u8bed\u8a00\u6307\u4ee4\u5728\u672a\u77e5\u73af\u5883\u4e2d\u6267\u884c\u591a\u79cd\u79fb\u52a8\u64cd\u4f5c\u4efb\u52a1\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u6a21\u578b\u7ecf\u8fc7\u4e24\u9636\u6bb5\u8bad\u7ec3\uff1a\u9884\u8bad\u7ec3\u548c\u540e\u8bad\u7ec3\uff0c\u9884\u8bad\u7ec3\u65f6\u4f7f\u7528\u8d85\u8fc710\u4e07\u5c0f\u65f6\u7684\u771f\u5b9e\u64cd\u4f5c\u8f68\u8ff9\u6570\u636e\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u5f00\u53d1\u4e86\u4e00\u4e2a\u53ef\u6269\u5c55\u7684\u81ea\u52a8\u6807\u6ce8\u6d41\u7a0b\uff0c\u7528\u81ea\u7136\u8bed\u8a00\u4e3a\u64cd\u4f5c\u8f68\u8ff9\u7247\u6bb5\u6ce8\u91ca\uff0c\u5e2e\u52a9\u6a21\u578b\u5b66\u4e60\u52a8\u4f5c\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u6a21\u578b\u5728\u9884\u8bad\u7ec3\u548c\u540e\u8bad\u7ec3\u4e2d\u90fd\u8868\u73b0\u51fa\u826f\u597d\u7684\u6269\u5c55\u6027\uff0c\u6570\u636e\u91cf\u548c\u6a21\u578b\u89c4\u6a21\u589e\u52a0\u65f6\u6027\u80fd\u6301\u7eed\u63d0\u5347\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u5728\u591a\u4e2a\u6a21\u62df\u57fa\u51c6\u6d4b\u8bd5\u4e2d\uff0c\u5c0f\u7c73\u673a\u5668\u4eba1\u7684\u6210\u529f\u7387\u548c\u5f97\u5206\u90fd\u8d85\u8fc7\u4e86\u73b0\u6709\u6700\u4f73\u6c34\u5e73\uff0c\u5c55\u793a\u4e86\u5176\u9ad8\u6548\u7684\u5fae\u8c03\u80fd\u529b\u3002</li>\n</ul>", "summary_simple": "<ul>\n    <li>Xiaomi-Robotics-1 is a new model that helps robots understand and follow language instructions for various tasks in new environments without needing much setup.</li>\n    <li>The model is trained in two stages: first, it learns general actions from a large amount of real-world data, and then it fine-tunes to work better with human-like instructions.</li>\n    <li>It uses an innovative system to label action data with natural language descriptions, improving how robots learn actions.</li>\n    <li>Tests show that the model performs better as it is trained with more data and larger sizes, leading to improved performance in real-world robot tasks.</li>\n    <li>Xiaomi-Robotics-1 sets new records for success rates on specific robot task benchmarks, outperforming previous models.</li>\n</ul>"}, "publishedAt": "2026-07-15T20:00:00.000Z", "title": "Xiaomi-Robotics-1: Scaling Vision-Language-Action Models with over 100K Hours of Real-World Trajectories", "summary": "We present Xiaomi-Robotics-1, a foundational vision-language-action (VLA) model capable of (1) following diverse language instructions to perform a wide range of mobile manipulation tasks in unseen environments out-of-the-box, and (2) efficiently adapting to novel downstream tasks with minimal fine-tuning data. We propose a two-stage training recipe consisting of pre-training and post-training. During pre-training, we imbue the model with broad and generalizable action-generation capabilities by training on over 100k hours of real-world manipulation trajectories collected via UMI devices. Crucially, we develop a scalable auto-labeling pipeline that annotates trajectory clips with natural languages describing scene state transitions, providing rich and precise conditioning for action learning. During post-training, we aim to align these capabilities with robot embodiments and imperative instructions that humans naturally use to prompt robots. Extensive experiments demonstrate strong scaling behavior. Xiaomi-Robotics-1 consistently improves with increased data scales and model sizes during pre-training. This scaling behavior directly transfers to post-training, where a stronger pre-training model yields better out-of-the-box real-robot performance in unseen environments. Furthermore, Xiaomi-Robotics-1 serves as a strong robot foundation policy that can be efficiently fine-tuned on complex, dexterous tasks with high data efficiency. Across multiple simulation benchmarks, Xiaomi-Robotics-1 outperforms state-of-the-art methods. Notably, it establishes a new state-of-the-art with a 57.6% success rate on RoboCasa365, surpassing the previous best of 46.6%. Furthermore, it achieves an average score of 20.07 on RoboDojo, significantly outperforming the prior state-of-the-art (13.07). Code and model checkpoints will be released. Project page: https://robotics.xiaomi.com/xiaomi-robotics-1.html", "mediaUrls": ["https://cdn-uploads.huggingface.co/production/uploads/670bd33ec9c7e01d3dbaf59d/WMsV90grYxbmZgQDMBn8a.mp4"], "thumbnail": "https://cdn-thumbnails.huggingface.co/social-thumbnails/papers/2607.15330.png", "numComments": 1, "submittedBy": {"_id": "670bd33ec9c7e01d3dbaf59d", "avatarUrl": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/noauth/PCL5O0f3DXjKrc_EvdAgb.png", "fullname": "yewen", "name": "YeWen27", "type": "user", "isPro": false, "isHf": false, "isHfAdmin": false, "isMod": false, "isUserFollowing": false}, "organization": {"_id": "697ad5f82057bf915ef24446", "name": "XiaomiRobotics", "fullname": "Xiaomi Robotics", "avatar": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/697ad78bb8e83c3ded37b2c7/gox0VlsrikZeJ_10vxe0A.png"}, "isAuthorParticipating": false}, {"paper": {"id": "2607.14530", "authors": [{"_id": "6a5d82836a69ce099f4d6d69", "name": "Xiangdong Zhang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d82836a69ce099f4d6d6a", "name": "Xiaohan Qin", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d82836a69ce099f4d6d6b", "name": "Sunan Zou", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d82836a69ce099f4d6d6c", "name": "Tuo Dai", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d82836a69ce099f4d6d6d", "name": "Xiaoming Shi", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d82836a69ce099f4d6d6e", "name": "Huaijin Wu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d82836a69ce099f4d6d6f", "name": "Yebin Yang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d82836a69ce099f4d6d70", "name": "Zhuo Xia", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d82836a69ce099f4d6d71", "name": "Shaofeng Zhang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d82836a69ce099f4d6d72", "name": "Lin Yao", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d82836a69ce099f4d6d73", "name": "Yuliang Liu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d82836a69ce099f4d6d74", "name": "Yu Cheng", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d82836a69ce099f4d6d75", "name": "Junchi Yan", "hidden": false}], "publishedAt": "2026-07-16T00:00:00.000Z", "submittedOnDailyAt": "2026-07-20T00:00:00.000Z", "title": "xHC: Expanded Hyper-Connections", "submittedOnDailyBy": {"_id": "656d8d4b1f8d9b618de91369", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/884dba9e56936241034b179d11a513b9.svg", "isPro": false, "fullname": "Xiangdong Zhang", "user": "aHapBean", "type": "user", "name": "aHapBean"}, "summary": "Hyper-Connections (HC) expand the residual stream of Transformers into N parallel streams, providing a form of memory scaling beyond model width and depth. Manifold-Constrained HC (mHC) stabilizes this formulation at scale. The large gains from N{=}1 to N{=}4 suggest residual-stream expansion as a promising scaling axis. However, existing HC-family methods typically stop at N{=}4. Our experiments reveal why: scaling mHC beyond this point yields diminishing performance gains and rapidly increasing training cost. We attribute this limitation to two bottlenecks: insufficient write-back information for an expanding number of streams and residual-mixing generation whose cost scales cubically with N. To address both bottlenecks, we propose xHC (Expanded Hyper-Connections), the first HC-family method to achieve meaningful expansion beyond N{=}4. xHC combines temporal feature augmentation for richer write-back with a sparse residual-stream architecture that updates only k=4 of the N=16 streams while retaining dense access to the full residual state. Across 18B and 28B MoE models, xHC delivers strong and consistent downstream improvements. On an 18B MoE model, xHC improves the average downstream score by 4.0 points over mHC, while adding only modest training FLOPs over the vanilla baseline. Scaling-law experiments show that the vanilla and mHC require 1.50times and 1.19times the compute of xHC, respectively, to reach the same loss. Practical large-N training also requires controlling memory traffic from the expanded residual state. We therefore introduce xHC-Flash, which reduces the per-sublayer memory traffic from 73.5C to 40C, comparable to the 34C required by mHC at N{=}4, while retaining the gains of full xHC. Together, xHC and xHC-Flash make large-N residual-stream expansion effective and practical for LLM pre-training.", "upvotes": 47, "discussionId": "6a5d82836a69ce099f4d6d76", "githubRepo": "https://github.com/aHapBean/xHC", "githubRepoAddedBy": "user", "githubStars": 38, "organization": {"_id": "68246a0a98117c02df67a547", "name": "rednote-hilab", "fullname": "rednote-hilab", "avatar": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/6807a1d6504547b3554b9c73/WgnnQDsz7FqnyTtv8mmRO.png"}, "summary_zh": "<ul>\n    <li>\u8d85\u8fde\u63a5\uff08HC\uff09\u5c06Transformer\u7684\u6b8b\u5dee\u6d41\u6269\u5c55\u4e3aN\u4e2a\u5e76\u884c\u6d41\uff0c\u63d0\u4f9b\u4e86\u4e00\u79cd\u8d85\u8d8a\u6a21\u578b\u5bbd\u5ea6\u548c\u6df1\u5ea6\u7684\u8bb0\u5fc6\u6269\u5c55\u65b9\u5f0f\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u6211\u4eec\u63d0\u51fa\u7684mHC\u65b9\u6cd5\u5728\u5927\u89c4\u6a21\u4e0b\u7a33\u5b9a\u4e86\u8fd9\u79cd\u6269\u5c55\uff0c\u4f46\u901a\u5e38\u53ea\u6269\u5c55\u5230N=4\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u8fdb\u4e00\u6b65\u6269\u5c55mHC\u4f1a\u5bfc\u81f4\u6027\u80fd\u63d0\u5347\u51cf\u5c11\u548c\u8bad\u7ec3\u6210\u672c\u8fc5\u901f\u589e\u52a0\uff0c\u4e3b\u8981\u662f\u7531\u4e8e\u4fe1\u606f\u56de\u5199\u4e0d\u8db3\u548c\u6b8b\u5dee\u6df7\u5408\u751f\u6210\u7684\u6210\u672c\u968fN\u7acb\u65b9\u589e\u957f\u3002</li>\n    <li>xHC\uff08\u6269\u5c55\u8d85\u8fde\u63a5\uff09\u662f\u7b2c\u4e00\u4e2a\u80fd\u6709\u6548\u6269\u5c55\u5230N>4\u7684HC\u65b9\u6cd5\uff0c\u901a\u8fc7\u4e30\u5bcc\u7684\u65f6\u95f4\u7279\u5f81\u589e\u5f3a\u548c\u7a00\u758f\u7684\u6b8b\u5dee\u6d41\u67b6\u6784\u6765\u89e3\u51b3\u8fd9\u4e9b\u74f6\u9888\u3002</li>\n    <li>xHC\u548c\u5176\u53d8\u4f53xHC-Flash\u4f7f\u5f97\u5927\u89c4\u6a21\u6b8b\u5dee\u6d41\u6269\u5c55\u5728\u5927\u578b\u8bed\u8a00\u6a21\u578b\u9884\u8bad\u7ec3\u4e2d\u66f4\u6709\u6548\u548c\u5b9e\u7528\u3002</li>\n</ul>", "summary_simple": "<ul>\n    <li>Hyper-Connections (HC) improve the memory capacity of Transformers by splitting their residual stream into multiple parallel streams.</li>\n    <li>Manifold-Constrained HC (mHC) helps stabilize this method but usually only scales up to 4 streams, leading to limited performance gains and higher training costs beyond that.</li>\n    <li>Two main issues hinder further scaling: not enough information for more streams and the increasing cost of mixing residuals as more streams are added.</li>\n    <li>xHC (Expanded Hyper-Connections) addresses these problems by using better feature augmentation and a sparse architecture that updates fewer streams, resulting in improved performance.</li>\n    <li>xHC and its optimized version, xHC-Flash, effectively allow for larger-scale training while managing memory use, showing significant improvements in model performance without excessive computational costs.</li>\n</ul>"}, "publishedAt": "2026-07-15T20:00:00.000Z", "title": "xHC: Expanded Hyper-Connections", "summary": "Hyper-Connections (HC) expand the residual stream of Transformers into N parallel streams, providing a form of memory scaling beyond model width and depth. Manifold-Constrained HC (mHC) stabilizes this formulation at scale. The large gains from N{=}1 to N{=}4 suggest residual-stream expansion as a promising scaling axis. However, existing HC-family methods typically stop at N{=}4. Our experiments reveal why: scaling mHC beyond this point yields diminishing performance gains and rapidly increasing training cost. We attribute this limitation to two bottlenecks: insufficient write-back information for an expanding number of streams and residual-mixing generation whose cost scales cubically with N. To address both bottlenecks, we propose xHC (Expanded Hyper-Connections), the first HC-family method to achieve meaningful expansion beyond N{=}4. xHC combines temporal feature augmentation for richer write-back with a sparse residual-stream architecture that updates only k=4 of the N=16 streams while retaining dense access to the full residual state. Across 18B and 28B MoE models, xHC delivers strong and consistent downstream improvements. On an 18B MoE model, xHC improves the average downstream score by 4.0 points over mHC, while adding only modest training FLOPs over the vanilla baseline. Scaling-law experiments show that the vanilla and mHC require 1.50times and 1.19times the compute of xHC, respectively, to reach the same loss. Practical large-N training also requires controlling memory traffic from the expanded residual state. We therefore introduce xHC-Flash, which reduces the per-sublayer memory traffic from 73.5C to 40C, comparable to the 34C required by mHC at N{=}4, while retaining the gains of full xHC. Together, xHC and xHC-Flash make large-N residual-stream expansion effective and practical for LLM pre-training.", "thumbnail": "https://cdn-thumbnails.huggingface.co/social-thumbnails/papers/2607.14530.png", "numComments": 1, "submittedBy": {"_id": "656d8d4b1f8d9b618de91369", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/884dba9e56936241034b179d11a513b9.svg", "fullname": "Xiangdong Zhang", "name": "aHapBean", "type": "user", "isPro": false, "isHf": false, "isHfAdmin": false, "isMod": false, "followerCount": 1, "isUserFollowing": false}, "organization": {"_id": "68246a0a98117c02df67a547", "name": "rednote-hilab", "fullname": "rednote-hilab", "avatar": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/6807a1d6504547b3554b9c73/WgnnQDsz7FqnyTtv8mmRO.png"}, "isAuthorParticipating": false}, {"paper": {"id": "2607.15314", "authors": [{"_id": "6a5d83ee6a69ce099f4d6d91", "name": "actAVA AI", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d83ee6a69ce099f4d6d93", "name": "Haolin Chen", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d83ee6a69ce099f4d6d94", "name": "Leon Qi", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d83ee6a69ce099f4d6d95", "name": "Steve Brown", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d83ee6a69ce099f4d6d96", "name": "Deon Metelski", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d83ee6a69ce099f4d6d97", "name": "Tao Xia", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d83ee6a69ce099f4d6d98", "name": "Joonyul Lee", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d83ee6a69ce099f4d6d99", "name": "Qixuan Wang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d83ee6a69ce099f4d6d9a", "name": "Kevin Riley", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d83ee6a69ce099f4d6d9b", "name": "Frank Wang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d83ee6a69ce099f4d6d9c", "user": {"_id": "632cdea254e2c512c8f95b12", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/a6d06cdd75861ae7d589f1343d81a5c5.svg", "isPro": false, "fullname": "Weiran Yao", "user": "weirayao", "type": "user", "name": "weirayao"}, "name": "Weiran Yao", "status": "claimed_verified", "statusLastChangedAt": "2026-07-20T16:06:02.233Z", "hidden": false}], "publishedAt": "2026-07-15T00:00:00.000Z", "submittedOnDailyAt": "2026-07-20T00:00:00.000Z", "title": "Cura 1T: Specialized Model for Agentic Healthcare", "submittedOnDailyBy": {"_id": "6039478ab3ecf716b1a5fd4d", "avatarUrl": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/6039478ab3ecf716b1a5fd4d/_Thy4E7taiSYBLKxEKJbT.jpeg", "isPro": true, "fullname": "taesiri", "user": "taesiri", "type": "user", "name": "taesiri"}, "summary": "Healthcare spans high-stakes communication, expert reasoning, and workflow execution, yet specialized LLMs that cover these use cases together remain limited. A healthcare model must handle patient consultation, clinical reasoning over text and images, interactive diagnosis, and electronic health record (EHR) tool use. These capabilities fail in different ways, and a narrow update for one task can degrade another. We present Cura 1T, a healthcare-specialized LLM trained through a human-gated self-evolution loop. In each evolution round, a training agent plans a target capability, trains the model, evaluates benchmark trajectories, and refines the data mixture from observed failures. This data-centered loop improves the model through targeted synthetic and curated examples rather than a single generic medical-data update. Across the healthcare evaluation suite, Cura 1T ranks at or near the top among frontier baselines, while remaining competitive on out-of-domain reasoning and agentic benchmarks.", "upvotes": 43, "discussionId": "6a5d83ee6a69ce099f4d6d9d", "projectPage": "https://actava.ai/cura", "githubRepo": "https://github.com/actava-ai/Cura", "githubRepoAddedBy": "user", "githubStars": 17, "summary_zh": "<ul>\n    <li>\u533b\u7597\u9886\u57df\u7684\u6c9f\u901a\u3001\u63a8\u7406\u548c\u5de5\u4f5c\u6d41\u7a0b\u6267\u884c\u975e\u5e38\u91cd\u8981\uff0c\u4f46\u4e13\u95e8\u7684\u8bed\u8a00\u6a21\u578b\uff08LLM\uff09\u4ecd\u7136\u6709\u9650\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u533b\u7597\u6a21\u578b\u9700\u8981\u5904\u7406\u60a3\u8005\u54a8\u8be2\u3001\u4e34\u5e8a\u63a8\u7406\u3001\u4e92\u52a8\u8bca\u65ad\u548c\u7535\u5b50\u5065\u5eb7\u8bb0\u5f55\u7b49\u4efb\u52a1\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u9488\u5bf9\u4e00\u4e2a\u4efb\u52a1\u7684\u66f4\u65b0\u53ef\u80fd\u4f1a\u5f71\u54cd\u5176\u4ed6\u4efb\u52a1\u7684\u8868\u73b0\u3002</li>\n    <li>Cura 1T\u662f\u4e00\u79cd\u4e13\u4e3a\u533b\u7597\u8bbe\u8ba1\u7684LLM\uff0c\u901a\u8fc7\u4eba\u7c7b\u5f15\u5bfc\u7684\u81ea\u6211\u8fdb\u5316\u5faa\u73af\u8fdb\u884c\u8bad\u7ec3\u3002</li>\n    <li>Cura 1T\u5728\u533b\u7597\u8bc4\u4f30\u4e2d\u8868\u73b0\u4f18\u5f02\uff0c\u5e76\u5728\u4e0d\u540c\u9886\u57df\u7684\u63a8\u7406\u548c\u4ee3\u7406\u57fa\u51c6\u4e0a\u4e5f\u4fdd\u6301\u7ade\u4e89\u529b\u3002</li>\n</ul>", "summary_simple": "<ul>\n    <li>Cura 1T is a specialized language model for healthcare that combines patient consultation, clinical reasoning, diagnosis, and EHR tool use.</li>\n    <li>Current healthcare models struggle with multiple tasks, and improving one area can negatively impact others.</li>\n    <li>The model improves through a unique training process that focuses on specific capabilities and learns from past mistakes.</li>\n    <li>Cura 1T uses targeted examples instead of just general medical data for better training results.</li>\n    <li>In evaluations, Cura 1T performs at or near the top compared to other leading models and is effective in various reasoning tasks.</li>\n</ul>"}, "publishedAt": "2026-07-14T20:00:00.000Z", "title": "Cura 1T: Specialized Model for Agentic Healthcare", "summary": "Healthcare spans high-stakes communication, expert reasoning, and workflow execution, yet specialized LLMs that cover these use cases together remain limited. A healthcare model must handle patient consultation, clinical reasoning over text and images, interactive diagnosis, and electronic health record (EHR) tool use. These capabilities fail in different ways, and a narrow update for one task can degrade another. We present Cura 1T, a healthcare-specialized LLM trained through a human-gated self-evolution loop. In each evolution round, a training agent plans a target capability, trains the model, evaluates benchmark trajectories, and refines the data mixture from observed failures. This data-centered loop improves the model through targeted synthetic and curated examples rather than a single generic medical-data update. Across the healthcare evaluation suite, Cura 1T ranks at or near the top among frontier baselines, while remaining competitive on out-of-domain reasoning and agentic benchmarks.", "thumbnail": "https://cdn-thumbnails.huggingface.co/social-thumbnails/papers/2607.15314.png", "numComments": 4, "submittedBy": {"_id": "6039478ab3ecf716b1a5fd4d", "avatarUrl": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/6039478ab3ecf716b1a5fd4d/_Thy4E7taiSYBLKxEKJbT.jpeg", "fullname": "taesiri", "name": "taesiri", "type": "user", "isPro": true, "isHf": false, "isHfAdmin": false, "isMod": false, "followerCount": 338, "isUserFollowing": false}, "isAuthorParticipating": true}, {"paper": {"id": "2607.15161", "authors": [{"_id": "6a5d456c6a69ce099f4d6c8d", "name": "Byeongho Heo", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d456c6a69ce099f4d6c8e", "name": "Jaehui Hwang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d456c6a69ce099f4d6c8f", "name": "Sangdoo Yun", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d456c6a69ce099f4d6c90", "name": "Dongyoon Han", "hidden": false}], "publishedAt": "2026-07-16T00:00:00.000Z", "submittedOnDailyAt": "2026-07-20T00:00:00.000Z", "title": "On-Policy Delta Distillation", "submittedOnDailyBy": {"_id": "64b9feed96676e40d0fa89a7", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/2154a6ceb87677ad2c9d9620de5b18ec.svg", "isPro": false, "fullname": "Byeongho Heo", "user": "bhheo", "type": "user", "name": "bhheo"}, "summary": "On-policy distillation is an alternative post-training method in reinforcement learning that alleviates the constraints imposed by reward models by providing token-level supervision from a teacher model. Although on-policy distillation has been studied and applied across various settings, its fundamental design remains underexplored. In this paper, we introduce a new distillation reward, termed the delta signal, instead of directly imitating the teacher's output distribution. The delta signal is defined as the difference between the teacher model and its base model prior to instruction tuning for reasoning capability. It therefore captures the changes induced by reasoning tuning and provides a more direct signal for transferring reasoning capabilities. Using extensive empirical evidence, we show that the delta signal substantially improves on-policy distillation and refer to the new distillation method as On-Policy Delta Distillation (OPD^2). Experiments across mathematics, science, and code-reasoning benchmarks demonstrate that OPD^2 consistently outperforms conventional on-policy distillation, enabling reasoning LLMs to achieve strong performance with only a short post-training period. Code will be available at https://github.com/naver-ai/opd2", "upvotes": 27, "discussionId": "6a5d456c6a69ce099f4d6c91", "githubRepo": "https://github.com/naver-ai/opd2", "githubRepoAddedBy": "user", "githubStars": 5, "organization": {"_id": "64ffe603efd273eec7768bde", "name": "naver-ai", "fullname": "NAVER AI Lab", "avatar": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/64ff1755b75685dd7a46e146/Zj2bxgq31oSqwVrw16IE_.png"}, "summary_zh": "<ul>\n    <li>\u63d0\u51fa\u4e86\u4e00\u79cd\u65b0\u7684\u5f3a\u5316\u5b66\u4e60\u65b9\u6cd5\uff0c\u79f0\u4e3a\u201c\u5728\u7ebf delta \u84b8\u998f\u201d\uff08On-Policy Delta Distillation\uff0c\u7b80\u79f0 OPD\u00b2\uff09\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u8be5\u65b9\u6cd5\u901a\u8fc7\u5f15\u5165\u201cdelta \u4fe1\u53f7\u201d\u6765\u6539\u5584\u4f20\u7edf\u7684\u84b8\u998f\u8fc7\u7a0b\uff0c\u8be5\u4fe1\u53f7\u53cd\u6620\u6559\u5e08\u6a21\u578b\u4e0e\u57fa\u672c\u6a21\u578b\u4e4b\u95f4\u7684\u5dee\u5f02\u3002</li>\n    <li>delta \u4fe1\u53f7\u53ef\u4ee5\u66f4\u76f4\u63a5\u5730\u4f20\u9012\u63a8\u7406\u80fd\u529b\uff0c\u800c\u4e0d\u662f\u5355\u7eaf\u6a21\u4eff\u6559\u5e08\u6a21\u578b\u7684\u8f93\u51fa\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u5b9e\u9a8c\u7ed3\u679c\u8868\u660e\uff0cOPD\u00b2 \u5728\u6570\u5b66\u3001\u79d1\u5b66\u548c\u4ee3\u7801\u63a8\u7406\u57fa\u51c6\u6d4b\u8bd5\u4e2d\u8868\u73b0\u4f18\u4e8e\u4f20\u7edf\u7684\u5728\u7ebf\u84b8\u998f\u65b9\u6cd5\u3002</li>\n    <li>OPD\u00b2 \u4f7f\u5f97\u63a8\u7406\u5927\u8bed\u8a00\u6a21\u578b\u5728\u77ed\u65f6\u95f4\u5185\u5b9e\u73b0\u5f3a\u5927\u6027\u80fd\uff0c\u76f8\u5173\u4ee3\u7801\u5c06\u516c\u5f00\u53d1\u5e03\u3002</li>\n</ul>", "summary_simple": "<ul>\n    <li>On-policy distillation is a method in reinforcement learning that improves learning by using guidance from a teacher model.</li>\n    <li>This paper introduces a new approach called the delta signal, which focuses on the differences between a teacher model and its base model before it learns reasoning skills.</li>\n    <li>The delta signal helps transfer reasoning abilities more effectively than just imitating the teacher's output.</li>\n    <li>The new method, called On-Policy Delta Distillation (OPD\u00b2), shows significant improvements in performance across various benchmarks in math, science, and code reasoning.</li>\n    <li>OPD\u00b2 allows reasoning models to perform well even after a short training period.</li>\n</ul>"}, "publishedAt": "2026-07-15T20:00:00.000Z", "title": "On-Policy Delta Distillation", "summary": "On-policy distillation is an alternative post-training method in reinforcement learning that alleviates the constraints imposed by reward models by providing token-level supervision from a teacher model. Although on-policy distillation has been studied and applied across various settings, its fundamental design remains underexplored. In this paper, we introduce a new distillation reward, termed the delta signal, instead of directly imitating the teacher's output distribution. The delta signal is defined as the difference between the teacher model and its base model prior to instruction tuning for reasoning capability. It therefore captures the changes induced by reasoning tuning and provides a more direct signal for transferring reasoning capabilities. Using extensive empirical evidence, we show that the delta signal substantially improves on-policy distillation and refer to the new distillation method as On-Policy Delta Distillation (OPD^2). Experiments across mathematics, science, and code-reasoning benchmarks demonstrate that OPD^2 consistently outperforms conventional on-policy distillation, enabling reasoning LLMs to achieve strong performance with only a short post-training period. Code will be available at https://github.com/naver-ai/opd2", "thumbnail": "https://cdn-thumbnails.huggingface.co/social-thumbnails/papers/2607.15161.png", "numComments": 1, "submittedBy": {"_id": "64b9feed96676e40d0fa89a7", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/2154a6ceb87677ad2c9d9620de5b18ec.svg", "fullname": "Byeongho Heo", "name": "bhheo", "type": "user", "isPro": false, "isHf": false, "isHfAdmin": false, "isMod": false, "followerCount": 8, "isUserFollowing": false}, "organization": {"_id": "64ffe603efd273eec7768bde", "name": "naver-ai", "fullname": "NAVER AI Lab", "avatar": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/64ff1755b75685dd7a46e146/Zj2bxgq31oSqwVrw16IE_.png"}, "isAuthorParticipating": false}, {"paper": {"id": "2607.15591", "authors": [{"_id": "6a5d80c56a69ce099f4d6d41", "name": "Bowen Zheng", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d80c56a69ce099f4d6d42", "name": "Chao Yi", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d80c56a69ce099f4d6d43", "name": "Dian Chen", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d80c56a69ce099f4d6d44", "name": "Gaoyang Guo", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d80c56a69ce099f4d6d45", "name": "Han Zhu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d80c56a69ce099f4d6d46", "user": {"_id": "65acfb3a14e6582c30b4ce76", "avatarUrl": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/65acfb3a14e6582c30b4ce76/RhEhePggBtyM0RIIqXQen.jpeg", "isPro": false, "fullname": "TangJiakai", "user": "TangJiakai5704", "type": "user", "name": "TangJiakai5704"}, "name": "Jiakai Tang", "status": "claimed_verified", "statusLastChangedAt": "2026-07-20T16:37:54.941Z", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d80c56a69ce099f4d6d47", "name": "Jian Wu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d80c56a69ce099f4d6d48", "name": "Mao Zhang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d80c56a69ce099f4d6d49", "name": "Wen Chen", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d80c56a69ce099f4d6d4a", "name": "Yifan Lu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d80c56a69ce099f4d6d4b", "name": "Yujie Luo", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d80c56a69ce099f4d6d4c", "name": "Yuning Jiang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d80c56a69ce099f4d6d4d", "name": "Zhujin Gao", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d80c56a69ce099f4d6d4e", "name": "Bo Zheng", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d80c56a69ce099f4d6d4f", "name": "Dixuan Wang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d80c56a69ce099f4d6d50", "name": "Hao Fang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d80c56a69ce099f4d6d51", "name": "Jiancai Liu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d80c56a69ce099f4d6d52", "name": "Jing Yu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d80c56a69ce099f4d6d53", "name": "Ke Chen", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d80c56a69ce099f4d6d54", "name": "Kewei Zhu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d80c56a69ce099f4d6d55", "name": "Mingke Xu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d80c56a69ce099f4d6d56", "name": "Wenjun Yang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d80c56a69ce099f4d6d57", "name": "Xunke Xi", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d80c56a69ce099f4d6d58", "name": "Zile Zhou", "hidden": false}], "publishedAt": "2026-07-17T00:00:00.000Z", "submittedOnDailyAt": "2026-07-20T00:00:00.000Z", "title": "RecGPT-V3 Technical Report", "submittedOnDailyBy": {"_id": "65acfb3a14e6582c30b4ce76", "avatarUrl": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/65acfb3a14e6582c30b4ce76/RhEhePggBtyM0RIIqXQen.jpeg", "isPro": false, "fullname": "TangJiakai", "user": "TangJiakai5704", "type": "user", "name": "TangJiakai5704"}, "summary": "Large language models (LLMs) are transforming recommender systems from matching co-occurrence patterns in historical behavior toward reasoning about the intent that drives it. RecGPT-V1 pioneered this paradigm on Taobao by centering user understanding, and RecGPT-V2 scaled it via coordinated multi-agent reasoning; both are deployed in production with consistent gains in user experience and commercial outcomes. However, operating RecGPT at scale reveals three challenges: (1) stateless behavior modeling, where each request reprocesses full user history, wasting computation and discarding prior analysis; (2) a tag-to-item information bottleneck, where natural-language tags form a lossy channel between user understanding and item grounding; and (3) inefficient explicit reasoning, whose lengthy chain-of-thought incurs untenable latency and compute overhead.\n  We present RecGPT-V3, a stateful, hybrid-modal recommender that reasons over natural language for open-world knowledge and Semantic IDs (SIDs) for concrete item grounding. A Memory Hub maintains structured, continually evolving user memory that distills long-horizon behavior into condensed units, cutting user-modeling computation by 55.8%. A Hybrid-modal Foundation Model allows the LLM jointly reason over text tags and SIDs, opening a high-bandwidth channel into the item space. Latent Intent Reasoning internalizes verbose rationales into compact learnable latent tokens that remain decodable into readable explanations, lowering output token cost by 200x. Deployed in Taobao's \"Guess What You Like\" feed, RecGPT-V3 achieves consistent gains in large-scale online A/B tests: IPV +1.28%, CTR +1.00%, TC +1.97%, GMV +3.97%, while cutting end-to-end serving resource consumption by 52.4%.", "upvotes": 26, "discussionId": "6a5d80c56a69ce099f4d6d59", "summary_zh": "<ul>\n  <li>\u5927\u578b\u8bed\u8a00\u6a21\u578b\uff08LLMs\uff09\u6b63\u5728\u6539\u53d8\u63a8\u8350\u7cfb\u7edf\uff0c\u4fa7\u91cd\u4e8e\u7406\u89e3\u7528\u6237\u610f\u56fe\u3002</li>\n  <li>RecGPT-V1 \u548c RecGPT-V2 \u5728\u6dd8\u5b9d\u4e0a\u6210\u529f\u5b9e\u65bd\uff0c\u63d0\u5347\u4e86\u7528\u6237\u4f53\u9a8c\u548c\u5546\u4e1a\u6210\u679c\u3002</li>\n  <li>RecGPT \u5728\u5927\u89c4\u6a21\u8fd0\u884c\u4e2d\u9762\u4e34\u4e09\u4e2a\u6311\u6218\uff1a\u65e0\u72b6\u6001\u884c\u4e3a\u5efa\u6a21\u3001\u6807\u7b7e\u4e0e\u5546\u54c1\u4fe1\u606f\u74f6\u9888\uff0c\u4ee5\u53ca\u6548\u7387\u4f4e\u4e0b\u7684\u63a8\u7406\u3002</li>\n  <li>RecGPT-V3 \u91c7\u7528\u6709\u72b6\u6001\u7684\u6df7\u5408\u6a21\u5f0f\u63a8\u8350\uff0c\u5229\u7528\u7528\u6237\u8bb0\u5fc6\u548c\u8bed\u4e49ID\u63d0\u9ad8\u63a8\u8350\u51c6\u786e\u6027\u3002</li>\n  <li>RecGPT-V3 \u5728\u6dd8\u5b9d\u7684\u5e94\u7528\u4e2d\uff0c\u5728\u7ebf\u6d4b\u8bd5\u663e\u793a\u7528\u6237\u4e92\u52a8\u548c\u9500\u552e\u5747\u6709\u663e\u8457\u63d0\u5347\uff0c\u540c\u65f6\u51cf\u5c11\u4e86\u8d44\u6e90\u6d88\u8017\u3002</li>\n</ul>", "summary_simple": "<ul>\n    <li>Large language models are improving how recommender systems understand user intent instead of just looking at past behavior.</li>\n    <li>RecGPT-V1 and RecGPT-V2 were successful in enhancing user experience on Taobao but faced challenges when used at a larger scale.</li>\n    <li>Key challenges included inefficiencies in processing user history, issues with how user understanding connects to item recommendations, and slow reasoning processes.</li>\n    <li>RecGPT-V3 introduces a new system that efficiently uses user memory and combines text with structured data for better recommendations.</li>\n    <li>Testing on Taobao showed that RecGPT-V3 improved key performance metrics while significantly reducing resource use.</li>\n</ul>"}, "publishedAt": "2026-07-16T20:00:00.000Z", "title": "RecGPT-V3 Technical Report", "summary": "Large language models (LLMs) are transforming recommender systems from matching co-occurrence patterns in historical behavior toward reasoning about the intent that drives it. RecGPT-V1 pioneered this paradigm on Taobao by centering user understanding, and RecGPT-V2 scaled it via coordinated multi-agent reasoning; both are deployed in production with consistent gains in user experience and commercial outcomes. However, operating RecGPT at scale reveals three challenges: (1) stateless behavior modeling, where each request reprocesses full user history, wasting computation and discarding prior analysis; (2) a tag-to-item information bottleneck, where natural-language tags form a lossy channel between user understanding and item grounding; and (3) inefficient explicit reasoning, whose lengthy chain-of-thought incurs untenable latency and compute overhead.\n  We present RecGPT-V3, a stateful, hybrid-modal recommender that reasons over natural language for open-world knowledge and Semantic IDs (SIDs) for concrete item grounding. A Memory Hub maintains structured, continually evolving user memory that distills long-horizon behavior into condensed units, cutting user-modeling computation by 55.8%. A Hybrid-modal Foundation Model allows the LLM jointly reason over text tags and SIDs, opening a high-bandwidth channel into the item space. Latent Intent Reasoning internalizes verbose rationales into compact learnable latent tokens that remain decodable into readable explanations, lowering output token cost by 200x. Deployed in Taobao's \"Guess What You Like\" feed, RecGPT-V3 achieves consistent gains in large-scale online A/B tests: IPV +1.28%, CTR +1.00%, TC +1.97%, GMV +3.97%, while cutting end-to-end serving resource consumption by 52.4%.", "thumbnail": "https://cdn-thumbnails.huggingface.co/social-thumbnails/papers/2607.15591.png", "numComments": 1, "submittedBy": {"_id": "65acfb3a14e6582c30b4ce76", "avatarUrl": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/65acfb3a14e6582c30b4ce76/RhEhePggBtyM0RIIqXQen.jpeg", "fullname": "TangJiakai", "name": "TangJiakai5704", "type": "user", "isPro": false, "isHf": false, "isHfAdmin": false, "isMod": false, "followerCount": 2, "isUserFollowing": false}, "isAuthorParticipating": true}, {"paper": {"id": "2607.13196", "authors": [{"_id": "6a5d81626a69ce099f4d6d62", "name": "Suzhen Zhong", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d81626a69ce099f4d6d63", "user": {"_id": "66f6f7ed07eab7c704930030", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/ac6c817a857446306abe4cf600a252ac.svg", "isPro": false, "fullname": "Shayan Noei", "user": "Shadsg", "type": "user", "name": "Shadsg"}, "name": "Shayan Noei", "status": "claimed_verified", "statusLastChangedAt": "2026-07-20T16:06:00.916Z", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d81626a69ce099f4d6d64", "name": "Bram Adams", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d81626a69ce099f4d6d65", "name": "Ying Zou", "hidden": false}], "publishedAt": "2026-07-14T00:00:00.000Z", "submittedOnDailyAt": "2026-07-20T00:00:00.000Z", "title": "From Human-Centric to Agentic Code Review: The Impact of Different Generations of Generative AI Technology on Review Quality", "submittedOnDailyBy": {"_id": "65dd617096d71c27a19a28d4", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/8f599654d0e84b95cfb20a43e75e4bc9.svg", "isPro": false, "fullname": "Suzhen Zhong", "user": "Suzhen", "type": "user", "name": "Suzhen"}, "summary": "Code review helps maintain software quality before code integration, but it also imposes a substantial workload on human reviewers. As generative artificial intelligence becomes part of software development, code review is shifting from a primarily human review process toward AI-supported review processes in which large language model (LLM) reviewers and AI agent reviewers participate alongside human reviewers. However, we still lack empirical evidence on how this transition affects review efficiency and review quality. In this paper, we study 1.02 million reviewed pull requests from 207 GitHub projects that transition across three code review eras: human-centric review, LLM-assisted review, and agentic code review. We identify three AI reviewer adoption practices: Gradual AI Adoption, Rapid LLM Adoption, and Rapid AI Agent Adoption. We further model pull request review discussions as reviewer interaction sequences to characterize how human, LLM, and AI agent reviewers collaborate during the review process. Our results show that agent-involved collaboration patterns, especially reviews initiated by AI agents or involving multiple AI agents, are associated with faster review decisions under Gradual AI Adoption and Rapid AI Agent Adoption. However, these efficiency gains do not translate into better review quality. We also find that review activity and pull request type remain important across eras, while human-AI collaboration patterns become the strongest explanatory factor for review efficiency once LLM and AI agent reviewers participate. These findings provide empirical guidance for designing AI-supported code review processes that improve efficiency without weakening review quality.", "upvotes": 24, "discussionId": "6a5d81636a69ce099f4d6d66", "organization": {"_id": "64d0515fe13e7c2bc5c36613", "name": "QueensUniversity", "fullname": "Queen's University", "avatar": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ae3d2eb1d2c23b167ab251211dda79f2?d=retro&size=100"}, "summary_zh": "<ul>\n    <li>\u4ee3\u7801\u5ba1\u67e5\u5728\u4ee3\u7801\u6574\u5408\u524d\u4fdd\u6301\u8f6f\u4ef6\u8d28\u91cf\uff0c\u4f46\u5bf9\u4eba\u5de5\u5ba1\u67e5\u8005\u7684\u5de5\u4f5c\u91cf\u5f88\u5927\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u968f\u7740\u751f\u6210\u6027\u4eba\u5de5\u667a\u80fd\u7684\u5e94\u7528\uff0c\u4ee3\u7801\u5ba1\u67e5\u6b63\u4ece\u4e3b\u8981\u7531\u4eba\u5de5\u8fdb\u884c\u8f6c\u5411\u4eba\u673a\u534f\u4f5c\u7684\u5ba1\u67e5\u8fc7\u7a0b\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u672c\u6587\u7814\u7a76\u4e86207\u4e2aGitHub\u9879\u76ee\u4e2d102\u4e07\u6b21\u5ba1\u67e5\u8bf7\u6c42\uff0c\u5206\u6790\u4e86\u4e09\u79cd\u4ee3\u7801\u5ba1\u67e5\u65b9\u5f0f\uff1a\u4eba\u5de5\u5ba1\u67e5\u3001LLM\u8f85\u52a9\u5ba1\u67e5\u548cAI\u4ee3\u7406\u5ba1\u67e5\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u53d1\u73b0AI\u5ba1\u67e5\u8005\u7684\u53c2\u4e0e\u53ef\u4ee5\u52a0\u5feb\u5ba1\u67e5\u901f\u5ea6\uff0c\u4f46\u5e76\u672a\u63d0\u9ad8\u5ba1\u67e5\u8d28\u91cf\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u4eba\u7c7b\u4e0eAI\u7684\u534f\u4f5c\u6a21\u5f0f\u662f\u5f71\u54cd\u5ba1\u67e5\u6548\u7387\u7684\u5173\u952e\u56e0\u7d20\uff0c\u8bbe\u8ba1AI\u652f\u6301\u7684\u4ee3\u7801\u5ba1\u67e5\u6d41\u7a0b\u65f6\u9700\u517c\u987e\u6548\u7387\u4e0e\u8d28\u91cf\u3002</li>\n</ul>", "summary_simple": "<ul>\n    <li>Code reviews are important for software quality but can be a heavy workload for reviewers.</li>\n    <li>Generative AI is changing code reviews from mostly human reviews to ones that involve AI, including large language models (LLMs) and AI agents.</li>\n    <li>The study looks at 1.02 million pull requests from 207 GitHub projects to see how different types of AI involvement affect review efficiency and quality.</li>\n    <li>Three practices of AI adoption in code reviews were identified: Gradual AI Adoption, Rapid LLM Adoption, and Rapid AI Agent Adoption.</li>\n    <li>While AI involvement can speed up the review process, it does not necessarily improve the quality of the reviews; human-AI collaboration patterns are key for efficiency.</li>\n</ul>"}, "publishedAt": "2026-07-13T20:00:00.000Z", "title": "From Human-Centric to Agentic Code Review: The Impact of Different Generations of Generative AI Technology on Review Quality", "summary": "Code review helps maintain software quality before code integration, but it also imposes a substantial workload on human reviewers. As generative artificial intelligence becomes part of software development, code review is shifting from a primarily human review process toward AI-supported review processes in which large language model (LLM) reviewers and AI agent reviewers participate alongside human reviewers. However, we still lack empirical evidence on how this transition affects review efficiency and review quality. In this paper, we study 1.02 million reviewed pull requests from 207 GitHub projects that transition across three code review eras: human-centric review, LLM-assisted review, and agentic code review. We identify three AI reviewer adoption practices: Gradual AI Adoption, Rapid LLM Adoption, and Rapid AI Agent Adoption. We further model pull request review discussions as reviewer interaction sequences to characterize how human, LLM, and AI agent reviewers collaborate during the review process. Our results show that agent-involved collaboration patterns, especially reviews initiated by AI agents or involving multiple AI agents, are associated with faster review decisions under Gradual AI Adoption and Rapid AI Agent Adoption. However, these efficiency gains do not translate into better review quality. We also find that review activity and pull request type remain important across eras, while human-AI collaboration patterns become the strongest explanatory factor for review efficiency once LLM and AI agent reviewers participate. These findings provide empirical guidance for designing AI-supported code review processes that improve efficiency without weakening review quality.", "thumbnail": "https://cdn-thumbnails.huggingface.co/social-thumbnails/papers/2607.13196.png", "numComments": 1, "submittedBy": {"_id": "65dd617096d71c27a19a28d4", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/8f599654d0e84b95cfb20a43e75e4bc9.svg", "fullname": "Suzhen Zhong", "name": "Suzhen", "type": "user", "isPro": false, "isHf": false, "isHfAdmin": false, "isMod": false, "followerCount": 2, "isUserFollowing": false}, "organization": {"_id": "64d0515fe13e7c2bc5c36613", "name": "QueensUniversity", "fullname": "Queen's University", "avatar": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ae3d2eb1d2c23b167ab251211dda79f2?d=retro&size=100"}, "isAuthorParticipating": false}, {"paper": {"id": "2607.16097", "authors": [{"_id": "6a5d7a966a69ce099f4d6cfe", "user": {"_id": "638828cd26952adc66f1bdbd", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/0be4c4af8f3d1ed9529bc77839952dab.svg", "isPro": false, "fullname": "Evangeline Shen", "user": "Evangelinejy", "type": "user", "name": "Evangelinejy"}, "name": "Jingyan Shen", "status": "claimed_verified", "statusLastChangedAt": "2026-07-20T16:52:59.363Z", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d7a966a69ce099f4d6cff", "name": "Ang Li", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d7a966a69ce099f4d6d00", "name": "Salman Rahman", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d7a966a69ce099f4d6d01", "name": "Yifan Sun", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d7a966a69ce099f4d6d02", "name": "Micah Goldblum", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d7a966a69ce099f4d6d03", "name": "Matus Telgarsky", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d7a966a69ce099f4d6d04", "name": "Pavel Izmailov", "hidden": false}], "publishedAt": "2026-07-17T00:00:00.000Z", "submittedOnDailyAt": "2026-07-20T00:00:00.000Z", "title": "Understanding Reasoning from Pretraining to Post-Training", "submittedOnDailyBy": {"_id": "638828cd26952adc66f1bdbd", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/0be4c4af8f3d1ed9529bc77839952dab.svg", "isPro": false, "fullname": "Evangeline Shen", "user": "Evangelinejy", "type": "user", "name": "Evangelinejy"}, "summary": "Reinforcement learning (RL) has become central to improving large language models (LLMs) on complex reasoning tasks, yet RL post-training is largely studied in isolation from the pretraining that precedes it. As a result, two basic questions remain open: (1) how do pretraining choices (model size, data) shape the returns to RL compute, and (2) what does RL actually do to the model? These questions are difficult to study in the standard LLM setting: pretraining corpora are vast and uncontrolled, making it hard to attribute behaviors to pretraining versus RL, and systematic compute sweeps across both stages are prohibitively expensive. To address these challenges, we use chess as a controlled testbed for studying reasoning across the full pretraining-to-post-training pipeline. We follow the standard LLM training pipeline by pretraining language models from 5M to 1B parameters on human chess games, supervised fine-tuning on synthetic reasoning traces, and running RL on chess puzzles with verifiable rewards. Using this framework, we find that the post-RL performance at given RL compute level is well-predicted from the pretraining loss, and slope of the RL reward curves improves approximately linearly with the pretraining tokens. Beyond scaling, we find that RL does not simply sharpen the SFT policy: on easy puzzles it amplifies correct moves the SFT policy already preferred, while on hard puzzles it surfaces correct moves that were nearly absent under SFT. We further test whether our findings transfer beyond chess by training a 1B language model on math-domain text, where the same predictive pattern emerges: longer-pretrained checkpoints reach higher post-RL performance and improve faster under RL. In sum, we provide a quantitative account of the pretraining-to-RL interface and a controlled testbed for studying the science of reasoning across the full pretraining-to-post-training pipeline.", "upvotes": 19, "discussionId": "6a5d7a966a69ce099f4d6d05", "githubRepo": "https://github.com/pavelslab-nyu/pre2post-chess", "githubRepoAddedBy": "user", "githubStars": 15, "summary_zh": "<ul>\n    <li>\u5f3a\u5316\u5b66\u4e60\uff08RL\uff09\u5728\u63d0\u5347\u5927\u578b\u8bed\u8a00\u6a21\u578b\uff08LLM\uff09\u590d\u6742\u63a8\u7406\u4efb\u52a1\u4e2d\u53d8\u5f97\u81f3\u5173\u91cd\u8981\uff0c\u4f46\u5176\u540e\u7eed\u8bad\u7ec3\u901a\u5e38\u4e0e\u524d\u671f\u8bad\u7ec3\u5206\u5f00\u7814\u7a76\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u672c\u6587\u63a2\u8ba8\u4e86\u4e24\u4e2a\u95ee\u9898\uff1a\u524d\u671f\u8bad\u7ec3\u7684\u9009\u62e9\u5982\u4f55\u5f71\u54cd\u540e\u7eedRL\u7684\u6548\u679c\uff0c\u4ee5\u53caRL\u5bf9\u6a21\u578b\u7684\u5b9e\u9645\u5f71\u54cd\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u4f7f\u7528\u68cb\u7c7b\u4f5c\u4e3a\u63a7\u5236\u6d4b\u8bd5\u5e73\u53f0\uff0c\u7814\u7a76\u4ece\u524d\u671f\u8bad\u7ec3\u5230\u540e\u671f\u8bad\u7ec3\u7684\u5b8c\u6574\u6d41\u7a0b\uff0c\u8fdb\u884c\u6a21\u578b\u9884\u8bad\u7ec3\u3001\u76d1\u7763\u5fae\u8c03\u548cRL\u8bad\u7ec3\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u7814\u7a76\u53d1\u73b0\uff0c\u540e\u7eedRL\u6027\u80fd\u4e0e\u524d\u671f\u8bad\u7ec3\u635f\u5931\u6709\u826f\u597d\u9884\u6d4b\u5173\u7cfb\uff0c\u4e14RL\u5956\u52b1\u66f2\u7ebf\u7684\u659c\u7387\u968f\u7740\u524d\u671f\u8bad\u7ec3\u6570\u636e\u7684\u589e\u52a0\u800c\u7ebf\u6027\u6539\u5584\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u540c\u6837\u7684\u6a21\u5f0f\u5728\u6570\u5b66\u9886\u57df\u7684\u6587\u672c\u8bad\u7ec3\u4e2d\u4e5f\u5f97\u5230\u4e86\u9a8c\u8bc1\uff0c\u8868\u660e\u957f\u65f6\u95f4\u7684\u9884\u8bad\u7ec3\u80fd\u591f\u63d0\u9ad8\u540e\u7eedRL\u7684\u6027\u80fd\u3002</li>\n</ul>", "summary_simple": "<ul>\n    <li>Reinforcement learning (RL) is important for enhancing large language models (LLMs) in complex reasoning tasks, but its relationship with pretraining is not well understood.</li>\n    <li>Two main questions are explored: how pretraining choices affect RL performance, and what RL actually does to the model's abilities.</li>\n    <li>The research uses chess as a controlled environment to study the entire training process, from pretraining to post-training.</li>\n    <li>Results show that post-RL performance can be predicted from pretraining loss, and more pretraining leads to better RL performance.</li>\n    <li>The findings are also applicable to other domains, like math, where longer pretraining improves RL outcomes in a similar way.</li>\n</ul>"}, "publishedAt": "2026-07-16T20:00:00.000Z", "title": "Understanding Reasoning from Pretraining to Post-Training", "summary": "Reinforcement learning (RL) has become central to improving large language models (LLMs) on complex reasoning tasks, yet RL post-training is largely studied in isolation from the pretraining that precedes it. As a result, two basic questions remain open: (1) how do pretraining choices (model size, data) shape the returns to RL compute, and (2) what does RL actually do to the model? These questions are difficult to study in the standard LLM setting: pretraining corpora are vast and uncontrolled, making it hard to attribute behaviors to pretraining versus RL, and systematic compute sweeps across both stages are prohibitively expensive. To address these challenges, we use chess as a controlled testbed for studying reasoning across the full pretraining-to-post-training pipeline. We follow the standard LLM training pipeline by pretraining language models from 5M to 1B parameters on human chess games, supervised fine-tuning on synthetic reasoning traces, and running RL on chess puzzles with verifiable rewards. Using this framework, we find that the post-RL performance at given RL compute level is well-predicted from the pretraining loss, and slope of the RL reward curves improves approximately linearly with the pretraining tokens. Beyond scaling, we find that RL does not simply sharpen the SFT policy: on easy puzzles it amplifies correct moves the SFT policy already preferred, while on hard puzzles it surfaces correct moves that were nearly absent under SFT. We further test whether our findings transfer beyond chess by training a 1B language model on math-domain text, where the same predictive pattern emerges: longer-pretrained checkpoints reach higher post-RL performance and improve faster under RL. In sum, we provide a quantitative account of the pretraining-to-RL interface and a controlled testbed for studying the science of reasoning across the full pretraining-to-post-training pipeline.", "thumbnail": "https://cdn-thumbnails.huggingface.co/social-thumbnails/papers/2607.16097.png", "numComments": 1, "submittedBy": {"_id": "638828cd26952adc66f1bdbd", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/0be4c4af8f3d1ed9529bc77839952dab.svg", "fullname": "Evangeline Shen", "name": "Evangelinejy", "type": "user", "isPro": false, "isHf": false, "isHfAdmin": false, "isMod": false, "followerCount": 2, "isUserFollowing": false}, "isAuthorParticipating": true}],
    "week": [{"paper": {"id": "2606.29538", "authors": [{"_id": "6a599a716c2e371e6ca38125", "name": "Yijia Fan", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a599a716c2e371e6ca38126", "name": "Zonglin Di", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a599a716c2e371e6ca38127", "name": "Zimo Wen", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a599a716c2e371e6ca38128", "name": "Yifan Yang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a599a716c2e371e6ca38129", "name": "Mingxi Cheng", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a599a716c2e371e6ca3812a", "user": {"_id": "65115c00a588fdb36558b673", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/1f36263dc4bfaf696a4aa959a6aab1e1.svg", "isPro": false, "fullname": "Qi Dai", "user": "daiqi", "type": "user", "name": "daiqi"}, "name": "Qi Dai", "status": "claimed_verified", "statusLastChangedAt": "2026-07-20T16:05:41.351Z", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a599a716c2e371e6ca3812b", "name": "Bei Liu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a599a716c2e371e6ca3812c", "name": "Kai Qiu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a599a716c2e371e6ca3812d", "name": "Yue Dong", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a599a716c2e371e6ca3812e", "name": "Ji Li", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a599a716c2e371e6ca3812f", "name": "Chong Luo", "hidden": false}], "mediaUrls": ["https://cdn-uploads.huggingface.co/production/uploads/62d18eb81e36881a57f29bf4/aZPQHsZww6x3R9D_J7Si9.mp4"], "publishedAt": "2026-07-16T00:00:00.000Z", "submittedOnDailyAt": "2026-07-20T00:00:00.000Z", "title": "RESOURCE2SKILL: Distilling Executable Agent Skills from Human-Created Multimodal Resources", "submittedOnDailyBy": {"_id": "62d18eb81e36881a57f29bf4", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/104851421b4ee9641daaf15942fa7ea1.svg", "isPro": false, "fullname": "Yif Yang", "user": "Yif29", "type": "user", "name": "Yif29"}, "summary": "Skills are a useful abstraction for software agents, turning human and agent experience into reusable procedural knowledge. Yet existing skill libraries are mostly hand-written, text-centric, or derived from agent traces, leaving tutorial videos and other multimodal human resources largely underused. We present RESOURCE2SKILL, a framework that distills multimodal resources, including tutorial videos, repositories, articles, and reference artifacts, into executable skills for software agents. RESOURCE2SKILL organizes these skills as a hierarchical multimodal Skill Wiki, where each entry combines structured text, code, visual examples, metadata, and provenance. This design preserves complementary signals from different resources: videos capture temporal operations and visual effects, code captures executable tool patterns, and articles or artifacts provide conceptual and stylistic grounding. At inference time, agents retrieve and compose relevant skills from the wiki; when coverage is insufficient, the same construction operator can acquire new skills online. Across seven practical authoring domains, RESOURCE2SKILL improves average overall score by +11.9 percentage points over no-skill agents and outperforms strong harness baselines in 26 of 28 main-aggregate model-domain cells. Ablations confirm the value of multimodal skill format, hierarchical organization, source diversity, selection strategy, and online acquisition.", "upvotes": 113, "discussionId": "6a599a726c2e371e6ca38130", "projectPage": "https://aka.ms/Resources2Skill", "githubRepo": "https://github.com/microsoft/Resource2Skill", "githubRepoAddedBy": "user", "githubStars": 64, "organization": {"_id": "68151d0f51add3813f3f7d1b", "name": "MicrosoftResearch", "fullname": "Microsoft Research", "avatar": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/6529a4f2f1205983224fa513/PeuVr7jSuJflmDBBGxoDX.png"}, "summary_zh": "<ul>\n    <li>RESOURCE2SKILL\u662f\u4e00\u4e2a\u5c06\u591a\u79cd\u8d44\u6e90\uff08\u5982\u6559\u7a0b\u89c6\u9891\u3001\u6587\u7ae0\u7b49\uff09\u8f6c\u5316\u4e3a\u8f6f\u4ef6\u4ee3\u7406\u53ef\u6267\u884c\u6280\u80fd\u7684\u6846\u67b6\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u8be5\u6846\u67b6\u5c06\u6280\u80fd\u7ec4\u7ec7\u6210\u4e00\u4e2a\u5c42\u6b21\u5316\u7684\u591a\u6a21\u6001\u6280\u80fd\u7ef4\u57fa\uff0c\u7ed3\u5408\u4e86\u6587\u672c\u3001\u4ee3\u7801\u3001\u89c6\u89c9\u793a\u4f8b\u7b49\u4fe1\u606f\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u901a\u8fc7\u591a\u79cd\u8d44\u6e90\u7684\u7ed3\u5408\uff0c\u4fdd\u7559\u4e86\u89c6\u9891\u7684\u65f6\u95f4\u64cd\u4f5c\u3001\u4ee3\u7801\u7684\u53ef\u6267\u884c\u6a21\u5f0f\u548c\u6587\u7ae0\u7684\u6982\u5ff5\u57fa\u7840\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u5728\u4e03\u4e2a\u5b9e\u9645\u5e94\u7528\u9886\u57df\u4e2d\uff0cRESOURCE2SKILL\u4f7f\u5e73\u5747\u5206\u6570\u63d0\u9ad8\u4e8611.9%\uff0c\u5e76\u572826\u4e2a\u6a21\u578b\u57df\u4e2d\u8d85\u8fc7\u4e86\u5f3a\u57fa\u7ebf\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u5b9e\u9a8c\u7ed3\u679c\u8868\u660e\uff0c\u6280\u80fd\u7684\u591a\u6a21\u6001\u683c\u5f0f\u548c\u5c42\u6b21\u5316\u7ec4\u7ec7\u5177\u6709\u91cd\u8981\u4ef7\u503c\u3002 </li>\n</ul>", "summary_simple": "<ul>\n    <li>RESOURCE2SKILL is a new system that helps software agents learn skills from various resources, like tutorial videos and articles.</li>\n    <li>The system organizes these skills in a hierarchical Skill Wiki, combining text, code, visuals, and metadata.</li>\n    <li>This approach uses different types of resources effectively; videos show how things work over time, while code provides practical examples.</li>\n    <li>When agents need new skills, they can find and create them using this system, improving their performance significantly.</li>\n    <li>Tests show RESOURCE2SKILL improves agent performance by an average of 11.9 percentage points compared to agents without skills.</li>\n</ul>"}, "publishedAt": "2026-07-15T20:00:00.000Z", "title": "RESOURCE2SKILL: Distilling Executable Agent Skills from Human-Created Multimodal Resources", "summary": "Skills are a useful abstraction for software agents, turning human and agent experience into reusable procedural knowledge. Yet existing skill libraries are mostly hand-written, text-centric, or derived from agent traces, leaving tutorial videos and other multimodal human resources largely underused. We present RESOURCE2SKILL, a framework that distills multimodal resources, including tutorial videos, repositories, articles, and reference artifacts, into executable skills for software agents. RESOURCE2SKILL organizes these skills as a hierarchical multimodal Skill Wiki, where each entry combines structured text, code, visual examples, metadata, and provenance. This design preserves complementary signals from different resources: videos capture temporal operations and visual effects, code captures executable tool patterns, and articles or artifacts provide conceptual and stylistic grounding. At inference time, agents retrieve and compose relevant skills from the wiki; when coverage is insufficient, the same construction operator can acquire new skills online. Across seven practical authoring domains, RESOURCE2SKILL improves average overall score by +11.9 percentage points over no-skill agents and outperforms strong harness baselines in 26 of 28 main-aggregate model-domain cells. Ablations confirm the value of multimodal skill format, hierarchical organization, source diversity, selection strategy, and online acquisition.", "mediaUrls": ["https://cdn-uploads.huggingface.co/production/uploads/62d18eb81e36881a57f29bf4/aZPQHsZww6x3R9D_J7Si9.mp4"], "thumbnail": "https://cdn-thumbnails.huggingface.co/social-thumbnails/papers/2606.29538.png", "numComments": 1, "submittedBy": {"_id": "62d18eb81e36881a57f29bf4", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/104851421b4ee9641daaf15942fa7ea1.svg", "fullname": "Yif Yang", "name": "Yif29", "type": "user", "isPro": false, "isHf": false, "isHfAdmin": false, "isMod": false, "followerCount": 5, "isUserFollowing": false}, "organization": {"_id": "68151d0f51add3813f3f7d1b", "name": "MicrosoftResearch", "fullname": "Microsoft Research", "avatar": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/6529a4f2f1205983224fa513/PeuVr7jSuJflmDBBGxoDX.png"}, "isAuthorParticipating": false}, {"paper": {"id": "2607.14935", "authors": [{"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca380f1", "name": "Xinhao Li", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca380f2", "name": "Yuhan Zhu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca380f3", "name": "Xiangyu Zeng", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca380f4", "name": "Yuhao Dong", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca380f5", "name": "Haoning Wu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca380f6", "name": "Zhiqiu Zhang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca380f7", "name": "Yuandong Yang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca380f8", "name": "Changlian Ma", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca380f9", "name": "Qingyu Zhang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca380fa", "name": "Yansong Shi", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca380fb", "name": "Xinyu Chen", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca380fc", "name": "Haoran Chen", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca380fd", "name": "Zizheng Huang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca380fe", "name": "Jun Zhang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca380ff", "name": "Kun Ouyang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca38100", "name": "Lin Sui", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca38101", "name": "Ziang Yan", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca38102", "name": "Yicheng Xu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca38103", "name": "Chenting Wang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca38104", "name": "Yinan He", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca38105", "name": "Hongjie Zhang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca38106", "name": "Yi Wang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca38107", "name": "Yu Qiao", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca38108", "name": "Yali Wang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca38109", "name": "Ziwei Liu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca3810a", "name": "Kai Chen", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca3810b", "name": "Limin Wang", "hidden": false}], "publishedAt": "2026-07-16T00:00:00.000Z", "submittedOnDailyAt": "2026-07-17T00:00:00.000Z", "title": "VideoChat3: Fully Open Video MLLM for Efficient and Generalist Video Understanding", "submittedOnDailyBy": {"_id": "62c77f4352d8ae531f5511f9", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/50198ccb02ccd286975a4613fbabee28.svg", "isPro": false, "fullname": "Limin Wang", "user": "lmwang", "type": "user", "name": "lmwang"}, "summary": "Recent advances in video understanding have spanned motion, long video, and streaming interaction, driving this field toward real-world applications. Despite this progress, current open-source models remain limited in several ways. They often struggle to generalize across diverse video types, making them effective only in specific domains. High computational demands further restrict their efficiency and scalability. Moreover, most models are only partially open, with key components such as training code, strategy, or datasets unavailable, which hinders reproducibility and slows community-driven development. To address these issues, we introduce VideoChat3, a fully open, efficient, and generalist video-centric MLLM. VideoChat3 advances video understanding through two complementary designs. For efficiency, we introduce Inflated 3D Vision Transformer (I3D-ViT) and Adaptive Frame Resolution for Streaming Video Perception, which enables efficient spatiotemporal representation and reduces the cost of processing video inputs during training and inference. For effectiveness, we develop a scalable video data synthesis pipeline that curates three diverse, high-quality training datasets: VideoChat3-Academic2M, VideoChat3-LV116K, and VideoChat3-OL617K, covering general, long-form, and streaming video scenarios, improving the model's generalization across domains. By integrating these designs, VideoChat3 achieves a rare balance of broad generalization and computational efficiency. Experiments across general, long-form, and streaming benchmarks demonstrate that VideoChat3 surpasses prior open-source models with equal or larger parameter counts with only 4B parameters and higher efficiency.", "upvotes": 108, "discussionId": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca3810c", "projectPage": "https://mcg-nju.github.io/VideoChat3", "githubRepo": "https://github.com/MCG-NJU/VideoChat3", "githubRepoAddedBy": "user", "githubStars": 43, "organization": {"_id": "62c77fde1e080b83746468bd", "name": "MCG-NJU", "fullname": "Multimedia Computing Group-Nanjing University", "avatar": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/noauth/OIFtHl-mDBM_5SqyR9T8f.png"}, "summary_zh": "<ul>\n    <li>\u89c6\u9891\u7406\u89e3\u9886\u57df\u53d6\u5f97\u4e86\u8fdb\u5c55\uff0c\u4f46\u73b0\u6709\u7684\u5f00\u6e90\u6a21\u578b\u5b58\u5728\u4e00\u4e9b\u9650\u5236\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u6a21\u578b\u5728\u4e0d\u540c\u89c6\u9891\u7c7b\u578b\u4e4b\u95f4\u7684\u6cdb\u5316\u80fd\u529b\u8f83\u5dee\uff0c\u8ba1\u7b97\u9700\u6c42\u9ad8\uff0c\u9650\u5236\u4e86\u6548\u7387\u548c\u53ef\u6269\u5c55\u6027\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u5927\u591a\u6570\u6a21\u578b\u7684\u5173\u952e\u7ec4\u4ef6\u5e76\u672a\u5b8c\u5168\u5f00\u653e\uff0c\u5f71\u54cd\u4e86\u53ef\u91cd\u590d\u6027\u548c\u793e\u533a\u5f00\u53d1\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u6211\u4eec\u63a8\u51fa\u4e86VideoChat3\uff0c\u8fd9\u662f\u4e00\u79cd\u5b8c\u5168\u5f00\u653e\u3001\u9ad8\u6548\u4e14\u901a\u7528\u7684\u89c6\u9891\u4e2d\u5fc3\u591a\u6a21\u6001\u8bed\u8a00\u6a21\u578b\u3002</li>\n    <li>VideoChat3\u901a\u8fc7\u521b\u65b0\u7684\u8bbe\u8ba1\u63d0\u9ad8\u4e86\u89c6\u9891\u7406\u89e3\u80fd\u529b\uff0c\u5e76\u5728\u591a\u4e2a\u57fa\u51c6\u6d4b\u8bd5\u4e2d\u8d85\u8d8a\u4e86\u4ee5\u524d\u7684\u5f00\u6e90\u6a21\u578b\u3002</li>\n</ul>", "summary_simple": "<ul>\n    <li>Video understanding has improved recently, but open-source models still have limitations.</li>\n    <li>Current models struggle to work well with different types of videos and require a lot of computing power.</li>\n    <li>Many models are only partially open, making it hard for others to reproduce their results.</li>\n    <li>VideoChat3 is a new, fully open video model that aims to be efficient and effective.</li>\n    <li>It uses advanced technology to reduce processing costs and has three diverse training datasets, making it better at understanding different video types.</li>\n</ul>"}, "publishedAt": "2026-07-15T20:00:00.000Z", "title": "VideoChat3: Fully Open Video MLLM for Efficient and Generalist Video Understanding", "summary": "Recent advances in video understanding have spanned motion, long video, and streaming interaction, driving this field toward real-world applications. Despite this progress, current open-source models remain limited in several ways. They often struggle to generalize across diverse video types, making them effective only in specific domains. High computational demands further restrict their efficiency and scalability. Moreover, most models are only partially open, with key components such as training code, strategy, or datasets unavailable, which hinders reproducibility and slows community-driven development. To address these issues, we introduce VideoChat3, a fully open, efficient, and generalist video-centric MLLM. VideoChat3 advances video understanding through two complementary designs. For efficiency, we introduce Inflated 3D Vision Transformer (I3D-ViT) and Adaptive Frame Resolution for Streaming Video Perception, which enables efficient spatiotemporal representation and reduces the cost of processing video inputs during training and inference. For effectiveness, we develop a scalable video data synthesis pipeline that curates three diverse, high-quality training datasets: VideoChat3-Academic2M, VideoChat3-LV116K, and VideoChat3-OL617K, covering general, long-form, and streaming video scenarios, improving the model's generalization across domains. By integrating these designs, VideoChat3 achieves a rare balance of broad generalization and computational efficiency. Experiments across general, long-form, and streaming benchmarks demonstrate that VideoChat3 surpasses prior open-source models with equal or larger parameter counts with only 4B parameters and higher efficiency.", "thumbnail": "https://cdn-thumbnails.huggingface.co/social-thumbnails/papers/2607.14935.png", "numComments": 1, "submittedBy": {"_id": "62c77f4352d8ae531f5511f9", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/50198ccb02ccd286975a4613fbabee28.svg", "fullname": "Limin Wang", "name": "lmwang", "type": "user", "isPro": false, "isHf": false, "isHfAdmin": false, "isMod": false, "followerCount": 2, "isUserFollowing": false}, "organization": {"_id": "62c77fde1e080b83746468bd", "name": "MCG-NJU", "fullname": "Multimedia Computing Group-Nanjing University", "avatar": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/noauth/OIFtHl-mDBM_5SqyR9T8f.png"}, "isAuthorParticipating": false}, {"paper": {"id": "2607.14777", "authors": [{"_id": "6a5991346c2e371e6ca38088", "name": "Jinyang Wu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5991346c2e371e6ca38089", "name": "Shuo Yang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5991346c2e371e6ca3808a", "name": "Zhengxi Lu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5991346c2e371e6ca3808b", "name": "Fan Zhang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5991346c2e371e6ca3808c", "name": "Yuhao Shen", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5991346c2e371e6ca3808d", "name": "Lang Feng", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5991346c2e371e6ca3808e", "name": "Haoran Luo", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5991346c2e371e6ca3808f", "name": "Zheng Lian", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5991346c2e371e6ca38090", "name": "Shuai Zhang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5991346c2e371e6ca38091", "name": "Zhengqi Wen", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5991346c2e371e6ca38092", "name": "Jianhua Tao", "hidden": false}], "publishedAt": "2026-07-16T00:00:00.000Z", "submittedOnDailyAt": "2026-07-17T00:00:00.000Z", "title": "SEED: Self-Evolving On-Policy Distillation for Agentic Reinforcement Learning", "submittedOnDailyBy": {"_id": "6747de57f8cab58c22ec94a2", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/5bae0341862fac24564781c0fa32aac5.svg", "isPro": false, "fullname": "Jinyang Wu", "user": "Jinyang23", "type": "user", "name": "Jinyang23"}, "summary": "Large language models are increasingly trained as interactive agents for long-horizon tasks involving multi-turn interaction, tool use, and environment feedback. Outcome-based reinforcement learning (RL) provides a practical optimization paradigm, but its sparse trajectory-level rewards offer limited guidance on intermediate decisions, leaving a supervision gap between episode-level outcomes and token-level policy learning. We propose SEED (SElf-Evolving On-Policy Distillation), a self-evolving framework that converts completed on-policy trajectories into training-time hindsight skills and distills their behavioral effect back into the policy model. SEED first fine-tunes the policy to analyze completed trajectories and generate natural-language skills that capture reusable workflows, decisive observations, or failure-avoidance rules. During RL, the current policy both collects trajectories and serves as the analyzer that extracts hindsight skills from them. Policy updates therefore improve subsequent decision making and skill analysis together, allowing hindsight supervision to evolve with the policy. SEED then re-scores the sampled actions under ordinary and skill-augmented contexts, converting the skill-induced probability shift into a dense token-level on-policy distillation signal. This signal is jointly optimized with outcome-based RL, keeping the auxiliary supervision aligned with the current trajectory distribution. Extensive experiments on text-based and vision-based agentic tasks show that SEED consistently improves performance and sample efficiency, exhibiting robust generalization to unseen scenarios. Our code is available at https://github.com/jinyangwu/SEED.", "upvotes": 67, "discussionId": "6a5991346c2e371e6ca38093", "projectPage": "https://jinyangwu.github.io/seed/", "githubRepo": "https://github.com/jinyangwu/SEED", "githubRepoAddedBy": "user", "githubStars": 81, "summary_zh": "<ul>\n  <li>\u5927\u578b\u8bed\u8a00\u6a21\u578b\u88ab\u8bad\u7ec3\u4e3a\u4e92\u52a8\u4ee3\u7406\uff0c\u9002\u7528\u4e8e\u591a\u8f6e\u4ea4\u4e92\u3001\u5de5\u5177\u4f7f\u7528\u548c\u73af\u5883\u53cd\u9988\u7684\u957f\u671f\u4efb\u52a1\u3002</li>\n  <li>\u57fa\u4e8e\u7ed3\u679c\u7684\u5f3a\u5316\u5b66\u4e60\uff08RL\uff09\u63d0\u4f9b\u4e86\u4e00\u79cd\u4f18\u5316\u65b9\u6cd5\uff0c\u4f46\u7a00\u758f\u7684\u5956\u52b1\u4fe1\u53f7\u4f7f\u4e2d\u95f4\u51b3\u7b56\u6307\u5bfc\u4e0d\u8db3\u3002</li>\n  <li>\u6211\u4eec\u63d0\u51fa\u4e86SEED\u6846\u67b6\uff0c\u901a\u8fc7\u5206\u6790\u5df2\u5b8c\u6210\u7684\u7b56\u7565\u8f68\u8ff9\uff0c\u751f\u6210\u53ef\u91cd\u7528\u7684\u81ea\u7136\u8bed\u8a00\u6280\u80fd\uff0c\u4ece\u800c\u6539\u5584\u51b3\u7b56\u8fc7\u7a0b\u3002</li>\n  <li>SEED\u5728\u8fdb\u884c\u5f3a\u5316\u5b66\u4e60\u65f6\uff0c\u65e2\u6536\u96c6\u8f68\u8ff9\uff0c\u53c8\u63d0\u53d6\u6280\u80fd\uff0c\u4ece\u800c\u4f7f\u7b56\u7565\u66f4\u65b0\u548c\u6280\u80fd\u5206\u6790\u76f8\u4e92\u4fc3\u8fdb\u3002</li>\n  <li>\u5927\u91cf\u5b9e\u9a8c\u8868\u660e\uff0cSEED\u5728\u6587\u672c\u548c\u89c6\u89c9\u4efb\u52a1\u4e0a\u63d0\u9ad8\u4e86\u6027\u80fd\u548c\u6837\u672c\u6548\u7387\uff0c\u5e76\u5728\u672a\u89c1\u573a\u666f\u4e2d\u8868\u73b0\u51fa\u826f\u597d\u7684\u6cdb\u5316\u80fd\u529b\u3002</li>\n</ul>", "summary_simple": "<ul>\n    <li>Large language models are being trained to perform complex tasks that require ongoing interaction and feedback.</li>\n    <li>Current reward systems in reinforcement learning can be limited, making it hard to learn from intermediate steps.</li>\n    <li>The SEED framework helps improve learning by analyzing past actions and creating useful skills that can be reused.</li>\n    <li>SEED allows the model to learn from its experiences while it is still training, making future decisions better.</li>\n    <li>Tests show that SEED enhances performance and efficiency in both text and visual tasks, helping the model adapt to new situations.</li>\n</ul>"}, "publishedAt": "2026-07-15T20:00:00.000Z", "title": "SEED: Self-Evolving On-Policy Distillation for Agentic Reinforcement Learning", "summary": "Large language models are increasingly trained as interactive agents for long-horizon tasks involving multi-turn interaction, tool use, and environment feedback. Outcome-based reinforcement learning (RL) provides a practical optimization paradigm, but its sparse trajectory-level rewards offer limited guidance on intermediate decisions, leaving a supervision gap between episode-level outcomes and token-level policy learning. We propose SEED (SElf-Evolving On-Policy Distillation), a self-evolving framework that converts completed on-policy trajectories into training-time hindsight skills and distills their behavioral effect back into the policy model. SEED first fine-tunes the policy to analyze completed trajectories and generate natural-language skills that capture reusable workflows, decisive observations, or failure-avoidance rules. During RL, the current policy both collects trajectories and serves as the analyzer that extracts hindsight skills from them. Policy updates therefore improve subsequent decision making and skill analysis together, allowing hindsight supervision to evolve with the policy. SEED then re-scores the sampled actions under ordinary and skill-augmented contexts, converting the skill-induced probability shift into a dense token-level on-policy distillation signal. This signal is jointly optimized with outcome-based RL, keeping the auxiliary supervision aligned with the current trajectory distribution. Extensive experiments on text-based and vision-based agentic tasks show that SEED consistently improves performance and sample efficiency, exhibiting robust generalization to unseen scenarios. Our code is available at https://github.com/jinyangwu/SEED.", "thumbnail": "https://cdn-thumbnails.huggingface.co/social-thumbnails/papers/2607.14777.png", "numComments": 1, "submittedBy": {"_id": "6747de57f8cab58c22ec94a2", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/5bae0341862fac24564781c0fa32aac5.svg", "fullname": "Jinyang Wu", "name": "Jinyang23", "type": "user", "isPro": false, "isHf": false, "isHfAdmin": false, "isMod": false, "followerCount": 12, "isUserFollowing": false}, "isAuthorParticipating": false}, {"paper": {"id": "2607.16051", "authors": [{"_id": "6a5d835d6a69ce099f4d6d79", "user": {"_id": "641ddac5be3bd3a5a06ed4a4", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/14969dff861d53b0a75305606495eca7.svg", "isPro": false, "fullname": "Zitian Gao", "user": "zgao3186", "type": "user", "name": "zgao3186"}, "name": "Zitian Gao", "status": "claimed_verified", "statusLastChangedAt": "2026-07-20T16:06:01.598Z", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d835d6a69ce099f4d6d7a", "name": "Yilong Chen", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d835d6a69ce099f4d6d7b", "name": "Yihao Xiao", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d835d6a69ce099f4d6d7c", "name": "Xinyu Yang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d835d6a69ce099f4d6d7d", "name": "Ran Tao", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d835d6a69ce099f4d6d7e", "name": "Joey Zhou", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d835d6a69ce099f4d6d7f", "name": "Bryan Dai", "hidden": false}], "publishedAt": "2026-07-17T00:00:00.000Z", "submittedOnDailyAt": "2026-07-20T00:00:00.000Z", "title": "Loop the Loopies!", "submittedOnDailyBy": {"_id": "6039478ab3ecf716b1a5fd4d", "avatarUrl": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/6039478ab3ecf716b1a5fd4d/_Thy4E7taiSYBLKxEKJbT.jpeg", "isPro": true, "fullname": "taesiri", "user": "taesiri", "type": "user", "name": "taesiri"}, "summary": "We present Loopie, the most powerful looped Transformer to date. The Loopie series consists of two Mixture-of-Experts (MoE) models: a 20B-parameter model with 2B active parameters and a 6Bparameter model with 0.6B active parameters. Looped Transformers have long faced a challenge: given an N-fold increase in pre-training compute, increasing the parameter count by a factor of N usually outperforms looping a model N times. Loopie addresses this challenge. Extensive ablation studies, including comparisons with a vanilla 30B-A3B model, show that Loopie substantially outperforms vanilla Transformer baselines trained with the same compute budget. Our novel post-training pipeline equips Loopie with strong reasoning abilities. At the 2025 IMO and IPhO, Loopie achieves gold-medal performance without tools.", "upvotes": 55, "discussionId": "6a5d835d6a69ce099f4d6d80", "organization": {"_id": "6937e1578cd2568ba4c9d3f9", "name": "IQuestLab", "fullname": "IQuest", "avatar": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/68c80cc3a1ca9a73c17d29f7/pjOEigZuk_UQ4dqyS482V.png"}, "summary_zh": "<ul>\n    <li>Loopie\u662f\u76ee\u524d\u6700\u5f3a\u5927\u7684\u5faa\u73af\u53d8\u6362\u5668\uff0c\u5305\u542b\u4e24\u4e2a\u6df7\u5408\u4e13\u5bb6\u6a21\u578b\u3002</li>\n    <li>20B\u53c2\u6570\u6a21\u578b\u67092B\u6d3b\u8dc3\u53c2\u6570\uff0c6B\u53c2\u6570\u6a21\u578b\u67090.6B\u6d3b\u8dc3\u53c2\u6570\u3002</li>\n    <li>Loopie\u89e3\u51b3\u4e86\u5faa\u73af\u53d8\u6362\u5668\u5728\u9884\u8bad\u7ec3\u8ba1\u7b97\u589e\u957f\u65f6\u7684\u6027\u80fd\u6311\u6218\u3002</li>\n    <li>Loopie\u5728\u4e0e\u4f20\u7edf30B-A3B\u6a21\u578b\u7684\u6bd4\u8f83\u4e2d\u8868\u73b0\u4f18\u8d8a\u3002</li>\n    <li>Loopie\u5177\u5907\u5f3a\u5927\u7684\u63a8\u7406\u80fd\u529b\uff0c\u5e76\u57282025\u5e74IMO\u548cIPhO\u4e2d\u8868\u73b0\u51fa\u8272\u3002</li>\n</ul>", "summary_simple": "<ul>\n  <li>Loopie is a new and powerful looped Transformer model.</li>\n  <li>It includes two versions: a 20 billion parameter model and a 6 billion parameter model.</li>\n  <li>Loopie improves performance by handling increased computational power better than traditional models.</li>\n  <li>It has been tested extensively and outperforms standard Transformer models with the same resources.</li>\n  <li>Loopie shows excellent reasoning skills and achieved top results in competitions without using tools.</li>\n</ul>"}, "publishedAt": "2026-07-16T20:00:00.000Z", "title": "Loop the Loopies!", "summary": "We present Loopie, the most powerful looped Transformer to date. The Loopie series consists of two Mixture-of-Experts (MoE) models: a 20B-parameter model with 2B active parameters and a 6Bparameter model with 0.6B active parameters. Looped Transformers have long faced a challenge: given an N-fold increase in pre-training compute, increasing the parameter count by a factor of N usually outperforms looping a model N times. Loopie addresses this challenge. Extensive ablation studies, including comparisons with a vanilla 30B-A3B model, show that Loopie substantially outperforms vanilla Transformer baselines trained with the same compute budget. Our novel post-training pipeline equips Loopie with strong reasoning abilities. At the 2025 IMO and IPhO, Loopie achieves gold-medal performance without tools.", "thumbnail": "https://cdn-thumbnails.huggingface.co/social-thumbnails/papers/2607.16051.png", "numComments": 0, "submittedBy": {"_id": "6039478ab3ecf716b1a5fd4d", "avatarUrl": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/6039478ab3ecf716b1a5fd4d/_Thy4E7taiSYBLKxEKJbT.jpeg", "fullname": "taesiri", "name": "taesiri", "type": "user", "isPro": true, "isHf": false, "isHfAdmin": false, "isMod": false, "followerCount": 338, "isUserFollowing": false}, "organization": {"_id": "6937e1578cd2568ba4c9d3f9", "name": "IQuestLab", "fullname": "IQuest", "avatar": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/68c80cc3a1ca9a73c17d29f7/pjOEigZuk_UQ4dqyS482V.png"}, "isAuthorParticipating": false}, {"paper": {"id": "2607.15330", "authors": [{"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6de9", "name": "Xiaomi Robotics Team", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6dea", "name": "Jun Guo", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6deb", "name": "Piaopiao Jin", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6dec", "name": "Jason Li", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6ded", "user": {"_id": "6337e04b171879571956212f", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/aa69142bf92e4c50b192463490251ed9.svg", "isPro": false, "fullname": "Li Peiyan", "user": "LPY", "type": "user", "name": "LPY"}, "name": "Peiyan Li", "status": "claimed_verified", "statusLastChangedAt": "2026-07-20T16:06:02.904Z", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6dee", "name": "Yingyan Li", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6def", "name": "Futeng Liu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6df0", "name": "Wanli Peng", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6df1", "name": "Optimus Qin", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6df2", "name": "Yifei Su", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6df3", "name": "Nan Sun", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6df4", "name": "Qiao Sun", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6df5", "name": "Runze Suo", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6df6", "name": "Heyun Wang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6df7", "name": "Yunhong Wang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6df8", "name": "Rujie Wu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6df9", "name": "Caoyu Xia", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6dfa", "name": "Lina Zhang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6dfb", "name": "Jack Zhao", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6dfc", "name": "Guoliang Chen", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6dfd", "name": "Wenlong Chen", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6dfe", "name": "Xinze He", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6dff", "name": "Bin Li", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6e00", "name": "Qing Li", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6e01", "name": "Zhuorong Li", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6e02", "name": "Heng Qu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6e03", "name": "Wenxuan Song", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6e04", "name": "Diyun Xiang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6e05", "name": "Yifan Xie", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6e06", "name": "Peiran Xu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6e07", "name": "Hangjun Ye", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6e08", "name": "Wen Ye", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6e09", "name": "Han Zhao", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6e0a", "name": "Quanyun Zhou", "hidden": false}], "mediaUrls": ["https://cdn-uploads.huggingface.co/production/uploads/670bd33ec9c7e01d3dbaf59d/WMsV90grYxbmZgQDMBn8a.mp4"], "publishedAt": "2026-07-16T00:00:00.000Z", "submittedOnDailyAt": "2026-07-20T00:00:00.000Z", "title": "Xiaomi-Robotics-1: Scaling Vision-Language-Action Models with over 100K Hours of Real-World Trajectories", "submittedOnDailyBy": {"_id": "670bd33ec9c7e01d3dbaf59d", "avatarUrl": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/noauth/PCL5O0f3DXjKrc_EvdAgb.png", "isPro": false, "fullname": "yewen", "user": "YeWen27", "type": "user", "name": "YeWen27"}, "summary": "We present Xiaomi-Robotics-1, a foundational vision-language-action (VLA) model capable of (1) following diverse language instructions to perform a wide range of mobile manipulation tasks in unseen environments out-of-the-box, and (2) efficiently adapting to novel downstream tasks with minimal fine-tuning data. We propose a two-stage training recipe consisting of pre-training and post-training. During pre-training, we imbue the model with broad and generalizable action-generation capabilities by training on over 100k hours of real-world manipulation trajectories collected via UMI devices. Crucially, we develop a scalable auto-labeling pipeline that annotates trajectory clips with natural languages describing scene state transitions, providing rich and precise conditioning for action learning. During post-training, we aim to align these capabilities with robot embodiments and imperative instructions that humans naturally use to prompt robots. Extensive experiments demonstrate strong scaling behavior. Xiaomi-Robotics-1 consistently improves with increased data scales and model sizes during pre-training. This scaling behavior directly transfers to post-training, where a stronger pre-training model yields better out-of-the-box real-robot performance in unseen environments. Furthermore, Xiaomi-Robotics-1 serves as a strong robot foundation policy that can be efficiently fine-tuned on complex, dexterous tasks with high data efficiency. Across multiple simulation benchmarks, Xiaomi-Robotics-1 outperforms state-of-the-art methods. Notably, it establishes a new state-of-the-art with a 57.6% success rate on RoboCasa365, surpassing the previous best of 46.6%. Furthermore, it achieves an average score of 20.07 on RoboDojo, significantly outperforming the prior state-of-the-art (13.07). Code and model checkpoints will be released. Project page: https://robotics.xiaomi.com/xiaomi-robotics-1.html", "upvotes": 54, "discussionId": "6a5d90cd6a69ce099f4d6e0b", "projectPage": "https://robotics.xiaomi.com/xiaomi-robotics-1.html", "githubRepo": "https://github.com/XiaomiRobotics/Xiaomi-Robotics-1", "githubRepoAddedBy": "user", "githubStars": 143, "organization": {"_id": "697ad5f82057bf915ef24446", "name": "XiaomiRobotics", "fullname": "Xiaomi Robotics", "avatar": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/697ad78bb8e83c3ded37b2c7/gox0VlsrikZeJ_10vxe0A.png"}, "summary_zh": "<ul>\n    <li>\u5c0f\u7c73\u673a\u5668\u4eba1\u662f\u4e00\u4e2a\u57fa\u7840\u7684\u89c6\u89c9-\u8bed\u8a00-\u52a8\u4f5c\u6a21\u578b\uff0c\u80fd\u591f\u6839\u636e\u8bed\u8a00\u6307\u4ee4\u5728\u672a\u77e5\u73af\u5883\u4e2d\u6267\u884c\u591a\u79cd\u79fb\u52a8\u64cd\u4f5c\u4efb\u52a1\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u6a21\u578b\u7ecf\u8fc7\u4e24\u9636\u6bb5\u8bad\u7ec3\uff1a\u9884\u8bad\u7ec3\u548c\u540e\u8bad\u7ec3\uff0c\u9884\u8bad\u7ec3\u65f6\u4f7f\u7528\u8d85\u8fc710\u4e07\u5c0f\u65f6\u7684\u771f\u5b9e\u64cd\u4f5c\u8f68\u8ff9\u6570\u636e\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u5f00\u53d1\u4e86\u4e00\u4e2a\u53ef\u6269\u5c55\u7684\u81ea\u52a8\u6807\u6ce8\u6d41\u7a0b\uff0c\u7528\u81ea\u7136\u8bed\u8a00\u4e3a\u64cd\u4f5c\u8f68\u8ff9\u7247\u6bb5\u6ce8\u91ca\uff0c\u5e2e\u52a9\u6a21\u578b\u5b66\u4e60\u52a8\u4f5c\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u6a21\u578b\u5728\u9884\u8bad\u7ec3\u548c\u540e\u8bad\u7ec3\u4e2d\u90fd\u8868\u73b0\u51fa\u826f\u597d\u7684\u6269\u5c55\u6027\uff0c\u6570\u636e\u91cf\u548c\u6a21\u578b\u89c4\u6a21\u589e\u52a0\u65f6\u6027\u80fd\u6301\u7eed\u63d0\u5347\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u5728\u591a\u4e2a\u6a21\u62df\u57fa\u51c6\u6d4b\u8bd5\u4e2d\uff0c\u5c0f\u7c73\u673a\u5668\u4eba1\u7684\u6210\u529f\u7387\u548c\u5f97\u5206\u90fd\u8d85\u8fc7\u4e86\u73b0\u6709\u6700\u4f73\u6c34\u5e73\uff0c\u5c55\u793a\u4e86\u5176\u9ad8\u6548\u7684\u5fae\u8c03\u80fd\u529b\u3002</li>\n</ul>", "summary_simple": "<ul>\n    <li>Xiaomi-Robotics-1 is a new model that helps robots understand and follow language instructions for various tasks in new environments without needing much setup.</li>\n    <li>The model is trained in two stages: first, it learns general actions from a large amount of real-world data, and then it fine-tunes to work better with human-like instructions.</li>\n    <li>It uses an innovative system to label action data with natural language descriptions, improving how robots learn actions.</li>\n    <li>Tests show that the model performs better as it is trained with more data and larger sizes, leading to improved performance in real-world robot tasks.</li>\n    <li>Xiaomi-Robotics-1 sets new records for success rates on specific robot task benchmarks, outperforming previous models.</li>\n</ul>"}, "publishedAt": "2026-07-15T20:00:00.000Z", "title": "Xiaomi-Robotics-1: Scaling Vision-Language-Action Models with over 100K Hours of Real-World Trajectories", "summary": "We present Xiaomi-Robotics-1, a foundational vision-language-action (VLA) model capable of (1) following diverse language instructions to perform a wide range of mobile manipulation tasks in unseen environments out-of-the-box, and (2) efficiently adapting to novel downstream tasks with minimal fine-tuning data. We propose a two-stage training recipe consisting of pre-training and post-training. During pre-training, we imbue the model with broad and generalizable action-generation capabilities by training on over 100k hours of real-world manipulation trajectories collected via UMI devices. Crucially, we develop a scalable auto-labeling pipeline that annotates trajectory clips with natural languages describing scene state transitions, providing rich and precise conditioning for action learning. During post-training, we aim to align these capabilities with robot embodiments and imperative instructions that humans naturally use to prompt robots. Extensive experiments demonstrate strong scaling behavior. Xiaomi-Robotics-1 consistently improves with increased data scales and model sizes during pre-training. This scaling behavior directly transfers to post-training, where a stronger pre-training model yields better out-of-the-box real-robot performance in unseen environments. Furthermore, Xiaomi-Robotics-1 serves as a strong robot foundation policy that can be efficiently fine-tuned on complex, dexterous tasks with high data efficiency. Across multiple simulation benchmarks, Xiaomi-Robotics-1 outperforms state-of-the-art methods. Notably, it establishes a new state-of-the-art with a 57.6% success rate on RoboCasa365, surpassing the previous best of 46.6%. Furthermore, it achieves an average score of 20.07 on RoboDojo, significantly outperforming the prior state-of-the-art (13.07). Code and model checkpoints will be released. Project page: https://robotics.xiaomi.com/xiaomi-robotics-1.html", "mediaUrls": ["https://cdn-uploads.huggingface.co/production/uploads/670bd33ec9c7e01d3dbaf59d/WMsV90grYxbmZgQDMBn8a.mp4"], "thumbnail": "https://cdn-thumbnails.huggingface.co/social-thumbnails/papers/2607.15330.png", "numComments": 1, "submittedBy": {"_id": "670bd33ec9c7e01d3dbaf59d", "avatarUrl": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/noauth/PCL5O0f3DXjKrc_EvdAgb.png", "fullname": "yewen", "name": "YeWen27", "type": "user", "isPro": false, "isHf": false, "isHfAdmin": false, "isMod": false, "isUserFollowing": false}, "organization": {"_id": "697ad5f82057bf915ef24446", "name": "XiaomiRobotics", "fullname": "Xiaomi Robotics", "avatar": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/697ad78bb8e83c3ded37b2c7/gox0VlsrikZeJ_10vxe0A.png"}, "isAuthorParticipating": false}, {"paper": {"id": "2607.15257", "authors": [{"_id": "6a59943a6c2e371e6ca380bd", "name": "Yuyao Zhang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a59943a6c2e371e6ca380be", "name": "Junjie Gao", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a59943a6c2e371e6ca380bf", "name": "Zhengxian Wu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a59943a6c2e371e6ca380c0", "name": "Jiaming Fan", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a59943a6c2e371e6ca380c1", "name": "Jin Zhang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a59943a6c2e371e6ca380c2", "name": "Shihan Ma", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a59943a6c2e371e6ca380c3", "name": "Yao Yao", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a59943a6c2e371e6ca380c4", "name": "Weiran Qi", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a59943a6c2e371e6ca380c5", "name": "Chuyan Jin", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a59943a6c2e371e6ca380c6", "name": "Guiyu Ma", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a59943a6c2e371e6ca380c7", "name": "Xingzhong Xu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a59943a6c2e371e6ca380c8", "name": "Kai Yang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a59943a6c2e371e6ca380c9", "name": "Ji-Rong Wen", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a59943a6c2e371e6ca380ca", "name": "Zhicheng Dou", "hidden": false}], "mediaUrls": ["https://cdn-uploads.huggingface.co/production/uploads/6039478ab3ecf716b1a5fd4d/ALn3GHZUn9chntoZi8p5w.mp4"], "publishedAt": "2026-07-16T00:00:00.000Z", "submittedOnDailyAt": "2026-07-17T00:00:00.000Z", "title": "SearchOS-V1: Towards Robust Open-Domain Information-Seeking Agent Collaboration", "submittedOnDailyBy": {"_id": "6039478ab3ecf716b1a5fd4d", "avatarUrl": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/6039478ab3ecf716b1a5fd4d/_Thy4E7taiSYBLKxEKJbT.jpeg", "isPro": true, "fullname": "taesiri", "user": "taesiri", "type": "user", "name": "taesiri"}, "summary": "Recent advances in Tool-Integrated Large Language Models have made web search a core capability of information-seeking agents. However, as interaction histories grow, agents increasingly struggle to track task progress. When search attempts fail to yield useful evidence, current single- and multi-agent systems can become trapped in repetitive loops, wasting search budgets and ultimately compromising the quality and completeness of the final output. We introduce SearchOS, a system-level multi-agent framework that turns fragile, implicit search progress into explicit, persistent, and shared state. First, we formulate open-domain information seeking as relational schema completion with grounded citations, where agents discover entities, populate attributes across linked tables, and anchor each value to source evidence. Then we design Search-Oriented Context Management (SOCM), which externalizes the evolving state into Frontier Task, an Evidence Graph, a Coverage Map, and Failure Memory. Built on SOCM, SearchOS applies a pipeline-parallel scheduling mechanism that overlaps the execution of sub-agents and continuously refills freed slots with tasks targeting unresolved coverage gaps to improve utilization and throughput. To schedule and control the execution of search agents, SearchOS introduces a Search Tool Middleware Harness that intercepts model and tool interactions to record grounded evidence and react to stalls or budget exhaustion, and provides a reusable hierarchical skill system comprising strategy and access skills to augment the agents' search process and avoid repeating failed search patterns across runs. On WideSearch and GISA, SearchOS leads all metrics among the evaluated single- and multi-agent baselines, paving the way toward robust information-seeking collaboration.", "upvotes": 49, "discussionId": "6a59943a6c2e371e6ca380cb", "githubRepo": "https://github.com/antins-labs/SearchOS", "githubRepoAddedBy": "user", "githubStars": 54, "organization": {"_id": "67c1d682826160b28f778510", "name": "antgroup", "fullname": "Ant Group", "avatar": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/662e1f9da266499277937d33/7VcPHdLSGlged3ixK1dys.jpeg"}, "summary_zh": "<ul>\n    <li>Tool-Integrated Large Language Models \u4f7f\u7f51\u7edc\u641c\u7d22\u6210\u4e3a\u4fe1\u606f\u83b7\u53d6\u4ee3\u7406\u7684\u6838\u5fc3\u80fd\u529b\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u968f\u7740\u4ea4\u4e92\u5386\u53f2\u7684\u589e\u957f\uff0c\u4ee3\u7406\u5728\u8ddf\u8e2a\u4efb\u52a1\u8fdb\u5c55\u65b9\u9762\u9762\u4e34\u6311\u6218\uff0c\u53ef\u80fd\u4f1a\u9677\u5165\u91cd\u590d\u641c\u7d22\u7684\u5faa\u73af\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u6211\u4eec\u63d0\u51fa\u4e86 SearchOS\uff0c\u4e00\u4e2a\u591a\u4ee3\u7406\u6846\u67b6\uff0c\u5c06\u8106\u5f31\u7684\u641c\u7d22\u8fdb\u5c55\u8f6c\u53d8\u4e3a\u660e\u786e\u3001\u6301\u4e45\u548c\u5171\u4eab\u7684\u72b6\u6001\u3002</li>\n    <li>SearchOS \u901a\u8fc7\u5f15\u5165\u641c\u7d22\u5bfc\u5411\u4e0a\u4e0b\u6587\u7ba1\u7406\uff08SOCM\uff09\u548c\u5e76\u884c\u8c03\u5ea6\u673a\u5236\uff0c\u63d0\u9ad8\u4e86\u4ee3\u7406\u7684\u641c\u7d22\u6548\u7387\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u5728 WideSearch \u548c GISA \u6d4b\u8bd5\u4e2d\uff0cSearchOS \u5728\u5404\u9879\u6307\u6807\u4e0a\u4f18\u4e8e\u5176\u4ed6\u5355\u4ee3\u7406\u548c\u591a\u4ee3\u7406\u7cfb\u7edf\uff0c\u4fc3\u8fdb\u4e86\u4fe1\u606f\u83b7\u53d6\u7684\u534f\u4f5c\u80fd\u529b\u3002</li>\n</ul>", "summary_simple": "<ul>\n    <li>Recent improvements in technology have made web search essential for information-seeking agents.</li>\n    <li>As agents handle more tasks, they often struggle to keep track of their progress, leading to inefficient searches.</li>\n    <li>SearchOS is a new system that helps agents manage their search progress more effectively by creating a clear and shared state of their tasks.</li>\n    <li>The system uses a method called Search-Oriented Context Management to organize information and improve task execution.</li>\n    <li>SearchOS outperforms other systems in tests, showing it can better support teamwork in information-seeking tasks.</li>\n</ul>"}, "publishedAt": "2026-07-15T20:00:00.000Z", "title": "SearchOS-V1: Towards Robust Open-Domain Information-Seeking Agent Collaboration", "summary": "Recent advances in Tool-Integrated Large Language Models have made web search a core capability of information-seeking agents. However, as interaction histories grow, agents increasingly struggle to track task progress. When search attempts fail to yield useful evidence, current single- and multi-agent systems can become trapped in repetitive loops, wasting search budgets and ultimately compromising the quality and completeness of the final output. We introduce SearchOS, a system-level multi-agent framework that turns fragile, implicit search progress into explicit, persistent, and shared state. First, we formulate open-domain information seeking as relational schema completion with grounded citations, where agents discover entities, populate attributes across linked tables, and anchor each value to source evidence. Then we design Search-Oriented Context Management (SOCM), which externalizes the evolving state into Frontier Task, an Evidence Graph, a Coverage Map, and Failure Memory. Built on SOCM, SearchOS applies a pipeline-parallel scheduling mechanism that overlaps the execution of sub-agents and continuously refills freed slots with tasks targeting unresolved coverage gaps to improve utilization and throughput. To schedule and control the execution of search agents, SearchOS introduces a Search Tool Middleware Harness that intercepts model and tool interactions to record grounded evidence and react to stalls or budget exhaustion, and provides a reusable hierarchical skill system comprising strategy and access skills to augment the agents' search process and avoid repeating failed search patterns across runs. On WideSearch and GISA, SearchOS leads all metrics among the evaluated single- and multi-agent baselines, paving the way toward robust information-seeking collaboration.", "mediaUrls": ["https://cdn-uploads.huggingface.co/production/uploads/6039478ab3ecf716b1a5fd4d/ALn3GHZUn9chntoZi8p5w.mp4"], "thumbnail": "https://cdn-thumbnails.huggingface.co/social-thumbnails/papers/2607.15257.png", "numComments": 0, "submittedBy": {"_id": "6039478ab3ecf716b1a5fd4d", "avatarUrl": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/6039478ab3ecf716b1a5fd4d/_Thy4E7taiSYBLKxEKJbT.jpeg", "fullname": "taesiri", "name": "taesiri", "type": "user", "isPro": true, "isHf": false, "isHfAdmin": false, "isMod": false, "followerCount": 336, "isUserFollowing": false}, "organization": {"_id": "67c1d682826160b28f778510", "name": "antgroup", "fullname": "Ant Group", "avatar": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/662e1f9da266499277937d33/7VcPHdLSGlged3ixK1dys.jpeg"}, "isAuthorParticipating": false}, {"paper": {"id": "2607.14530", "authors": [{"_id": "6a5d82836a69ce099f4d6d69", "name": "Xiangdong Zhang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d82836a69ce099f4d6d6a", "name": "Xiaohan Qin", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d82836a69ce099f4d6d6b", "name": "Sunan Zou", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d82836a69ce099f4d6d6c", "name": "Tuo Dai", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d82836a69ce099f4d6d6d", "name": "Xiaoming Shi", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d82836a69ce099f4d6d6e", "name": "Huaijin Wu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d82836a69ce099f4d6d6f", "name": "Yebin Yang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d82836a69ce099f4d6d70", "name": "Zhuo Xia", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d82836a69ce099f4d6d71", "name": "Shaofeng Zhang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d82836a69ce099f4d6d72", "name": "Lin Yao", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d82836a69ce099f4d6d73", "name": "Yuliang Liu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d82836a69ce099f4d6d74", "name": "Yu Cheng", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d82836a69ce099f4d6d75", "name": "Junchi Yan", "hidden": false}], "publishedAt": "2026-07-16T00:00:00.000Z", "submittedOnDailyAt": "2026-07-20T00:00:00.000Z", "title": "xHC: Expanded Hyper-Connections", "submittedOnDailyBy": {"_id": "656d8d4b1f8d9b618de91369", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/884dba9e56936241034b179d11a513b9.svg", "isPro": false, "fullname": "Xiangdong Zhang", "user": "aHapBean", "type": "user", "name": "aHapBean"}, "summary": "Hyper-Connections (HC) expand the residual stream of Transformers into N parallel streams, providing a form of memory scaling beyond model width and depth. Manifold-Constrained HC (mHC) stabilizes this formulation at scale. The large gains from N{=}1 to N{=}4 suggest residual-stream expansion as a promising scaling axis. However, existing HC-family methods typically stop at N{=}4. Our experiments reveal why: scaling mHC beyond this point yields diminishing performance gains and rapidly increasing training cost. We attribute this limitation to two bottlenecks: insufficient write-back information for an expanding number of streams and residual-mixing generation whose cost scales cubically with N. To address both bottlenecks, we propose xHC (Expanded Hyper-Connections), the first HC-family method to achieve meaningful expansion beyond N{=}4. xHC combines temporal feature augmentation for richer write-back with a sparse residual-stream architecture that updates only k=4 of the N=16 streams while retaining dense access to the full residual state. Across 18B and 28B MoE models, xHC delivers strong and consistent downstream improvements. On an 18B MoE model, xHC improves the average downstream score by 4.0 points over mHC, while adding only modest training FLOPs over the vanilla baseline. Scaling-law experiments show that the vanilla and mHC require 1.50times and 1.19times the compute of xHC, respectively, to reach the same loss. Practical large-N training also requires controlling memory traffic from the expanded residual state. We therefore introduce xHC-Flash, which reduces the per-sublayer memory traffic from 73.5C to 40C, comparable to the 34C required by mHC at N{=}4, while retaining the gains of full xHC. Together, xHC and xHC-Flash make large-N residual-stream expansion effective and practical for LLM pre-training.", "upvotes": 47, "discussionId": "6a5d82836a69ce099f4d6d76", "githubRepo": "https://github.com/aHapBean/xHC", "githubRepoAddedBy": "user", "githubStars": 38, "organization": {"_id": "68246a0a98117c02df67a547", "name": "rednote-hilab", "fullname": "rednote-hilab", "avatar": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/6807a1d6504547b3554b9c73/WgnnQDsz7FqnyTtv8mmRO.png"}, "summary_zh": "<ul>\n    <li>\u8d85\u8fde\u63a5\uff08HC\uff09\u5c06Transformer\u7684\u6b8b\u5dee\u6d41\u6269\u5c55\u4e3aN\u4e2a\u5e76\u884c\u6d41\uff0c\u63d0\u4f9b\u4e86\u4e00\u79cd\u8d85\u8d8a\u6a21\u578b\u5bbd\u5ea6\u548c\u6df1\u5ea6\u7684\u8bb0\u5fc6\u6269\u5c55\u65b9\u5f0f\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u6211\u4eec\u63d0\u51fa\u7684mHC\u65b9\u6cd5\u5728\u5927\u89c4\u6a21\u4e0b\u7a33\u5b9a\u4e86\u8fd9\u79cd\u6269\u5c55\uff0c\u4f46\u901a\u5e38\u53ea\u6269\u5c55\u5230N=4\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u8fdb\u4e00\u6b65\u6269\u5c55mHC\u4f1a\u5bfc\u81f4\u6027\u80fd\u63d0\u5347\u51cf\u5c11\u548c\u8bad\u7ec3\u6210\u672c\u8fc5\u901f\u589e\u52a0\uff0c\u4e3b\u8981\u662f\u7531\u4e8e\u4fe1\u606f\u56de\u5199\u4e0d\u8db3\u548c\u6b8b\u5dee\u6df7\u5408\u751f\u6210\u7684\u6210\u672c\u968fN\u7acb\u65b9\u589e\u957f\u3002</li>\n    <li>xHC\uff08\u6269\u5c55\u8d85\u8fde\u63a5\uff09\u662f\u7b2c\u4e00\u4e2a\u80fd\u6709\u6548\u6269\u5c55\u5230N>4\u7684HC\u65b9\u6cd5\uff0c\u901a\u8fc7\u4e30\u5bcc\u7684\u65f6\u95f4\u7279\u5f81\u589e\u5f3a\u548c\u7a00\u758f\u7684\u6b8b\u5dee\u6d41\u67b6\u6784\u6765\u89e3\u51b3\u8fd9\u4e9b\u74f6\u9888\u3002</li>\n    <li>xHC\u548c\u5176\u53d8\u4f53xHC-Flash\u4f7f\u5f97\u5927\u89c4\u6a21\u6b8b\u5dee\u6d41\u6269\u5c55\u5728\u5927\u578b\u8bed\u8a00\u6a21\u578b\u9884\u8bad\u7ec3\u4e2d\u66f4\u6709\u6548\u548c\u5b9e\u7528\u3002</li>\n</ul>", "summary_simple": "<ul>\n    <li>Hyper-Connections (HC) improve the memory capacity of Transformers by splitting their residual stream into multiple parallel streams.</li>\n    <li>Manifold-Constrained HC (mHC) helps stabilize this method but usually only scales up to 4 streams, leading to limited performance gains and higher training costs beyond that.</li>\n    <li>Two main issues hinder further scaling: not enough information for more streams and the increasing cost of mixing residuals as more streams are added.</li>\n    <li>xHC (Expanded Hyper-Connections) addresses these problems by using better feature augmentation and a sparse architecture that updates fewer streams, resulting in improved performance.</li>\n    <li>xHC and its optimized version, xHC-Flash, effectively allow for larger-scale training while managing memory use, showing significant improvements in model performance without excessive computational costs.</li>\n</ul>"}, "publishedAt": "2026-07-15T20:00:00.000Z", "title": "xHC: Expanded Hyper-Connections", "summary": "Hyper-Connections (HC) expand the residual stream of Transformers into N parallel streams, providing a form of memory scaling beyond model width and depth. Manifold-Constrained HC (mHC) stabilizes this formulation at scale. The large gains from N{=}1 to N{=}4 suggest residual-stream expansion as a promising scaling axis. However, existing HC-family methods typically stop at N{=}4. Our experiments reveal why: scaling mHC beyond this point yields diminishing performance gains and rapidly increasing training cost. We attribute this limitation to two bottlenecks: insufficient write-back information for an expanding number of streams and residual-mixing generation whose cost scales cubically with N. To address both bottlenecks, we propose xHC (Expanded Hyper-Connections), the first HC-family method to achieve meaningful expansion beyond N{=}4. xHC combines temporal feature augmentation for richer write-back with a sparse residual-stream architecture that updates only k=4 of the N=16 streams while retaining dense access to the full residual state. Across 18B and 28B MoE models, xHC delivers strong and consistent downstream improvements. On an 18B MoE model, xHC improves the average downstream score by 4.0 points over mHC, while adding only modest training FLOPs over the vanilla baseline. Scaling-law experiments show that the vanilla and mHC require 1.50times and 1.19times the compute of xHC, respectively, to reach the same loss. Practical large-N training also requires controlling memory traffic from the expanded residual state. We therefore introduce xHC-Flash, which reduces the per-sublayer memory traffic from 73.5C to 40C, comparable to the 34C required by mHC at N{=}4, while retaining the gains of full xHC. Together, xHC and xHC-Flash make large-N residual-stream expansion effective and practical for LLM pre-training.", "thumbnail": "https://cdn-thumbnails.huggingface.co/social-thumbnails/papers/2607.14530.png", "numComments": 1, "submittedBy": {"_id": "656d8d4b1f8d9b618de91369", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/884dba9e56936241034b179d11a513b9.svg", "fullname": "Xiangdong Zhang", "name": "aHapBean", "type": "user", "isPro": false, "isHf": false, "isHfAdmin": false, "isMod": false, "followerCount": 1, "isUserFollowing": false}, "organization": {"_id": "68246a0a98117c02df67a547", "name": "rednote-hilab", "fullname": "rednote-hilab", "avatar": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/6807a1d6504547b3554b9c73/WgnnQDsz7FqnyTtv8mmRO.png"}, "isAuthorParticipating": false}, {"paper": {"id": "2607.12625", "authors": [{"_id": "6a583e1769aa0f8878bddaf5", "name": "Yunxin Li", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a583e1769aa0f8878bddaf6", "name": "Jinchao Li", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a583e1769aa0f8878bddaf7", "name": "Shibo Su", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a583e1769aa0f8878bddaf8", "name": "Zhenran Xu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a583e1769aa0f8878bddaf9", "name": "Chenrui Zhao", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a583e1769aa0f8878bddafa", "name": "Tongshu Bian", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a583e1769aa0f8878bddafb", "name": "Xiaoman Liang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a583e1769aa0f8878bddafc", "name": "Meishan Zhang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a583e1769aa0f8878bddafd", "name": "Baotian Hu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a583e1769aa0f8878bddafe", "name": "Min Zhang", "hidden": false}], "mediaUrls": ["https://cdn-uploads.huggingface.co/production/uploads/62fdb01bc1588e1d4c6c1a7c/FuxFYDTH-NZ52ZP6zGPWy.png"], "publishedAt": "2026-07-15T00:00:00.000Z", "submittedOnDailyAt": "2026-07-16T00:00:00.000Z", "title": "KnowAct-GUIClaw: Know Deeply, Act Perfectly, Personal GUI Assistant with Self-Evolving Memory and Skill", "submittedOnDailyBy": {"_id": "62fdb01bc1588e1d4c6c1a7c", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/bd03085995b1c34e0ac8a845cf2c4e83.svg", "isPro": false, "fullname": "Yunxin Li", "user": "YunxinLi", "type": "user", "name": "YunxinLi"}, "summary": "OpenClaw has emerged as a leading agent framework for complex task automation, yet it faces insufficient cross-platform GUI interaction support and a well-built self-evolution mechanism. These flaws limit its adaptation to diverse device ecosystems and prevent performance improvements through continuous learning from execution experience. To resolve these issues, we propose the Know Deeply, Act Perfectly paradigm for personal assistants, which holds that accumulated user interaction and task-running experience directly improve execution accuracy and efficiency, unifying cognitive comprehension and operational execution. Based on this paradigm, we introduce KnowAct-GUIClaw, a novel Know-Route-Act-Reflect framework designed to address OpenClaw's GUI manipulation deficits and break through its cross-platform and recursive self-improvement constraints. First, the host agent leverages accumulated interaction experience and task-relevant knowledge for long-horizon task decomposition and allocation (Know). Second, a pluggable GUI subagent with an experience-attributable memory system (Know) and self-evolving skill library (Act), enabling seamless cross-platform migration and fast-path integration. Especially, this framework continuously stores user profiles and feedback to improve the accuracy of task decomposition and tool calls. Extensive experiments across Android, iOS, HarmonyOS and Windows show that KnowAct-GUIClaw achieves superior efficiency, accuracy and cross-platform adaptability. Especially, the GUIClaw with open-source Kimi-2.6 models achieves the best performance (64.1%) on the long-horizon MobileWorld benchmark, beating all agentical frameworks and closed-source agentical models, e.g., Seed-2.0-Pro and GPT-5.5. Additionally, the knowledgeable memory and execution skills supported by our framework are transferable across diverse base models, improving by 8.5% with Kimi-2.6.", "upvotes": 44, "discussionId": "6a583e1769aa0f8878bddaff", "projectPage": "https://shibosusu.github.io/KnowAct-GUIClaw/", "githubRepo": "https://github.com/HITsz-TMG/KnowAct", "githubRepoAddedBy": "user", "githubStars": 45, "organization": {"_id": "629867d7f2bf8bd3e468706e", "name": "HIT-TMG", "fullname": "Lychee Team", "avatar": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/64b7679a08e2452d18db9a9e/uk4QHGGYqcrEHmiweTFWy.png"}, "summary_zh": "<ul>\n    <li>OpenClaw\u662f\u4e00\u4e2a\u590d\u6742\u4efb\u52a1\u81ea\u52a8\u5316\u7684\u4ee3\u7406\u6846\u67b6\uff0c\u4f46\u5728\u8de8\u5e73\u53f0GUI\u4ea4\u4e92\u548c\u81ea\u6211\u8fdb\u5316\u673a\u5236\u65b9\u9762\u5b58\u5728\u4e0d\u8db3\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u4e3a\u4e86\u89e3\u51b3\u8fd9\u4e9b\u95ee\u9898\uff0c\u63d0\u51fa\u4e86\u201cKnow Deeply, Act Perfectly\u201d\u7406\u5ff5\uff0c\u5f3a\u8c03\u7528\u6237\u4ea4\u4e92\u548c\u4efb\u52a1\u6267\u884c\u7ecf\u9a8c\u7684\u79ef\u7d2f\u53ef\u4ee5\u63d0\u9ad8\u6267\u884c\u51c6\u786e\u6027\u548c\u6548\u7387\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u5f15\u5165\u4e86KnowAct-GUIClaw\u6846\u67b6\uff0c\u65e8\u5728\u6539\u5584OpenClaw\u7684GUI\u64cd\u4f5c\u548c\u81ea\u6211\u63d0\u5347\u80fd\u529b\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u901a\u8fc7\u79ef\u7d2f\u7684\u4ea4\u4e92\u7ecf\u9a8c\u548c\u4efb\u52a1\u76f8\u5173\u77e5\u8bc6\uff0c\u6846\u67b6\u80fd\u8fdb\u884c\u957f\u8fdc\u4efb\u52a1\u7684\u5206\u89e3\u548c\u5206\u914d\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u5b9e\u9a8c\u8868\u660e\uff0cKnowAct-GUIClaw\u5728Android\u3001iOS\u3001HarmonyOS\u548cWindows\u4e0a\u8868\u73b0\u51fa\u8272\uff0c\u7279\u522b\u662f\u5728MobileWorld\u57fa\u51c6\u6d4b\u8bd5\u4e2d\u53d6\u5f97\u4e86\u6700\u4f73\u6027\u80fd\u3002</li>\n</ul>", "summary_simple": "<ul>\n    <li>OpenClaw is a framework for automating complex tasks but struggles with cross-platform GUI support and self-improvement.</li>\n    <li>The proposed solution, KnowAct-GUIClaw, helps enhance execution accuracy by learning from user interactions and experiences.</li>\n    <li>This framework allows for better task management and GUI manipulation across different platforms like Android, iOS, and Windows.</li>\n    <li>Experiments show KnowAct-GUIClaw outperforms other frameworks in terms of efficiency and accuracy.</li>\n    <li>The improvement in performance is notable, especially with the open-source Kimi-2.6 model, surpassing other agents significantly.</li>\n</ul>"}, "publishedAt": "2026-07-14T20:00:00.000Z", "title": "KnowAct-GUIClaw: Know Deeply, Act Perfectly, Personal GUI Assistant with Self-Evolving Memory and Skill", "summary": "OpenClaw has emerged as a leading agent framework for complex task automation, yet it faces insufficient cross-platform GUI interaction support and a well-built self-evolution mechanism. These flaws limit its adaptation to diverse device ecosystems and prevent performance improvements through continuous learning from execution experience. To resolve these issues, we propose the Know Deeply, Act Perfectly paradigm for personal assistants, which holds that accumulated user interaction and task-running experience directly improve execution accuracy and efficiency, unifying cognitive comprehension and operational execution. Based on this paradigm, we introduce KnowAct-GUIClaw, a novel Know-Route-Act-Reflect framework designed to address OpenClaw's GUI manipulation deficits and break through its cross-platform and recursive self-improvement constraints. First, the host agent leverages accumulated interaction experience and task-relevant knowledge for long-horizon task decomposition and allocation (Know). Second, a pluggable GUI subagent with an experience-attributable memory system (Know) and self-evolving skill library (Act), enabling seamless cross-platform migration and fast-path integration. Especially, this framework continuously stores user profiles and feedback to improve the accuracy of task decomposition and tool calls. Extensive experiments across Android, iOS, HarmonyOS and Windows show that KnowAct-GUIClaw achieves superior efficiency, accuracy and cross-platform adaptability. Especially, the GUIClaw with open-source Kimi-2.6 models achieves the best performance (64.1%) on the long-horizon MobileWorld benchmark, beating all agentical frameworks and closed-source agentical models, e.g., Seed-2.0-Pro and GPT-5.5. Additionally, the knowledgeable memory and execution skills supported by our framework are transferable across diverse base models, improving by 8.5% with Kimi-2.6.", "mediaUrls": ["https://cdn-uploads.huggingface.co/production/uploads/62fdb01bc1588e1d4c6c1a7c/FuxFYDTH-NZ52ZP6zGPWy.png"], "thumbnail": "https://cdn-thumbnails.huggingface.co/social-thumbnails/papers/2607.12625.png", "numComments": 1, "submittedBy": {"_id": "62fdb01bc1588e1d4c6c1a7c", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/bd03085995b1c34e0ac8a845cf2c4e83.svg", "fullname": "Yunxin Li", "name": "YunxinLi", "type": "user", "isPro": false, "isHf": false, "isHfAdmin": false, "isMod": false, "followerCount": 12, "isUserFollowing": false}, "organization": {"_id": "629867d7f2bf8bd3e468706e", "name": "HIT-TMG", "fullname": "Lychee Team", "avatar": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/64b7679a08e2452d18db9a9e/uk4QHGGYqcrEHmiweTFWy.png"}, "isAuthorParticipating": false}, {"paper": {"id": "2607.15314", "authors": [{"_id": "6a5d83ee6a69ce099f4d6d91", "name": "actAVA AI", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d83ee6a69ce099f4d6d93", "name": "Haolin Chen", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d83ee6a69ce099f4d6d94", "name": "Leon Qi", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d83ee6a69ce099f4d6d95", "name": "Steve Brown", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d83ee6a69ce099f4d6d96", "name": "Deon Metelski", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d83ee6a69ce099f4d6d97", "name": "Tao Xia", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d83ee6a69ce099f4d6d98", "name": "Joonyul Lee", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d83ee6a69ce099f4d6d99", "name": "Qixuan Wang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d83ee6a69ce099f4d6d9a", "name": "Kevin Riley", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d83ee6a69ce099f4d6d9b", "name": "Frank Wang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5d83ee6a69ce099f4d6d9c", "user": {"_id": "632cdea254e2c512c8f95b12", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/a6d06cdd75861ae7d589f1343d81a5c5.svg", "isPro": false, "fullname": "Weiran Yao", "user": "weirayao", "type": "user", "name": "weirayao"}, "name": "Weiran Yao", "status": "claimed_verified", "statusLastChangedAt": "2026-07-20T16:06:02.233Z", "hidden": false}], "publishedAt": "2026-07-15T00:00:00.000Z", "submittedOnDailyAt": "2026-07-20T00:00:00.000Z", "title": "Cura 1T: Specialized Model for Agentic Healthcare", "submittedOnDailyBy": {"_id": "6039478ab3ecf716b1a5fd4d", "avatarUrl": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/6039478ab3ecf716b1a5fd4d/_Thy4E7taiSYBLKxEKJbT.jpeg", "isPro": true, "fullname": "taesiri", "user": "taesiri", "type": "user", "name": "taesiri"}, "summary": "Healthcare spans high-stakes communication, expert reasoning, and workflow execution, yet specialized LLMs that cover these use cases together remain limited. A healthcare model must handle patient consultation, clinical reasoning over text and images, interactive diagnosis, and electronic health record (EHR) tool use. These capabilities fail in different ways, and a narrow update for one task can degrade another. We present Cura 1T, a healthcare-specialized LLM trained through a human-gated self-evolution loop. In each evolution round, a training agent plans a target capability, trains the model, evaluates benchmark trajectories, and refines the data mixture from observed failures. This data-centered loop improves the model through targeted synthetic and curated examples rather than a single generic medical-data update. Across the healthcare evaluation suite, Cura 1T ranks at or near the top among frontier baselines, while remaining competitive on out-of-domain reasoning and agentic benchmarks.", "upvotes": 43, "discussionId": "6a5d83ee6a69ce099f4d6d9d", "projectPage": "https://actava.ai/cura", "githubRepo": "https://github.com/actava-ai/Cura", "githubRepoAddedBy": "user", "githubStars": 17, "summary_zh": "<ul>\n    <li>\u533b\u7597\u9886\u57df\u7684\u6c9f\u901a\u3001\u63a8\u7406\u548c\u5de5\u4f5c\u6d41\u7a0b\u6267\u884c\u975e\u5e38\u91cd\u8981\uff0c\u4f46\u4e13\u95e8\u7684\u8bed\u8a00\u6a21\u578b\uff08LLM\uff09\u4ecd\u7136\u6709\u9650\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u533b\u7597\u6a21\u578b\u9700\u8981\u5904\u7406\u60a3\u8005\u54a8\u8be2\u3001\u4e34\u5e8a\u63a8\u7406\u3001\u4e92\u52a8\u8bca\u65ad\u548c\u7535\u5b50\u5065\u5eb7\u8bb0\u5f55\u7b49\u4efb\u52a1\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u9488\u5bf9\u4e00\u4e2a\u4efb\u52a1\u7684\u66f4\u65b0\u53ef\u80fd\u4f1a\u5f71\u54cd\u5176\u4ed6\u4efb\u52a1\u7684\u8868\u73b0\u3002</li>\n    <li>Cura 1T\u662f\u4e00\u79cd\u4e13\u4e3a\u533b\u7597\u8bbe\u8ba1\u7684LLM\uff0c\u901a\u8fc7\u4eba\u7c7b\u5f15\u5bfc\u7684\u81ea\u6211\u8fdb\u5316\u5faa\u73af\u8fdb\u884c\u8bad\u7ec3\u3002</li>\n    <li>Cura 1T\u5728\u533b\u7597\u8bc4\u4f30\u4e2d\u8868\u73b0\u4f18\u5f02\uff0c\u5e76\u5728\u4e0d\u540c\u9886\u57df\u7684\u63a8\u7406\u548c\u4ee3\u7406\u57fa\u51c6\u4e0a\u4e5f\u4fdd\u6301\u7ade\u4e89\u529b\u3002</li>\n</ul>", "summary_simple": "<ul>\n    <li>Cura 1T is a specialized language model for healthcare that combines patient consultation, clinical reasoning, diagnosis, and EHR tool use.</li>\n    <li>Current healthcare models struggle with multiple tasks, and improving one area can negatively impact others.</li>\n    <li>The model improves through a unique training process that focuses on specific capabilities and learns from past mistakes.</li>\n    <li>Cura 1T uses targeted examples instead of just general medical data for better training results.</li>\n    <li>In evaluations, Cura 1T performs at or near the top compared to other leading models and is effective in various reasoning tasks.</li>\n</ul>"}, "publishedAt": "2026-07-14T20:00:00.000Z", "title": "Cura 1T: Specialized Model for Agentic Healthcare", "summary": "Healthcare spans high-stakes communication, expert reasoning, and workflow execution, yet specialized LLMs that cover these use cases together remain limited. A healthcare model must handle patient consultation, clinical reasoning over text and images, interactive diagnosis, and electronic health record (EHR) tool use. These capabilities fail in different ways, and a narrow update for one task can degrade another. We present Cura 1T, a healthcare-specialized LLM trained through a human-gated self-evolution loop. In each evolution round, a training agent plans a target capability, trains the model, evaluates benchmark trajectories, and refines the data mixture from observed failures. This data-centered loop improves the model through targeted synthetic and curated examples rather than a single generic medical-data update. Across the healthcare evaluation suite, Cura 1T ranks at or near the top among frontier baselines, while remaining competitive on out-of-domain reasoning and agentic benchmarks.", "thumbnail": "https://cdn-thumbnails.huggingface.co/social-thumbnails/papers/2607.15314.png", "numComments": 4, "submittedBy": {"_id": "6039478ab3ecf716b1a5fd4d", "avatarUrl": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/6039478ab3ecf716b1a5fd4d/_Thy4E7taiSYBLKxEKJbT.jpeg", "fullname": "taesiri", "name": "taesiri", "type": "user", "isPro": true, "isHf": false, "isHfAdmin": false, "isMod": false, "followerCount": 338, "isUserFollowing": false}, "isAuthorParticipating": true}, {"paper": {"id": "2607.13639", "authors": [{"_id": "6a5840ab69aa0f8878bddb06", "name": "Shiyin Lu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5840ab69aa0f8878bddb07", "name": "Yinglun Li", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5840ab69aa0f8878bddb08", "name": "Yu Xia", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5840ab69aa0f8878bddb09", "name": "Yuhui Chen", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5840ab69aa0f8878bddb0a", "name": "An-Yang Ji", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5840ab69aa0f8878bddb0b", "name": "Jun-Peng Jiang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5840ab69aa0f8878bddb0c", "name": "Qing-Guo Chen", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5840ab69aa0f8878bddb0d", "name": "Jianshan Zhao", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5840ab69aa0f8878bddb0e", "name": "En Lin", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5840ab69aa0f8878bddb0f", "name": "Haijun Li", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5840ab69aa0f8878bddb10", "name": "Cheng Qin", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5840ab69aa0f8878bddb11", "name": "Zhao Xu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5840ab69aa0f8878bddb12", "name": "Weihua Luo", "hidden": false}], "publishedAt": "2026-07-15T00:00:00.000Z", "submittedOnDailyAt": "2026-07-16T00:00:00.000Z", "title": "OvisOCR2 Technical Report", "submittedOnDailyBy": {"_id": "6039478ab3ecf716b1a5fd4d", "avatarUrl": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/6039478ab3ecf716b1a5fd4d/_Thy4E7taiSYBLKxEKJbT.jpeg", "isPro": true, "fullname": "taesiri", "user": "taesiri", "type": "user", "name": "taesiri"}, "summary": "We introduce OvisOCR2, a 0.8B document parsing model. OvisOCR2 is designed as an end-to-end parser: given a document page image, it generates a Markdown representation in natural reading order, covering text, formulas, tables, and visual regions. We build a data engine that combines filtered real-document annotations with synthetic pages whose rendered images and Markdown targets are derived from the same HTML source. The training recipe includes supervised fine-tuning, reinforcement learning on a 4B branch with a multi-component reward design, on-policy distillation into the 0.8B model, and model fusion. On OmniDocBench v1.6, OvisOCR2 achieves a state-of-the-art overall score of 96.58, placing an end-to-end model at the top of this leaderboard previously dominated by pipeline methods and highlighting the potential of end-to-end document parsing. On PureDocBench, OvisOCR2 also achieves the highest Avg3 score of 75.06. Beyond these two public benchmarks, we evaluate OvisOCR2 on an in-house benchmark designed to cover a broader set of long-tail and challenging scenarios. OvisOCR2 obtains the best overall performance among the compared methods, providing further evidence of its generalization and robustness. OvisOCR2 is available at https://huggingface.co/ATH-MaaS/OvisOCR2.", "upvotes": 42, "discussionId": "6a5840ac69aa0f8878bddb13", "summary_zh": "<ul>\n    <li>OvisOCR2\u662f\u4e00\u4e2a0.8\u4ebf\u53c2\u6570\u7684\u6587\u6863\u89e3\u6790\u6a21\u578b\uff0c\u80fd\u591f\u5c06\u6587\u6863\u9875\u9762\u56fe\u50cf\u8f6c\u5316\u4e3a\u81ea\u7136\u9605\u8bfb\u987a\u5e8f\u7684Markdown\u683c\u5f0f\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u8be5\u6a21\u578b\u4f7f\u7528\u771f\u5b9e\u6587\u6863\u6ce8\u91ca\u548c\u5408\u6210\u9875\u9762\u7684\u7ed3\u5408\u6570\u636e\u5f15\u64ce\u8fdb\u884c\u8bad\u7ec3\uff0c\u5e76\u901a\u8fc7\u76d1\u7763\u5fae\u8c03\u548c\u5f3a\u5316\u5b66\u4e60\u4f18\u5316\u6027\u80fd\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u5728OmniDocBench v1.6\u4e0a\uff0cOvisOCR2\u83b7\u5f97\u4e8696.58\u7684\u6700\u9ad8\u5206\uff0c\u8d85\u8d8a\u4e86\u4ee5\u5f80\u7684\u7ba1\u9053\u65b9\u6cd5\uff0c\u5c55\u793a\u4e86\u7aef\u5230\u7aef\u6587\u6863\u89e3\u6790\u7684\u6f5c\u529b\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u5728PureDocBench\u4e0a\uff0cOvisOCR2\u7684Avg3\u5f97\u5206\u4e5f\u8fbe\u5230\u4e8675.06\uff0c\u4e3a\u6240\u6709\u6bd4\u8f83\u65b9\u6cd5\u4e2d\u7684\u6700\u9ad8\u5206\u3002</li>\n    <li>OvisOCR2\u5728\u5185\u90e8\u57fa\u51c6\u6d4b\u8bd5\u4e2d\u8868\u73b0\u4f18\u5f02\uff0c\u663e\u793a\u51fa\u5176\u5e7f\u6cdb\u7684\u6cdb\u5316\u80fd\u529b\u548c\u7a33\u5065\u6027\u3002</li>\n</ul>", "summary_simple": "<ul>\n    <li>OvisOCR2 is a new document parsing model that converts document images into Markdown format.</li>\n    <li>It can process text, formulas, tables, and images in a natural reading order.</li>\n    <li>The model is trained using a mix of real and synthetic document data and employs advanced training techniques.</li>\n    <li>OvisOCR2 achieves top scores in major benchmarks, outperforming previous models that used separate processing steps.</li>\n    <li>The model shows strong performance in various challenging scenarios and is available for use online.</li>\n</ul>"}, "publishedAt": "2026-07-14T20:00:00.000Z", "title": "OvisOCR2 Technical Report", "summary": "We introduce OvisOCR2, a 0.8B document parsing model. OvisOCR2 is designed as an end-to-end parser: given a document page image, it generates a Markdown representation in natural reading order, covering text, formulas, tables, and visual regions. We build a data engine that combines filtered real-document annotations with synthetic pages whose rendered images and Markdown targets are derived from the same HTML source. The training recipe includes supervised fine-tuning, reinforcement learning on a 4B branch with a multi-component reward design, on-policy distillation into the 0.8B model, and model fusion. On OmniDocBench v1.6, OvisOCR2 achieves a state-of-the-art overall score of 96.58, placing an end-to-end model at the top of this leaderboard previously dominated by pipeline methods and highlighting the potential of end-to-end document parsing. On PureDocBench, OvisOCR2 also achieves the highest Avg3 score of 75.06. Beyond these two public benchmarks, we evaluate OvisOCR2 on an in-house benchmark designed to cover a broader set of long-tail and challenging scenarios. OvisOCR2 obtains the best overall performance among the compared methods, providing further evidence of its generalization and robustness. OvisOCR2 is available at https://huggingface.co/ATH-MaaS/OvisOCR2.", "thumbnail": "https://cdn-thumbnails.huggingface.co/social-thumbnails/papers/2607.13639.png", "numComments": 0, "submittedBy": {"_id": "6039478ab3ecf716b1a5fd4d", "avatarUrl": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/6039478ab3ecf716b1a5fd4d/_Thy4E7taiSYBLKxEKJbT.jpeg", "fullname": "taesiri", "name": "taesiri", "type": "user", "isPro": true, "isHf": false, "isHfAdmin": false, "isMod": false, "followerCount": 335, "isUserFollowing": false}, "isAuthorParticipating": false}],
    "month": [{"paper": {"id": "2606.30534", "authors": [{"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e917", "user": {"_id": "68c429ef60f075cc46cc9cff", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/21d277a1b46eabc967121a111e270cdd.svg", "isPro": false, "fullname": "yh-wang", "user": "yh-wang", "type": "user", "name": "yh-wang"}, "name": "Yihao Wang", "status": "claimed_verified", "statusLastChangedAt": "2026-07-01T09:49:27.650Z", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e918", "user": {"_id": "668f5478b3991ac0c3fc9c2f", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/a775853d3b88e7b1c8494ca837b5495c.svg", "isPro": false, "fullname": "yuhengji", "user": "yuheng2000", "type": "user", "name": "yuheng2000"}, "name": "Yuheng Ji", "status": "claimed_verified", "statusLastChangedAt": "2026-07-01T09:49:25.392Z", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e919", "user": {"_id": "668fa476cbcaf7ab0e4c58b3", "avatarUrl": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/668fa476cbcaf7ab0e4c58b3/F5Jj-nPCjU6uxZyfkY3qw.jpeg", "isPro": false, "fullname": "Mingyu Cao", "user": "cmyopu", "type": "user", "name": "cmyopu"}, "name": "Mingyu Cao", "status": "claimed_verified", "statusLastChangedAt": "2026-07-01T08:47:12.327Z", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e91a", "user": {"_id": "671fa0de0a34a05602094909", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/e35890e1f71a8c3f4e33b35a027e180a.svg", "isPro": false, "fullname": "Yanqing Shen", "user": "syq1105", "type": "user", "name": "syq1105"}, "name": "Yanqing Shen", "status": "claimed_verified", "statusLastChangedAt": "2026-07-01T08:47:16.531Z", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e91b", "name": "Runze Xiao", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e91c", "user": {"_id": "67ecd5dc6b33c72fba1fc70f", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/27ff8fb1534f1d277ae03e8adc64ffba.svg", "isPro": false, "fullname": "huaihai lyu", "user": "HuaihaiLyu", "type": "user", "name": "HuaihaiLyu"}, "name": "Huaihai Lyu", "status": "claimed_verified", "statusLastChangedAt": "2026-07-01T08:47:10.262Z", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e91d", "user": {"_id": "643613fdaaef013d1af18717", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/b4689886eaf2103d8e92f90ea5e5bc5e.svg", "isPro": false, "fullname": "Senwei Xie", "user": "jsw19", "type": "user", "name": "jsw19"}, "name": "Senwei Xie", "status": "claimed_verified", "statusLastChangedAt": "2026-07-01T09:49:51.559Z", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e91e", "name": "Euan Liu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e91f", "name": "Klara Tian", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e920", "name": "Tianfeng Long", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e921", "name": "Yichi Zhang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e922", "name": "Zhengliang Cai", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e923", "name": "Ruike Chen", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e924", "name": "Jifan Zhao", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e925", "name": "Ruochuan Shi", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e926", "user": {"_id": "65fce52cb6fa00949682d41b", "avatarUrl": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/65fce52cb6fa00949682d41b/RZ6J1Ovix-jJW9KSiWcEk.jpeg", "isPro": false, "fullname": "Zihan Tang", "user": "tzh21", "type": "user", "name": "tzh21"}, "name": "Zihan Tang", "status": "claimed_verified", "statusLastChangedAt": "2026-07-01T08:47:14.193Z", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e927", "name": "Jing Lyu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e928", "name": "Wenxing Tan", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e929", "name": "Ningbo Zhang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e92a", "name": "Yangtao Hu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e92b", "name": "Yuming Gao", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e92c", "name": "Xiansheng Chen", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e92d", "name": "Junkai Zhao", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e92e", "name": "Congsheng Xu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e92f", "name": "Boan Zhu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e930", "name": "Ziqi Wang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e931", "name": "Yupu Feng", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e932", "name": "Qiongqiong Zhang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e933", "name": "Yingli Zhao", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e934", "name": "Yulong Ao", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e935", "name": "Shaoxuan Xie", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e936", "name": "You Liu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e937", "name": "Guocai Yao", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e938", "name": "Leiduo Zhang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e939", "name": "Xiaodan Liu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e93a", "name": "Yunyan Zhang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e93b", "name": "Yance Jiao", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e93c", "name": "Xinyan Yang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e93d", "name": "Jiaxing Wei", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e93e", "name": "Xu Liu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e93f", "name": "Tengfei Pan", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e940", "name": "Shaokai Nie", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e941", "name": "Chunlei Men", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e942", "name": "Sen Cui", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e943", "name": "Xiaojie Jin", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e944", "name": "Hongyang Li", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e945", "name": "Jianlan Luo", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e946", "name": "Yao Mu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e947", "name": "Yunchao Wei", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e948", "name": "Jun Yan", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e949", "name": "Hang Zhao", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e94a", "name": "Xiaolong Zheng", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e94b", "name": "Jiaming Li", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e94c", "name": "Yonghua Lin", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e94d", "name": "Tiejun Huang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e94e", "name": "Zhongyuan Wang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e94f", "name": "Pengwei Wang", "hidden": false}], "mediaUrls": ["https://cdn-uploads.huggingface.co/production/uploads/68c429ef60f075cc46cc9cff/ceZCPH1jShoRORZCEPALp.mp4"], "publishedAt": "2026-06-29T00:00:00.000Z", "submittedOnDailyAt": "2026-07-01T00:00:00.000Z", "title": "Orca: The World is in Your Mind", "submittedOnDailyBy": {"_id": "68c429ef60f075cc46cc9cff", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/21d277a1b46eabc967121a111e270cdd.svg", "isPro": false, "fullname": "yh-wang", "user": "yh-wang", "type": "user", "name": "yh-wang"}, "summary": "We introduce Orca, an initial instantiation of a general world foundation model. Orca learns a unified world latent space from multimodal world signals and exposes it through multimodal readout interfaces. Rather than optimizing isolated next-token, next-frame, or next-action prediction, we are centered on Next-State-Prediction modeling, offering a unified state-transition modeling route toward understanding, predicting, and acting upon the world. Orca learns through two complementary paradigms: unconscious learning captures dense natural state transitions from continuous videos, and conscious learning models sparse meaningful state transitions by language-described events and VQA supervision. For pre-training, we construct a large-scale world-learning inventory data, including 125K hours of video data and 160M event annotations. After pre-training, Orca learns a unified world latent space. To examine whether the learned latent supports downstream, we evaluate it by three representative downstream readouts: text generation, image prediction, and embodied action generation. Orca's backbone is frozen, and only the lightweight modality-specific decoders are trainable. Experiments show the scalability of the proposed paradigm and verify that stronger world latent enables stronger downstream readouts. Orca outperforms similar-sized specialized baselines. These results show that Orca, as a general world foundation model, presents a promising approach to understanding, predicting, and acting upon the world. Finally, we discuss the current limitations, aiming to provide useful insights and inspiration for the community.", "upvotes": 176, "discussionId": "6a4334fd763f63ca3757e950", "projectPage": "https://orca-wm.github.io/", "ai_summary": "Orca establishes a unified world latent space through next-state-prediction modeling using multimodal data and demonstrates superior performance in downstream tasks compared to specialized baselines.", "ai_keywords": ["world foundation model", "world latent space", "multimodal readout interfaces", "next-state-prediction modeling", "unconscious learning", "conscious learning", "world-learning inventory data", "embodied action generation", "downstream readouts", "modality-specific decoders"], "ai_summary_model": "Qwen/Qwen2.5-Coder-32B-Instruct", "summary_zh": "<ul>\n    <li>Orca\u662f\u4e00\u4e2a\u901a\u7528\u7684\u4e16\u754c\u57fa\u7840\u6a21\u578b\uff0c\u80fd\u591f\u4ece\u591a\u79cd\u4fe1\u53f7\u4e2d\u5b66\u4e60\u7edf\u4e00\u7684\u4e16\u754c\u6f5c\u5728\u7a7a\u95f4\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u5b83\u7684\u91cd\u70b9\u5728\u4e8e\u9884\u6d4b\u4e0b\u4e00\u4e2a\u72b6\u6001\uff0c\u800c\u4e0d\u662f\u5355\u72ec\u7684\u4e0b\u4e00\u4e2a\u8bcd\u3001\u5e27\u6216\u52a8\u4f5c\u3002</li>\n    <li>Orca\u901a\u8fc7\u65e0\u610f\u8bc6\u5b66\u4e60\u548c\u6709\u610f\u8bc6\u5b66\u4e60\u4e24\u79cd\u65b9\u5f0f\u8fdb\u884c\u5b66\u4e60\uff0c\u524d\u8005\u5229\u7528\u8fde\u7eed\u89c6\u9891\u6355\u6349\u81ea\u7136\u72b6\u6001\u8f6c\u53d8\uff0c\u540e\u8005\u901a\u8fc7\u8bed\u8a00\u4e8b\u4ef6\u548c\u89c6\u89c9\u95ee\u7b54\u6765\u5efa\u6a21\u6709\u610f\u4e49\u7684\u72b6\u6001\u8f6c\u53d8\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u5728\u9884\u8bad\u7ec3\u9636\u6bb5\uff0cOrca\u4f7f\u7528\u4e86125K\u5c0f\u65f6\u7684\u89c6\u9891\u6570\u636e\u548c160M\u4e8b\u4ef6\u6ce8\u91ca\uff0c\u6784\u5efa\u4e86\u5927\u578b\u7684\u4e16\u754c\u5b66\u4e60\u6570\u636e\u96c6\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u5b9e\u9a8c\u8868\u660e\uff0cOrca\u5728\u6587\u672c\u751f\u6210\u3001\u56fe\u50cf\u9884\u6d4b\u548c\u52a8\u4f5c\u751f\u6210\u7b49\u4efb\u52a1\u4e0a\u8868\u73b0\u4f18\u4e8e\u540c\u7c7b\u4e13\u95e8\u6a21\u578b\uff0c\u8bc1\u660e\u4e86\u5176\u4f5c\u4e3a\u901a\u7528\u4e16\u754c\u57fa\u7840\u6a21\u578b\u7684\u6f5c\u529b\u3002</li>\n</ul>", "summary_simple": "<ul>\n    <li>Orca is a new model that learns to understand the world by combining different types of data, like videos and language.</li>\n    <li>Instead of just predicting what comes next, Orca focuses on predicting how states change over time.</li>\n    <li>It learns in two ways: by observing many continuous videos (unconscious learning) and by understanding important events described in language (conscious learning).</li>\n    <li>Orca is trained on a large dataset, which includes 125,000 hours of video and 160 million event descriptions.</li>\n    <li>It shows strong performance in generating text, predicting images, and generating actions, outperforming other similar models.</li>\n</ul>"}, "publishedAt": "2026-06-28T20:00:00.000Z", "title": "Orca: The World is in Your Mind", "summary": "We introduce Orca, an initial instantiation of a general world foundation model. Orca learns a unified world latent space from multimodal world signals and exposes it through multimodal readout interfaces. Rather than optimizing isolated next-token, next-frame, or next-action prediction, we are centered on Next-State-Prediction modeling, offering a unified state-transition modeling route toward understanding, predicting, and acting upon the world. Orca learns through two complementary paradigms: unconscious learning captures dense natural state transitions from continuous videos, and conscious learning models sparse meaningful state transitions by language-described events and VQA supervision. For pre-training, we construct a large-scale world-learning inventory data, including 125K hours of video data and 160M event annotations. After pre-training, Orca learns a unified world latent space. To examine whether the learned latent supports downstream, we evaluate it by three representative downstream readouts: text generation, image prediction, and embodied action generation. Orca's backbone is frozen, and only the lightweight modality-specific decoders are trainable. Experiments show the scalability of the proposed paradigm and verify that stronger world latent enables stronger downstream readouts. Orca outperforms similar-sized specialized baselines. These results show that Orca, as a general world foundation model, presents a promising approach to understanding, predicting, and acting upon the world. Finally, we discuss the current limitations, aiming to provide useful insights and inspiration for the community.", "mediaUrls": ["https://cdn-uploads.huggingface.co/production/uploads/68c429ef60f075cc46cc9cff/ceZCPH1jShoRORZCEPALp.mp4"], "thumbnail": "https://cdn-thumbnails.huggingface.co/social-thumbnails/papers/2606.30534.png", "numComments": 5, "submittedBy": {"_id": "68c429ef60f075cc46cc9cff", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/21d277a1b46eabc967121a111e270cdd.svg", "fullname": "yh-wang", "name": "yh-wang", "type": "user", "isPro": false, "isHf": false, "isHfAdmin": false, "isMod": false, "followerCount": 3, "isUserFollowing": false}, "isAuthorParticipating": true}, {"paper": {"id": "2607.13285", "authors": [{"_id": "6a58413769aa0f8878bddb16", "name": "Ruhan Wang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a58413769aa0f8878bddb17", "name": "Yucheng Shi", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a58413769aa0f8878bddb18", "name": "Zongxia Li", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a58413769aa0f8878bddb19", "name": "Zhongzhi Li", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a58413769aa0f8878bddb1a", "name": "Yue Yu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a58413769aa0f8878bddb1b", "name": "Junyao Yang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a58413769aa0f8878bddb1c", "name": "Kishan Panaganti", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a58413769aa0f8878bddb1d", "name": "Haitao Mi", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a58413769aa0f8878bddb1e", "name": "Dongruo Zhou", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a58413769aa0f8878bddb1f", "name": "Leoweiliang", "hidden": false}], "publishedAt": "2026-07-14T00:00:00.000Z", "submittedOnDailyAt": "2026-07-16T00:00:00.000Z", "title": "Harness Handbook: Making Evolving Agent Harnesses Readable,Navigable, and Editable", "submittedOnDailyBy": {"_id": "6039478ab3ecf716b1a5fd4d", "avatarUrl": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/6039478ab3ecf716b1a5fd4d/_Thy4E7taiSYBLKxEKJbT.jpeg", "isPro": true, "fullname": "taesiri", "user": "taesiri", "type": "user", "name": "taesiri"}, "summary": "The capability of a modern AI agent depends not only on its foundation model but also on its harness, which constructs prompts, manages state, invokes tools, and coordinates execution. As models, APIs, environments, and requirements evolve, the harness must be continually modified. Before such a change can be made, a developer or coding agent must identify all code locations that implement the target behavior. This is difficult because production harnesses are large, tightly coupled, and behaviorally distributed, while modification requests describe what the system should do and repositories are organized by files and modules. Code search, repository indexing, and long-context processing ease inspection, but still leave this behavior-to-code mapping to be recovered by hand. Behavior localization is therefore a central bottleneck in harness evolution. We introduce the Harness Handbook, a behavior-centric representation synthesized automatically from a harness codebase via static analysis and LLM-assisted structuring, linking each behavior to its corresponding source. We also introduce Behavior-Guided Progressive Disclosure (BGPD), which guides agents from high-level behaviors to relevant implementation details and verifies candidate locations against the current source. On diverse modification requests from two open-source harnesses, Handbook-Assisted planning improves behavior localization and edit-plan quality while using fewer planner tokens, with the largest gains on scattered sites, rarely executed paths, and cross-module interactions. Evolving complex agentic systems thus depends not only on generating edits, but also on determining where those edits should be made.", "upvotes": 164, "discussionId": "6a58413769aa0f8878bddb20", "projectPage": "https://ruhan-wang.github.io/Harness-Handbook/", "organization": {"_id": "6645f953c39288df638dbdd5", "name": "Tencent-Hunyuan", "fullname": "Tencent Hunyuan", "avatar": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/62d22496c58f969c152bcefd/woKSjt2wXvBNKussyYPsa.png"}, "summary_zh": "<ul>\n    <li  >\u73b0\u4ee3AI\u4ee3\u7406\u7684\u80fd\u529b\u4e0d\u4ec5\u4f9d\u8d56\u4e8e\u57fa\u7840\u6a21\u578b\uff0c\u8fd8\u4f9d\u8d56\u4e8e\u5176\u201c\u5de5\u5177\u201d\uff0c\u7528\u4e8e\u6784\u5efa\u63d0\u793a\u3001\u7ba1\u7406\u72b6\u6001\u548c\u534f\u8c03\u6267\u884c\u3002</li>\n    <li >\u968f\u7740\u6a21\u578b\u548c\u9700\u6c42\u7684\u53d8\u5316\uff0c\u5fc5\u987b\u4e0d\u65ad\u4fee\u6539\u5de5\u5177\uff0c\u800c\u5f00\u53d1\u8005\u9700\u8981\u8bc6\u522b\u6240\u6709\u5b9e\u73b0\u76ee\u6807\u884c\u4e3a\u7684\u4ee3\u7801\u4f4d\u7f6e\uff0c\u8fd9\u5f88\u56f0\u96be\u3002</li>\n    <li >\u4ee3\u7801\u641c\u7d22\u548c\u957f\u4e0a\u4e0b\u6587\u5904\u7406\u53ef\u4ee5\u5e2e\u52a9\u68c0\u67e5\uff0c\u4f46\u884c\u4e3a\u4e0e\u4ee3\u7801\u7684\u6620\u5c04\u4ecd\u9700\u624b\u52a8\u6062\u590d\uff0c\u6210\u4e3a\u5de5\u5177\u6f14\u53d8\u7684\u74f6\u9888\u3002</li>\n    <li >\u6211\u4eec\u63d0\u51fa\u4e86\u300a\u5de5\u5177\u624b\u518c\u300b\uff0c\u901a\u8fc7\u9759\u6001\u5206\u6790\u548c\u5927\u578b\u8bed\u8a00\u6a21\u578b\u8f85\u52a9\u7ed3\u6784\u5316\u81ea\u52a8\u751f\u6210\uff0c\u94fe\u63a5\u884c\u4e3a\u4e0e\u6e90\u4ee3\u7801\u3002</li>\n    <li >\u884c\u4e3a\u5f15\u5bfc\u7684\u6e10\u8fdb\u62ab\u9732\uff08BGPD\uff09\u53ef\u4ee5\u5e2e\u52a9\u4ee3\u7406\u4ece\u9ad8\u5c42\u884c\u4e3a\u4e86\u89e3\u5177\u4f53\u5b9e\u73b0\uff0c\u5e76\u9a8c\u8bc1\u5019\u9009\u4f4d\u7f6e\u3002</li>\n</ul>", "summary_simple": "<ul>\n    <li>Modern AI agents rely on a combination of their foundation model and a harness that manages their operations.</li>\n    <li>When the harness needs updates, developers struggle to find all the relevant code because it is often complex and spread across many files.</li>\n    <li>Behavior localization is a major challenge in evolving these systems, as it requires connecting desired behaviors to specific code implementations.</li>\n    <li>The Harness Handbook provides a way to automatically link behaviors to their source code, using static analysis and AI support.</li>\n    <li>Behavior-Guided Progressive Disclosure (BGPD) helps developers navigate from general behaviors to detailed code, improving the quality of updates while reducing effort.</li>\n</ul>"}, "publishedAt": "2026-07-13T20:00:00.000Z", "title": "Harness Handbook: Making Evolving Agent Harnesses Readable,Navigable, and Editable", "summary": "The capability of a modern AI agent depends not only on its foundation model but also on its harness, which constructs prompts, manages state, invokes tools, and coordinates execution. As models, APIs, environments, and requirements evolve, the harness must be continually modified. Before such a change can be made, a developer or coding agent must identify all code locations that implement the target behavior. This is difficult because production harnesses are large, tightly coupled, and behaviorally distributed, while modification requests describe what the system should do and repositories are organized by files and modules. Code search, repository indexing, and long-context processing ease inspection, but still leave this behavior-to-code mapping to be recovered by hand. Behavior localization is therefore a central bottleneck in harness evolution. We introduce the Harness Handbook, a behavior-centric representation synthesized automatically from a harness codebase via static analysis and LLM-assisted structuring, linking each behavior to its corresponding source. We also introduce Behavior-Guided Progressive Disclosure (BGPD), which guides agents from high-level behaviors to relevant implementation details and verifies candidate locations against the current source. On diverse modification requests from two open-source harnesses, Handbook-Assisted planning improves behavior localization and edit-plan quality while using fewer planner tokens, with the largest gains on scattered sites, rarely executed paths, and cross-module interactions. Evolving complex agentic systems thus depends not only on generating edits, but also on determining where those edits should be made.", "thumbnail": "https://cdn-thumbnails.huggingface.co/social-thumbnails/papers/2607.13285.png", "numComments": 3, "submittedBy": {"_id": "6039478ab3ecf716b1a5fd4d", "avatarUrl": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/6039478ab3ecf716b1a5fd4d/_Thy4E7taiSYBLKxEKJbT.jpeg", "fullname": "taesiri", "name": "taesiri", "type": "user", "isPro": true, "isHf": false, "isHfAdmin": false, "isMod": false, "followerCount": 335, "isUserFollowing": false}, "organization": {"_id": "6645f953c39288df638dbdd5", "name": "Tencent-Hunyuan", "fullname": "Tencent Hunyuan", "avatar": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/62d22496c58f969c152bcefd/woKSjt2wXvBNKussyYPsa.png"}, "isAuthorParticipating": false}, {"paper": {"id": "2606.29526", "authors": [{"_id": "6a48ce6bd66e8ea154bc7e29", "name": "Jing Liang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a48ce6bd66e8ea154bc7e2a", "name": "Hongyao Tang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a48ce6bd66e8ea154bc7e2b", "name": "Yi Ma", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a48ce6bd66e8ea154bc7e2c", "name": "Yancheng He", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a48ce6bd66e8ea154bc7e2d", "name": "Weixun Wang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a48ce6bd66e8ea154bc7e2e", "name": "Xiaoyang Li", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a48ce6bd66e8ea154bc7e2f", "name": "Ju Huang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a48ce6bd66e8ea154bc7e30", "name": "Wenbo Su", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a48ce6bd66e8ea154bc7e31", "name": "Jinyi Liu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a48ce6bd66e8ea154bc7e32", "name": "Yan Zheng", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a48ce6bd66e8ea154bc7e33", "name": "Jianye Hao", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a48ce6bd66e8ea154bc7e34", "name": "Bo Zheng", "hidden": false}], "publishedAt": "2026-06-28T00:00:00.000Z", "submittedOnDailyAt": "2026-07-06T00:00:00.000Z", "title": "The Mirage of Optimizing Training Policies: Monotonic Inference Policies as the Real Objective for LLM Reinforcement Learning", "submittedOnDailyBy": {"_id": "6778da4a1788ddf1c1ef323b", "avatarUrl": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/no-auth/AttI7uQyC151_1592Lc2H.png", "isPro": false, "fullname": "Jing Liang", "user": "AnitaLeung", "type": "user", "name": "AnitaLeung"}, "summary": "Reinforcement learning (RL) has gained growing attention in large language model (LLM) post-training, yet RL training remains fragile and can suffer from instability or collapse. One vital cause is training-inference mismatch: LLM adopts separate inference and training engines for generation efficiency and training precision, which in practice exhibits inconsistent probabilities for the same trajectories on training and inference sides, even with synchronized model parameters. This naturally induces a special type of off-policyness ever existing and poisoning the training. Prior works have made various efforts in addressing the off-policyness to stabilize the training policies under the mismatch. In this paper, we point out the objective misalignment neglected by existing works that an effective update to the policy in the training engine not necessarily ensures the improvement of the inference policy, i.e., the one used in deployment. To this end, we propose a new policy optimization objective for LLM RL, named Monotonic Inference Policy Improvement (MIPI). Following this principle, we introduce Monotonic Inference Policy Update (MIPU), a two-step LLM RL framework that constructs sampler-referenced candidate updates and selectively accepts synchronized candidates using an inference-side gap proxy. Experiments conducted on two model scales under high mismatch show that MIPU improves average reasoning performance and training stability.", "upvotes": 141, "discussionId": "6a48ce6cd66e8ea154bc7e35", "projectPage": "https://anitaleungxx.github.io/MIPU/", "ai_summary": "Training-inference mismatch in reinforcement learning for large language models leads to instability, which is addressed through a new policy optimization objective and framework that ensures consistent policy improvements between training and inference phases.", "ai_keywords": ["reinforcement learning", "large language models", "training-inference mismatch", "off-policy", "policy optimization", "policy improvement", "inference policy", "training stability", "reasoning performance"], "ai_summary_model": "Qwen/Qwen2.5-Coder-32B-Instruct", "summary_zh": "<ul>\n    <li>\u5f3a\u5316\u5b66\u4e60\uff08RL\uff09\u5728\u5927\u578b\u8bed\u8a00\u6a21\u578b\uff08LLM\uff09\u540e\u8bad\u7ec3\u4e2d\u8d8a\u6765\u8d8a\u53d7\u5230\u5173\u6ce8\uff0c\u4f46\u8bad\u7ec3\u8fc7\u7a0b\u4e0d\u7a33\u5b9a\uff0c\u5bb9\u6613\u5d29\u6e83\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u4e00\u4e2a\u4e3b\u8981\u539f\u56e0\u662f\u8bad\u7ec3\u548c\u63a8\u7406\u4e4b\u95f4\u7684\u4e0d\u5339\u914d\uff0c\u5bfc\u81f4\u76f8\u540c\u8f68\u8ff9\u7684\u6982\u7387\u4e0d\u4e00\u81f4\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u73b0\u6709\u7814\u7a76\u81f4\u529b\u4e8e\u89e3\u51b3\u8fd9\u79cd\u4e0d\u5339\u914d\u7684\u95ee\u9898\uff0c\u4f46\u5ffd\u89c6\u4e86\u76ee\u6807\u4e0d\u4e00\u81f4\u7684\u95ee\u9898\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u672c\u6587\u63d0\u51fa\u4e86\u4e00\u79cd\u65b0\u7684\u7b56\u7565\u4f18\u5316\u76ee\u6807\uff0c\u79f0\u4e3a\u5355\u8c03\u63a8\u7406\u653f\u7b56\u6539\u8fdb\uff08MIPI\uff09\uff0c\u4ee5\u53ca\u4e00\u79cd\u4e24\u6b65\u6846\u67b6MIPU\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u5b9e\u9a8c\u8868\u660e\uff0cMIPU\u5728\u9ad8\u4e0d\u5339\u914d\u60c5\u51b5\u4e0b\u63d0\u9ad8\u4e86\u63a8\u7406\u6027\u80fd\u548c\u8bad\u7ec3\u7a33\u5b9a\u6027\u3002</li>\n</ul>", "summary_simple": "<ul>\n  <li>Reinforcement learning (RL) for large language models (LLMs) is becoming popular but can be unstable and fragile.</li>\n  <li>A major issue is the mismatch between training and inference processes, leading to inconsistent results even with the same model parameters.</li>\n  <li>Existing solutions have focused on addressing this mismatch, but they often ignore how updates in training do not always improve inference performance.</li>\n  <li>The authors propose a new method called Monotonic Inference Policy Improvement (MIPI) to better align training with inference goals.</li>\n  <li>They introduce a two-step framework, Monotonic Inference Policy Update (MIPU), which improves reasoning performance and stability during training.</li>\n</ul>"}, "publishedAt": "2026-06-27T20:00:00.000Z", "title": "The Mirage of Optimizing Training Policies: Monotonic Inference Policies as the Real Objective for LLM Reinforcement Learning", "summary": "Reinforcement learning (RL) has gained growing attention in large language model (LLM) post-training, yet RL training remains fragile and can suffer from instability or collapse. One vital cause is training-inference mismatch: LLM adopts separate inference and training engines for generation efficiency and training precision, which in practice exhibits inconsistent probabilities for the same trajectories on training and inference sides, even with synchronized model parameters. This naturally induces a special type of off-policyness ever existing and poisoning the training. Prior works have made various efforts in addressing the off-policyness to stabilize the training policies under the mismatch. In this paper, we point out the objective misalignment neglected by existing works that an effective update to the policy in the training engine not necessarily ensures the improvement of the inference policy, i.e., the one used in deployment. To this end, we propose a new policy optimization objective for LLM RL, named Monotonic Inference Policy Improvement (MIPI). Following this principle, we introduce Monotonic Inference Policy Update (MIPU), a two-step LLM RL framework that constructs sampler-referenced candidate updates and selectively accepts synchronized candidates using an inference-side gap proxy. Experiments conducted on two model scales under high mismatch show that MIPU improves average reasoning performance and training stability.", "thumbnail": "https://cdn-thumbnails.huggingface.co/social-thumbnails/papers/2606.29526.png", "numComments": 1, "submittedBy": {"_id": "6778da4a1788ddf1c1ef323b", "avatarUrl": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/no-auth/AttI7uQyC151_1592Lc2H.png", "fullname": "Jing Liang", "name": "AnitaLeung", "type": "user", "isPro": false, "isHf": false, "isHfAdmin": false, "isMod": false, "followerCount": 2, "isUserFollowing": false}, "isAuthorParticipating": false}, {"paper": {"id": "2606.28733", "authors": [{"_id": "6a43896919e14c76c1bfad0b", "name": "Han Luo", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a43896919e14c76c1bfad0c", "name": "Bingbing Wen", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a43896919e14c76c1bfad0d", "name": "Lucy Lu Wang", "hidden": false}], "publishedAt": "2026-06-27T00:00:00.000Z", "submittedOnDailyAt": "2026-06-30T00:00:00.000Z", "title": "Agentic Abstention: Do Agents Know When to Stop Instead of Act?", "submittedOnDailyBy": {"_id": "68a0606dbbcbb7c347256908", "avatarUrl": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/68a0606dbbcbb7c347256908/JuZGxOT1EHi1dn2_qf2Xz.jpeg", "isPro": false, "fullname": "Han Luo", "user": "sxcn", "type": "user", "name": "sxcn"}, "summary": "LLM agents are expected to act over multiple turns, using search, browsing interfaces, and terminal tools to complete user goals. Yet not every goal is well specified or achievable in the available environment. In such cases, a reliable agent should recognize that further interaction is unlikely to help and abstain from additional tool calls. We define Agentic Abstention, the problem of deciding when an agent should stop acting under uncertainty. Unlike standard LLM abstention, which is usually evaluated as a single-turn answer-or-abstain decision, agentic abstention is a sequential decision problem: an agent can answer, abstain, or gather more information at each turn, and the need to abstain may only become clear after interacting with the environment. We study this problem across web shopping, terminal environments, and question answering, evaluating 13 LLM-as-agent systems and 2 agent scaffolds on more than 28,000 tasks. Our results show that the main challenge is not only whether agents can abstain, but also when they abstain. Some agents never abstain when they should, while others do so only after many unnecessary interactions. This gap is especially large on tasks where the instruction appears feasible until the environment reveals otherwise (e.g., no valid result matches the instruction). We further find that model scale, reasoning, and agent scaffolding affect abstention in different ways, where larger or more capable models sometimes perform worse at timely abstention. Finally, we introduce CONVOLVE, a context engineering method for improving agentic abstention that distills full interaction trajectories into reusable stopping rules. On WebShop, CONVOLVE substantially improves timely abstention without updating model parameters, raising Llama-3.3-70B's timely recall rate from 26.7 to 57.4. Our dataset and code are available at https://lhannnn.github.io/agentic-abstention", "upvotes": 120, "discussionId": "6a43896919e14c76c1bfad0e", "projectPage": "https://lhannnn.github.io/agentic-abstention", "ai_summary": "Agentic abstention involves determining when an AI agent should cease interaction under uncertainty, requiring sequential decision-making across multiple environments and task types.", "ai_keywords": ["agentic abstention", "LLM-as-agent systems", "sequential decision problem", "web shopping", "terminal environments", "question answering", "context engineering", "CONVOLVE", "stopping rules"], "ai_summary_model": "Qwen/Qwen2.5-Coder-32B-Instruct", "organization": {"_id": "6315a1bb86b3db2ac420100e", "name": "UW", "fullname": "University of Washington", "avatar": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/61ac8f8a00d01045fca0ad2f/gr5B_WVvbMr4kTox5UkwZ.jpeg"}, "summary_zh": "<ul>\n    <li>\u7814\u7a76\u4e86\u5927\u578b\u8bed\u8a00\u6a21\u578b\uff08LLM\uff09\u4ee3\u7406\u5728\u591a\u8f6e\u4e92\u52a8\u4e2d\u5982\u4f55\u5224\u65ad\u4f55\u65f6\u505c\u6b62\u884c\u52a8\u7684\u95ee\u9898\uff0c\u79f0\u4e3a\u201c\u4ee3\u7406\u6027\u5f03\u6743\u201d\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u4ee3\u7406\u5728\u4e0d\u786e\u5b9a\u60c5\u51b5\u4e0b\u9700\u8981\u5224\u65ad\u662f\u5426\u7ee7\u7eed\u4e92\u52a8\u6216\u83b7\u53d6\u66f4\u591a\u4fe1\u606f\uff0c\u800c\u4e0d\u662f\u6bcf\u6b21\u90fd\u7ed9\u51fa\u7b54\u6848\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u5206\u6790\u4e8613\u4e2aLLM\u4ee3\u7406\u7cfb\u7edf\u548c2\u4e2a\u4ee3\u7406\u67b6\u6784\uff0c\u8fdb\u884c\u4e86\u8d85\u8fc728,000\u4e2a\u4efb\u52a1\u7684\u6d4b\u8bd5\uff0c\u53d1\u73b0\u5f88\u591a\u4ee3\u7406\u5728\u5e94\u8be5\u5f03\u6743\u65f6\u53cd\u800c\u4e0d\u5f03\u6743\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u6a21\u578b\u89c4\u6a21\u3001\u63a8\u7406\u80fd\u529b\u548c\u4ee3\u7406\u67b6\u6784\u5bf9\u5f03\u6743\u51b3\u7b56\u6709\u4e0d\u540c\u5f71\u54cd\uff0c\u6709\u4e9b\u5927\u6a21\u578b\u5728\u53ca\u65f6\u5f03\u6743\u4e0a\u8868\u73b0\u4e0d\u4f73\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u5f15\u5165\u4e86CONVOLVE\u65b9\u6cd5\uff0c\u901a\u8fc7\u63d0\u70bc\u4e92\u52a8\u8f68\u8ff9\u751f\u6210\u53ef\u91cd\u7528\u7684\u505c\u6b62\u89c4\u5219\uff0c\u663e\u8457\u63d0\u9ad8\u4e86\u4ee3\u7406\u7684\u53ca\u65f6\u5f03\u6743\u80fd\u529b\u3002</li>\n</ul>", "summary_simple": "<ul>\n    <li>LLM agents need to make decisions over multiple interactions to achieve user goals, but not all goals are clear or achievable.</li>\n    <li>Agentic Abstention is the challenge of knowing when an agent should stop trying to act when uncertain.</li>\n    <li>This study evaluates 13 LLM systems across various tasks, finding that some agents either never stop when they should or take too long to do so.</li>\n    <li>The performance of agents regarding timely abstention varies based on model size, reasoning ability, and scaffolding methods.</li>\n    <li>CONVOLVE is a new method that improves the ability of agents to know when to stop, significantly increasing their effectiveness without changing model parameters.</li>\n</ul>"}, "publishedAt": "2026-06-26T20:00:00.000Z", "title": "Agentic Abstention: Do Agents Know When to Stop Instead of Act?", "summary": "LLM agents are expected to act over multiple turns, using search, browsing interfaces, and terminal tools to complete user goals. Yet not every goal is well specified or achievable in the available environment. In such cases, a reliable agent should recognize that further interaction is unlikely to help and abstain from additional tool calls. We define Agentic Abstention, the problem of deciding when an agent should stop acting under uncertainty. Unlike standard LLM abstention, which is usually evaluated as a single-turn answer-or-abstain decision, agentic abstention is a sequential decision problem: an agent can answer, abstain, or gather more information at each turn, and the need to abstain may only become clear after interacting with the environment. We study this problem across web shopping, terminal environments, and question answering, evaluating 13 LLM-as-agent systems and 2 agent scaffolds on more than 28,000 tasks. Our results show that the main challenge is not only whether agents can abstain, but also when they abstain. Some agents never abstain when they should, while others do so only after many unnecessary interactions. This gap is especially large on tasks where the instruction appears feasible until the environment reveals otherwise (e.g., no valid result matches the instruction). We further find that model scale, reasoning, and agent scaffolding affect abstention in different ways, where larger or more capable models sometimes perform worse at timely abstention. Finally, we introduce CONVOLVE, a context engineering method for improving agentic abstention that distills full interaction trajectories into reusable stopping rules. On WebShop, CONVOLVE substantially improves timely abstention without updating model parameters, raising Llama-3.3-70B's timely recall rate from 26.7 to 57.4. Our dataset and code are available at https://lhannnn.github.io/agentic-abstention", "thumbnail": "https://cdn-thumbnails.huggingface.co/social-thumbnails/papers/2606.28733.png", "numComments": 8, "submittedBy": {"_id": "68a0606dbbcbb7c347256908", "avatarUrl": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/68a0606dbbcbb7c347256908/JuZGxOT1EHi1dn2_qf2Xz.jpeg", "fullname": "Han Luo", "name": "sxcn", "type": "user", "isPro": false, "isHf": false, "isHfAdmin": false, "isMod": false, "followerCount": 1, "isUserFollowing": false}, "organization": {"_id": "6315a1bb86b3db2ac420100e", "name": "UW", "fullname": "University of Washington", "avatar": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/61ac8f8a00d01045fca0ad2f/gr5B_WVvbMr4kTox5UkwZ.jpeg"}, "isAuthorParticipating": false}, {"paper": {"id": "2606.29538", "authors": [{"_id": "6a599a716c2e371e6ca38125", "name": "Yijia Fan", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a599a716c2e371e6ca38126", "name": "Zonglin Di", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a599a716c2e371e6ca38127", "name": "Zimo Wen", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a599a716c2e371e6ca38128", "name": "Yifan Yang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a599a716c2e371e6ca38129", "name": "Mingxi Cheng", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a599a716c2e371e6ca3812a", "user": {"_id": "65115c00a588fdb36558b673", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/1f36263dc4bfaf696a4aa959a6aab1e1.svg", "isPro": false, "fullname": "Qi Dai", "user": "daiqi", "type": "user", "name": "daiqi"}, "name": "Qi Dai", "status": "claimed_verified", "statusLastChangedAt": "2026-07-20T16:05:41.351Z", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a599a716c2e371e6ca3812b", "name": "Bei Liu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a599a716c2e371e6ca3812c", "name": "Kai Qiu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a599a716c2e371e6ca3812d", "name": "Yue Dong", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a599a716c2e371e6ca3812e", "name": "Ji Li", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a599a716c2e371e6ca3812f", "name": "Chong Luo", "hidden": false}], "mediaUrls": ["https://cdn-uploads.huggingface.co/production/uploads/62d18eb81e36881a57f29bf4/aZPQHsZww6x3R9D_J7Si9.mp4"], "publishedAt": "2026-07-16T00:00:00.000Z", "submittedOnDailyAt": "2026-07-20T00:00:00.000Z", "title": "RESOURCE2SKILL: Distilling Executable Agent Skills from Human-Created Multimodal Resources", "submittedOnDailyBy": {"_id": "62d18eb81e36881a57f29bf4", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/104851421b4ee9641daaf15942fa7ea1.svg", "isPro": false, "fullname": "Yif Yang", "user": "Yif29", "type": "user", "name": "Yif29"}, "summary": "Skills are a useful abstraction for software agents, turning human and agent experience into reusable procedural knowledge. Yet existing skill libraries are mostly hand-written, text-centric, or derived from agent traces, leaving tutorial videos and other multimodal human resources largely underused. We present RESOURCE2SKILL, a framework that distills multimodal resources, including tutorial videos, repositories, articles, and reference artifacts, into executable skills for software agents. RESOURCE2SKILL organizes these skills as a hierarchical multimodal Skill Wiki, where each entry combines structured text, code, visual examples, metadata, and provenance. This design preserves complementary signals from different resources: videos capture temporal operations and visual effects, code captures executable tool patterns, and articles or artifacts provide conceptual and stylistic grounding. At inference time, agents retrieve and compose relevant skills from the wiki; when coverage is insufficient, the same construction operator can acquire new skills online. Across seven practical authoring domains, RESOURCE2SKILL improves average overall score by +11.9 percentage points over no-skill agents and outperforms strong harness baselines in 26 of 28 main-aggregate model-domain cells. Ablations confirm the value of multimodal skill format, hierarchical organization, source diversity, selection strategy, and online acquisition.", "upvotes": 113, "discussionId": "6a599a726c2e371e6ca38130", "projectPage": "https://aka.ms/Resources2Skill", "githubRepo": "https://github.com/microsoft/Resource2Skill", "githubRepoAddedBy": "user", "githubStars": 64, "organization": {"_id": "68151d0f51add3813f3f7d1b", "name": "MicrosoftResearch", "fullname": "Microsoft Research", "avatar": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/6529a4f2f1205983224fa513/PeuVr7jSuJflmDBBGxoDX.png"}, "summary_zh": "<ul>\n    <li>RESOURCE2SKILL\u662f\u4e00\u4e2a\u5c06\u591a\u79cd\u8d44\u6e90\uff08\u5982\u6559\u7a0b\u89c6\u9891\u3001\u6587\u7ae0\u7b49\uff09\u8f6c\u5316\u4e3a\u8f6f\u4ef6\u4ee3\u7406\u53ef\u6267\u884c\u6280\u80fd\u7684\u6846\u67b6\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u8be5\u6846\u67b6\u5c06\u6280\u80fd\u7ec4\u7ec7\u6210\u4e00\u4e2a\u5c42\u6b21\u5316\u7684\u591a\u6a21\u6001\u6280\u80fd\u7ef4\u57fa\uff0c\u7ed3\u5408\u4e86\u6587\u672c\u3001\u4ee3\u7801\u3001\u89c6\u89c9\u793a\u4f8b\u7b49\u4fe1\u606f\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u901a\u8fc7\u591a\u79cd\u8d44\u6e90\u7684\u7ed3\u5408\uff0c\u4fdd\u7559\u4e86\u89c6\u9891\u7684\u65f6\u95f4\u64cd\u4f5c\u3001\u4ee3\u7801\u7684\u53ef\u6267\u884c\u6a21\u5f0f\u548c\u6587\u7ae0\u7684\u6982\u5ff5\u57fa\u7840\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u5728\u4e03\u4e2a\u5b9e\u9645\u5e94\u7528\u9886\u57df\u4e2d\uff0cRESOURCE2SKILL\u4f7f\u5e73\u5747\u5206\u6570\u63d0\u9ad8\u4e8611.9%\uff0c\u5e76\u572826\u4e2a\u6a21\u578b\u57df\u4e2d\u8d85\u8fc7\u4e86\u5f3a\u57fa\u7ebf\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u5b9e\u9a8c\u7ed3\u679c\u8868\u660e\uff0c\u6280\u80fd\u7684\u591a\u6a21\u6001\u683c\u5f0f\u548c\u5c42\u6b21\u5316\u7ec4\u7ec7\u5177\u6709\u91cd\u8981\u4ef7\u503c\u3002 </li>\n</ul>", "summary_simple": "<ul>\n    <li>RESOURCE2SKILL is a new system that helps software agents learn skills from various resources, like tutorial videos and articles.</li>\n    <li>The system organizes these skills in a hierarchical Skill Wiki, combining text, code, visuals, and metadata.</li>\n    <li>This approach uses different types of resources effectively; videos show how things work over time, while code provides practical examples.</li>\n    <li>When agents need new skills, they can find and create them using this system, improving their performance significantly.</li>\n    <li>Tests show RESOURCE2SKILL improves agent performance by an average of 11.9 percentage points compared to agents without skills.</li>\n</ul>"}, "publishedAt": "2026-07-15T20:00:00.000Z", "title": "RESOURCE2SKILL: Distilling Executable Agent Skills from Human-Created Multimodal Resources", "summary": "Skills are a useful abstraction for software agents, turning human and agent experience into reusable procedural knowledge. Yet existing skill libraries are mostly hand-written, text-centric, or derived from agent traces, leaving tutorial videos and other multimodal human resources largely underused. We present RESOURCE2SKILL, a framework that distills multimodal resources, including tutorial videos, repositories, articles, and reference artifacts, into executable skills for software agents. RESOURCE2SKILL organizes these skills as a hierarchical multimodal Skill Wiki, where each entry combines structured text, code, visual examples, metadata, and provenance. This design preserves complementary signals from different resources: videos capture temporal operations and visual effects, code captures executable tool patterns, and articles or artifacts provide conceptual and stylistic grounding. At inference time, agents retrieve and compose relevant skills from the wiki; when coverage is insufficient, the same construction operator can acquire new skills online. Across seven practical authoring domains, RESOURCE2SKILL improves average overall score by +11.9 percentage points over no-skill agents and outperforms strong harness baselines in 26 of 28 main-aggregate model-domain cells. Ablations confirm the value of multimodal skill format, hierarchical organization, source diversity, selection strategy, and online acquisition.", "mediaUrls": ["https://cdn-uploads.huggingface.co/production/uploads/62d18eb81e36881a57f29bf4/aZPQHsZww6x3R9D_J7Si9.mp4"], "thumbnail": "https://cdn-thumbnails.huggingface.co/social-thumbnails/papers/2606.29538.png", "numComments": 1, "submittedBy": {"_id": "62d18eb81e36881a57f29bf4", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/104851421b4ee9641daaf15942fa7ea1.svg", "fullname": "Yif Yang", "name": "Yif29", "type": "user", "isPro": false, "isHf": false, "isHfAdmin": false, "isMod": false, "followerCount": 5, "isUserFollowing": false}, "organization": {"_id": "68151d0f51add3813f3f7d1b", "name": "MicrosoftResearch", "fullname": "Microsoft Research", "avatar": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/6529a4f2f1205983224fa513/PeuVr7jSuJflmDBBGxoDX.png"}, "isAuthorParticipating": false}, {"paper": {"id": "2607.11683", "authors": [{"_id": "6a55e685a9d74d6e65bbd8f3", "user": {"_id": "668bdbf4db71d9daf74909ec", "avatarUrl": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/668bdbf4db71d9daf74909ec/HspmqM3ITYR4vn59z1hxt.jpeg", "isPro": false, "fullname": "Mikhail Komarov", "user": "AsphodelRem", "type": "user", "name": "AsphodelRem"}, "name": "Mikhail Komarov", "status": "claimed_verified", "statusLastChangedAt": "2026-07-20T16:04:58.625Z", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a55e685a9d74d6e65bbd8f4", "name": "Ivan Bondarenko", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a55e685a9d74d6e65bbd8f5", "name": "Stanislav Shtuka", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a55e685a9d74d6e65bbd8f6", "name": "Oleg Sedukhin", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a55e685a9d74d6e65bbd8f7", "name": "Roman Shuvalov", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a55e685a9d74d6e65bbd8f8", "user": {"_id": "65de080d7b8cd1aab189a284", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/b9e84281959004689c5be6401801c408.svg", "isPro": false, "fullname": "Yana Dementyeva", "user": "YanaDementyeva", "type": "user", "name": "YanaDementyeva"}, "name": "Yana Dementyeva", "status": "claimed_verified", "statusLastChangedAt": "2026-07-20T16:04:59.255Z", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a55e685a9d74d6e65bbd8f9", "name": "Matvey Solovyov", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a55e685a9d74d6e65bbd8fa", "name": "Nikolay O. Nikitin", "hidden": false}], "publishedAt": "2026-07-13T00:00:00.000Z", "submittedOnDailyAt": "2026-07-20T00:00:00.000Z", "title": "RAGU: A Multi-Step GraphRAG Engine with a Compact Domain-Adapted LLM", "submittedOnDailyBy": {"_id": "62b1e0f76a5435fd9a60a8dc", "avatarUrl": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/1655824626110-noauth.png", "isPro": true, "fullname": "Ivan Bondarenko", "user": "bond005", "type": "user", "name": "bond005"}, "summary": "Graph retrieval-augmented generation (GraphRAG) enhances large language models with structured knowledge, yet existing systems construct knowledge graphs in a single extraction pass, producing noisy entities and brittle retrieval. RAGU, an open-source modular GraphRAG engine, addresses this by separating extraction from consolidation: entities and relations pass through two-stage typed extraction, DBSCAN-backed deduplication, LLM summarization, and Leiden community detection. A key insight motivates a compact extractor: the skills an in-pipeline LLM needs - comprehension, extraction, reasoning over context - are language skills that grow only weakly with model size, unlike factual world knowledge. Accordingly, we train Meno-Lite-0.1, a 7B model optimized for language skills, which outperforms Qwen2.5-32B on knowledge-graph construction (+12.5% relative harmonic mean) and matches it on English GraphRAG tasks. On GraphRAG-Bench (Medical), RAGU retrieves the most complete context at every factoid level (evidence recall up to 0.84 vs. leq0.76) and overtakes HippoRAG2 on synthesis tasks; on multi-hop factoid QA, the apparent HippoRAG2 advantage is shown to be largely an answer-format artifact. RAGU is installable via pip install graph_ragu, runs on a single GPU, and is released under MIT. The source code is publicly available at https://github.com/RaguTeam/RAGU, and the Meno-Lite-0.1 model can be obtained from https://huggingface.co/bond005/meno-lite-0.1.", "upvotes": 111, "discussionId": "6a55e686a9d74d6e65bbd8fb", "githubRepo": "https://github.com/RaguTeam/RAGU", "githubRepoAddedBy": "user", "githubStars": 77, "organization": {"_id": "62b1e262f4a72794188b6757", "name": "NSU", "fullname": "Novosibirsk State University", "avatar": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/1655825086683-62b1e0f76a5435fd9a60a8dc.png"}, "summary_zh": "<ul>\n    <li>GraphRAG\u901a\u8fc7\u7ed3\u6784\u5316\u77e5\u8bc6\u589e\u5f3a\u5927\u578b\u8bed\u8a00\u6a21\u578b\uff0c\u4f46\u73b0\u6709\u7cfb\u7edf\u5728\u77e5\u8bc6\u56fe\u8c31\u6784\u5efa\u4e2d\u5b58\u5728\u566a\u58f0\u548c\u8106\u5f31\u6027\u3002</li>\n    <li>RAGU\u662f\u4e00\u4e2a\u5f00\u6e90\u7684\u6a21\u5757\u5316GraphRAG\u5f15\u64ce\uff0c\u901a\u8fc7\u5206\u79bb\u63d0\u53d6\u548c\u6574\u5408\u6765\u89e3\u51b3\u8fd9\u4e9b\u95ee\u9898\u3002</li>\n    <li>RAGU\u4f7f\u7528\u4e24\u9636\u6bb5\u7c7b\u578b\u63d0\u53d6\u3001\u53bb\u91cd\u3001\u603b\u7ed3\u548c\u793e\u533a\u68c0\u6d4b\u6765\u63d0\u9ad8\u77e5\u8bc6\u56fe\u8c31\u7684\u8d28\u91cf\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u8bad\u7ec3\u7684Meno-Lite-0.1\u6a21\u578b\u5728\u77e5\u8bc6\u56fe\u8c31\u6784\u5efa\u4e0a\u8868\u73b0\u4f18\u4e8e\u66f4\u5927\u7684Qwen2.5-32B\u6a21\u578b\u3002</li>\n    <li>RAGU\u53ef\u901a\u8fc7pip\u5b89\u88c5\uff0c\u652f\u6301\u5355GPU\u8fd0\u884c\uff0c\u6e90\u4ee3\u7801\u548c\u6a21\u578b\u53ef\u5728GitHub\u548cHugging Face\u4e0a\u83b7\u53d6\u3002</li>\n</ul>", "summary_simple": "<ul>\n    <li>GraphRAG improves language models by using structured knowledge but often produces noisy results.</li>\n    <li>RAGU is a new open-source tool that improves knowledge graph creation by separating the extraction and consolidation processes.</li>\n    <li>It uses advanced techniques like deduplication and community detection to enhance the quality of the graphs.</li>\n    <li>The Meno-Lite-0.1 model, designed for better language skills, performs better than larger models on knowledge graph tasks.</li>\n    <li>RAGU can be easily installed, runs on a single GPU, and its code and model are available online.</li>\n</ul>"}, "publishedAt": "2026-07-12T20:00:00.000Z", "title": "RAGU: A Multi-Step GraphRAG Engine with a Compact Domain-Adapted LLM", "summary": "Graph retrieval-augmented generation (GraphRAG) enhances large language models with structured knowledge, yet existing systems construct knowledge graphs in a single extraction pass, producing noisy entities and brittle retrieval. RAGU, an open-source modular GraphRAG engine, addresses this by separating extraction from consolidation: entities and relations pass through two-stage typed extraction, DBSCAN-backed deduplication, LLM summarization, and Leiden community detection. A key insight motivates a compact extractor: the skills an in-pipeline LLM needs - comprehension, extraction, reasoning over context - are language skills that grow only weakly with model size, unlike factual world knowledge. Accordingly, we train Meno-Lite-0.1, a 7B model optimized for language skills, which outperforms Qwen2.5-32B on knowledge-graph construction (+12.5% relative harmonic mean) and matches it on English GraphRAG tasks. On GraphRAG-Bench (Medical), RAGU retrieves the most complete context at every factoid level (evidence recall up to 0.84 vs. leq0.76) and overtakes HippoRAG2 on synthesis tasks; on multi-hop factoid QA, the apparent HippoRAG2 advantage is shown to be largely an answer-format artifact. RAGU is installable via pip install graph_ragu, runs on a single GPU, and is released under MIT. The source code is publicly available at https://github.com/RaguTeam/RAGU, and the Meno-Lite-0.1 model can be obtained from https://huggingface.co/bond005/meno-lite-0.1.", "thumbnail": "https://cdn-thumbnails.huggingface.co/social-thumbnails/papers/2607.11683.png", "numComments": 3, "submittedBy": {"_id": "62b1e0f76a5435fd9a60a8dc", "avatarUrl": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/1655824626110-noauth.png", "fullname": "Ivan Bondarenko", "name": "bond005", "type": "user", "isPro": true, "isHf": false, "isHfAdmin": false, "isMod": false, "followerCount": 88, "isUserFollowing": false}, "organization": {"_id": "62b1e262f4a72794188b6757", "name": "NSU", "fullname": "Novosibirsk State University", "avatar": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/1655825086683-62b1e0f76a5435fd9a60a8dc.png"}, "isAuthorParticipating": false}, {"paper": {"id": "2607.14935", "authors": [{"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca380f1", "name": "Xinhao Li", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca380f2", "name": "Yuhan Zhu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca380f3", "name": "Xiangyu Zeng", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca380f4", "name": "Yuhao Dong", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca380f5", "name": "Haoning Wu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca380f6", "name": "Zhiqiu Zhang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca380f7", "name": "Yuandong Yang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca380f8", "name": "Changlian Ma", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca380f9", "name": "Qingyu Zhang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca380fa", "name": "Yansong Shi", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca380fb", "name": "Xinyu Chen", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca380fc", "name": "Haoran Chen", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca380fd", "name": "Zizheng Huang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca380fe", "name": "Jun Zhang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca380ff", "name": "Kun Ouyang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca38100", "name": "Lin Sui", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca38101", "name": "Ziang Yan", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca38102", "name": "Yicheng Xu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca38103", "name": "Chenting Wang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca38104", "name": "Yinan He", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca38105", "name": "Hongjie Zhang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca38106", "name": "Yi Wang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca38107", "name": "Yu Qiao", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca38108", "name": "Yali Wang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca38109", "name": "Ziwei Liu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca3810a", "name": "Kai Chen", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca3810b", "name": "Limin Wang", "hidden": false}], "publishedAt": "2026-07-16T00:00:00.000Z", "submittedOnDailyAt": "2026-07-17T00:00:00.000Z", "title": "VideoChat3: Fully Open Video MLLM for Efficient and Generalist Video Understanding", "submittedOnDailyBy": {"_id": "62c77f4352d8ae531f5511f9", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/50198ccb02ccd286975a4613fbabee28.svg", "isPro": false, "fullname": "Limin Wang", "user": "lmwang", "type": "user", "name": "lmwang"}, "summary": "Recent advances in video understanding have spanned motion, long video, and streaming interaction, driving this field toward real-world applications. Despite this progress, current open-source models remain limited in several ways. They often struggle to generalize across diverse video types, making them effective only in specific domains. High computational demands further restrict their efficiency and scalability. Moreover, most models are only partially open, with key components such as training code, strategy, or datasets unavailable, which hinders reproducibility and slows community-driven development. To address these issues, we introduce VideoChat3, a fully open, efficient, and generalist video-centric MLLM. VideoChat3 advances video understanding through two complementary designs. For efficiency, we introduce Inflated 3D Vision Transformer (I3D-ViT) and Adaptive Frame Resolution for Streaming Video Perception, which enables efficient spatiotemporal representation and reduces the cost of processing video inputs during training and inference. For effectiveness, we develop a scalable video data synthesis pipeline that curates three diverse, high-quality training datasets: VideoChat3-Academic2M, VideoChat3-LV116K, and VideoChat3-OL617K, covering general, long-form, and streaming video scenarios, improving the model's generalization across domains. By integrating these designs, VideoChat3 achieves a rare balance of broad generalization and computational efficiency. Experiments across general, long-form, and streaming benchmarks demonstrate that VideoChat3 surpasses prior open-source models with equal or larger parameter counts with only 4B parameters and higher efficiency.", "upvotes": 108, "discussionId": "6a5996a76c2e371e6ca3810c", "projectPage": "https://mcg-nju.github.io/VideoChat3", "githubRepo": "https://github.com/MCG-NJU/VideoChat3", "githubRepoAddedBy": "user", "githubStars": 43, "organization": {"_id": "62c77fde1e080b83746468bd", "name": "MCG-NJU", "fullname": "Multimedia Computing Group-Nanjing University", "avatar": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/noauth/OIFtHl-mDBM_5SqyR9T8f.png"}, "summary_zh": "<ul>\n    <li>\u89c6\u9891\u7406\u89e3\u9886\u57df\u53d6\u5f97\u4e86\u8fdb\u5c55\uff0c\u4f46\u73b0\u6709\u7684\u5f00\u6e90\u6a21\u578b\u5b58\u5728\u4e00\u4e9b\u9650\u5236\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u6a21\u578b\u5728\u4e0d\u540c\u89c6\u9891\u7c7b\u578b\u4e4b\u95f4\u7684\u6cdb\u5316\u80fd\u529b\u8f83\u5dee\uff0c\u8ba1\u7b97\u9700\u6c42\u9ad8\uff0c\u9650\u5236\u4e86\u6548\u7387\u548c\u53ef\u6269\u5c55\u6027\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u5927\u591a\u6570\u6a21\u578b\u7684\u5173\u952e\u7ec4\u4ef6\u5e76\u672a\u5b8c\u5168\u5f00\u653e\uff0c\u5f71\u54cd\u4e86\u53ef\u91cd\u590d\u6027\u548c\u793e\u533a\u5f00\u53d1\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u6211\u4eec\u63a8\u51fa\u4e86VideoChat3\uff0c\u8fd9\u662f\u4e00\u79cd\u5b8c\u5168\u5f00\u653e\u3001\u9ad8\u6548\u4e14\u901a\u7528\u7684\u89c6\u9891\u4e2d\u5fc3\u591a\u6a21\u6001\u8bed\u8a00\u6a21\u578b\u3002</li>\n    <li>VideoChat3\u901a\u8fc7\u521b\u65b0\u7684\u8bbe\u8ba1\u63d0\u9ad8\u4e86\u89c6\u9891\u7406\u89e3\u80fd\u529b\uff0c\u5e76\u5728\u591a\u4e2a\u57fa\u51c6\u6d4b\u8bd5\u4e2d\u8d85\u8d8a\u4e86\u4ee5\u524d\u7684\u5f00\u6e90\u6a21\u578b\u3002</li>\n</ul>", "summary_simple": "<ul>\n    <li>Video understanding has improved recently, but open-source models still have limitations.</li>\n    <li>Current models struggle to work well with different types of videos and require a lot of computing power.</li>\n    <li>Many models are only partially open, making it hard for others to reproduce their results.</li>\n    <li>VideoChat3 is a new, fully open video model that aims to be efficient and effective.</li>\n    <li>It uses advanced technology to reduce processing costs and has three diverse training datasets, making it better at understanding different video types.</li>\n</ul>"}, "publishedAt": "2026-07-15T20:00:00.000Z", "title": "VideoChat3: Fully Open Video MLLM for Efficient and Generalist Video Understanding", "summary": "Recent advances in video understanding have spanned motion, long video, and streaming interaction, driving this field toward real-world applications. Despite this progress, current open-source models remain limited in several ways. They often struggle to generalize across diverse video types, making them effective only in specific domains. High computational demands further restrict their efficiency and scalability. Moreover, most models are only partially open, with key components such as training code, strategy, or datasets unavailable, which hinders reproducibility and slows community-driven development. To address these issues, we introduce VideoChat3, a fully open, efficient, and generalist video-centric MLLM. VideoChat3 advances video understanding through two complementary designs. For efficiency, we introduce Inflated 3D Vision Transformer (I3D-ViT) and Adaptive Frame Resolution for Streaming Video Perception, which enables efficient spatiotemporal representation and reduces the cost of processing video inputs during training and inference. For effectiveness, we develop a scalable video data synthesis pipeline that curates three diverse, high-quality training datasets: VideoChat3-Academic2M, VideoChat3-LV116K, and VideoChat3-OL617K, covering general, long-form, and streaming video scenarios, improving the model's generalization across domains. By integrating these designs, VideoChat3 achieves a rare balance of broad generalization and computational efficiency. Experiments across general, long-form, and streaming benchmarks demonstrate that VideoChat3 surpasses prior open-source models with equal or larger parameter counts with only 4B parameters and higher efficiency.", "thumbnail": "https://cdn-thumbnails.huggingface.co/social-thumbnails/papers/2607.14935.png", "numComments": 1, "submittedBy": {"_id": "62c77f4352d8ae531f5511f9", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/50198ccb02ccd286975a4613fbabee28.svg", "fullname": "Limin Wang", "name": "lmwang", "type": "user", "isPro": false, "isHf": false, "isHfAdmin": false, "isMod": false, "followerCount": 2, "isUserFollowing": false}, "organization": {"_id": "62c77fde1e080b83746468bd", "name": "MCG-NJU", "fullname": "Multimedia Computing Group-Nanjing University", "avatar": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/noauth/OIFtHl-mDBM_5SqyR9T8f.png"}, "isAuthorParticipating": false}, {"paper": {"id": "2607.03118", "authors": [{"_id": "6a505b7675fd3d966bd45d93", "user": {"_id": "66c0a08bac74db25de8427ec", "avatarUrl": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/66c0a08bac74db25de8427ec/9D-piDBZqSt6KNkHImmkv.jpeg", "isPro": false, "fullname": "Jintao Zhang", "user": "jt-zhang", "type": "user", "name": "jt-zhang"}, "name": "Jintao Zhang", "status": "claimed_verified", "statusLastChangedAt": "2026-07-10T07:45:02.035Z", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a505b7675fd3d966bd45d94", "name": "Kai Jiang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a505b7675fd3d966bd45d95", "name": "Jintao Chen", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a505b7675fd3d966bd45d96", "name": "Xu Wang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a505b7675fd3d966bd45d97", "name": "Yang Luo", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a505b7675fd3d966bd45d98", "name": "Yuji Wang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a505b7675fd3d966bd45d99", "name": "Dechuang Chen", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a505b7675fd3d966bd45d9a", "user": {"_id": "64b76528fdb702b3d8641514", "avatarUrl": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/64b76528fdb702b3d8641514/Ho-uWcQCAEIURM1lhWEWJ.jpeg", "isPro": false, "fullname": "Jungang Li", "user": "Jungang", "type": "user", "name": "Jungang"}, "name": "Jungang Li", "status": "claimed_verified", "statusLastChangedAt": "2026-07-10T07:44:54.616Z", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a505b7675fd3d966bd45d9b", "name": "Chengyang Ye", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a505b7675fd3d966bd45d9c", "name": "Marco Chen", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a505b7675fd3d966bd45d9d", "user": {"_id": "64c269a52d73768f07ac266c", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/d497a960f8aef6a974907b68ed750c1c.svg", "isPro": true, "fullname": "Zhu Hongzhou", "user": "zhuhz22", "type": "user", "name": "zhuhz22"}, "name": "Hongzhou Zhu", "status": "claimed_verified", "statusLastChangedAt": "2026-07-10T07:44:59.447Z", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a505b7675fd3d966bd45d9e", "name": "Min Zhao", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a505b7675fd3d966bd45d9f", "name": "Yuxuan Jiang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a505b7675fd3d966bd45da0", "name": "Zhengkun Huang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a505b7675fd3d966bd45da1", "name": "Chendong Xiang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a505b7675fd3d966bd45da2", "name": "Kaiwen Zheng", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a505b7675fd3d966bd45da3", "name": "Haoxu Wang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a505b7675fd3d966bd45da4", "name": "Xiaohang Wang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a505b7675fd3d966bd45da5", "user": {"_id": "646ecab85d05113e43280e75", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/8d123a17b8ad528029bc33d01dbcb532.svg", "isPro": false, "fullname": "Qi Jia", "user": "kuafou", "type": "user", "name": "kuafou"}, "name": "Qi Jia", "status": "claimed_verified", "statusLastChangedAt": "2026-07-10T07:44:56.955Z", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a505b7675fd3d966bd45da6", "name": "Xin Chen", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a505b7675fd3d966bd45da7", "name": "Yimin Chen", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a505b7675fd3d966bd45da8", "name": "Youhe Jiang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a505b7675fd3d966bd45da9", "name": "Fangcheng Fu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a505b7675fd3d966bd45daa", "name": "Zhijie Deng", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a505b7675fd3d966bd45dab", "name": "Fan Bao", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a505b7675fd3d966bd45dac", "name": "Jianfei Chen", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a505b7675fd3d966bd45dad", "name": "Jun Zhu", "hidden": false}], "mediaUrls": ["https://cdn-uploads.huggingface.co/production/uploads/66c0a08bac74db25de8427ec/tOyCS73TCOOklV-7xys8i.png"], "publishedAt": "2026-07-03T00:00:00.000Z", "submittedOnDailyAt": "2026-07-10T00:00:00.000Z", "title": "Vidu S1: A Real-Time Interactive Video Generation Model", "submittedOnDailyBy": {"_id": "66c0a08bac74db25de8427ec", "avatarUrl": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/66c0a08bac74db25de8427ec/9D-piDBZqSt6KNkHImmkv.jpeg", "isPro": false, "fullname": "Jintao Zhang", "user": "jt-zhang", "type": "user", "name": "jt-zhang"}, "summary": "We introduce Vidu S1, a real-time interactive video generation model supporting voice control of digital characters. Users can control video generation content at any moment through voice instructions. Vidu S1 supports infinite-length real-time video generation without blurring, drift, or visual distortion. Built with TurboDiffusion and TurboServe, Vidu S1 outputs 540p real-time videos at up to 42 FPS on regular consumer GPUs. Users can upload custom images of real people, anime, and pets, and choose different voice tones for personalized experiences. Experiments show that Vidu S1 achieves the best performance across all test metrics while fully meeting real-time inference requirements. A playable online demo is available at https://vidu.com/vidu-stream.", "upvotes": 108, "discussionId": "6a505b7675fd3d966bd45dae", "projectPage": "https://vidu.com/vidu-stream", "githubRepo": "https://github.com/shengshu-ai/Vidu-S1", "githubRepoAddedBy": "user", "ai_summary": "Vidu S1 is a real-time interactive video generation model that supports voice-controlled digital character animation with infinite-length output and high frame rate on consumer hardware.", "ai_keywords": ["TurboDiffusion", "TurboServe", "real-time video generation", "voice control", "digital characters", "infinite-length video", "frame rate", "consumer GPUs"], "ai_summary_model": "Qwen/Qwen2.5-Coder-32B-Instruct", "githubStars": 127, "organization": {"_id": "628735cbc83a2d6ab8d14a66", "name": "Tsinghua", "fullname": "Tsinghua University", "avatar": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/6c5c1441e3283e7543342e59277ea219?d=retro&size=100"}, "summary_zh": "<ul>\n    <li>Vidu S1 \u662f\u4e00\u79cd\u5b9e\u65f6\u4e92\u52a8\u89c6\u9891\u751f\u6210\u6a21\u578b\uff0c\u53ef\u4ee5\u901a\u8fc7\u8bed\u97f3\u63a7\u5236\u6570\u5b57\u89d2\u8272\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u7528\u6237\u53ef\u4ee5\u968f\u65f6\u901a\u8fc7\u8bed\u97f3\u6307\u4ee4\u63a7\u5236\u89c6\u9891\u5185\u5bb9\u751f\u6210\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u652f\u6301\u65e0\u9650\u957f\u5ea6\u7684\u5b9e\u65f6\u89c6\u9891\u751f\u6210\uff0c\u4e14\u6ca1\u6709\u6a21\u7cca\u3001\u6f02\u79fb\u6216\u89c6\u89c9\u5931\u771f\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u4f7f\u7528 TurboDiffusion \u548c TurboServe\uff0c\u80fd\u591f\u5728\u5e38\u89c4\u6d88\u8d39\u7ea7 GPU \u4e0a\u4ee5 540p \u5206\u8fa8\u7387\u751f\u6210\u6bcf\u79d2 42 \u5e27\u7684\u89c6\u9891\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u7528\u6237\u53ef\u4ee5\u4e0a\u4f20\u81ea\u5b9a\u4e49\u56fe\u50cf\uff0c\u9009\u62e9\u4e0d\u540c\u7684\u58f0\u97f3\u8bed\u8c03\uff0c\u4f53\u9a8c\u4e2a\u6027\u5316\u670d\u52a1\u3002</li>\n</ul>", "summary_simple": "<ul>\n    <li>Vidu S1 is a model that generates interactive videos in real-time using voice commands.</li>\n    <li>It creates high-quality videos without blurring or distortion and can generate videos of any length.</li>\n    <li>The model works on regular consumer GPUs, producing videos at 540p and up to 42 frames per second.</li>\n    <li>Users can upload their own images and select different voice tones for a personalized experience.</li>\n    <li>An online demo is available for users to try out the features of Vidu S1.</li>\n</ul>"}, "publishedAt": "2026-07-02T20:00:00.000Z", "title": "Vidu S1: A Real-Time Interactive Video Generation Model", "summary": "We introduce Vidu S1, a real-time interactive video generation model supporting voice control of digital characters. Users can control video generation content at any moment through voice instructions. Vidu S1 supports infinite-length real-time video generation without blurring, drift, or visual distortion. Built with TurboDiffusion and TurboServe, Vidu S1 outputs 540p real-time videos at up to 42 FPS on regular consumer GPUs. Users can upload custom images of real people, anime, and pets, and choose different voice tones for personalized experiences. Experiments show that Vidu S1 achieves the best performance across all test metrics while fully meeting real-time inference requirements. A playable online demo is available at https://vidu.com/vidu-stream.", "mediaUrls": ["https://cdn-uploads.huggingface.co/production/uploads/66c0a08bac74db25de8427ec/tOyCS73TCOOklV-7xys8i.png"], "thumbnail": "https://cdn-thumbnails.huggingface.co/social-thumbnails/papers/2607.03118.png", "numComments": 6, "submittedBy": {"_id": "66c0a08bac74db25de8427ec", "avatarUrl": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/66c0a08bac74db25de8427ec/9D-piDBZqSt6KNkHImmkv.jpeg", "fullname": "Jintao Zhang", "name": "jt-zhang", "type": "user", "isPro": false, "isHf": false, "isHfAdmin": false, "isMod": false, "followerCount": 56, "isUserFollowing": false}, "organization": {"_id": "628735cbc83a2d6ab8d14a66", "name": "Tsinghua", "fullname": "Tsinghua University", "avatar": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/6c5c1441e3283e7543342e59277ea219?d=retro&size=100"}, "isAuthorParticipating": true}, {"paper": {"id": "2607.13125", "authors": [{"_id": "6a585e6f69aa0f8878bddbe2", "name": "Guoxuan Chen", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a585e6f69aa0f8878bddbe3", "name": "Chufeng Xiao", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a585e6f69aa0f8878bddbe4", "name": "Haoran Yang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a585e6f69aa0f8878bddbe5", "name": "Siyue Xie", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a585e6f69aa0f8878bddbe6", "name": "Binxiao Huang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a585e6f69aa0f8878bddbe7", "name": "Ming Zhang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a585e6f69aa0f8878bddbe8", "name": "Cheuk Him Chau", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a585e6f69aa0f8878bddbe9", "name": "Xinyu Fu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a585e6f69aa0f8878bddbea", "name": "Yingzhao Lian", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a585e6f69aa0f8878bddbeb", "name": "Tom S. Y. Li", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a585e6f69aa0f8878bddbec", "name": "Jintao Lin", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a585e6f69aa0f8878bddbed", "name": "Bowen Dong", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a585e6f69aa0f8878bddbee", "name": "Zian Qian", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a585e6f69aa0f8878bddbef", "name": "Yuhao Liu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a585e6f69aa0f8878bddbf0", "name": "Yuxuan Hu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a585e6f69aa0f8878bddbf1", "name": "Weikang Shi", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a585e6f69aa0f8878bddbf2", "name": "Bin Zou", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a585e6f69aa0f8878bddbf3", "name": "Bowen Zheng", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a585e6f69aa0f8878bddbf4", "name": "Haoxuan Che", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a585e6f69aa0f8878bddbf5", "name": "Chang Chen", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a585e6f69aa0f8878bddbf6", "name": "Yuyang He", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a585e6f69aa0f8878bddbf7", "name": "Heyang Sun", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a585e6f69aa0f8878bddbf8", "name": "Tianyu Huang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a585e6f69aa0f8878bddbf9", "name": "Chong Hou Choi", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a585e6f69aa0f8878bddbfa", "name": "Cheng Gong", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a585e6f69aa0f8878bddbfb", "name": "Han Shi", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a585e6f69aa0f8878bddbfc", "name": "Haoli Bai", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a585e6f69aa0f8878bddbfd", "name": "Xihui Liu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a585e6f69aa0f8878bddbfe", "name": "Hongsheng Li", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a585e6f69aa0f8878bddbff", "name": "Qifeng Chen", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a585e6f69aa0f8878bddc00", "name": "Chao Huang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a585e6f69aa0f8878bddc01", "name": "Rui Liu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a585e6f69aa0f8878bddc02", "name": "Chenyang Lei", "hidden": false}], "publishedAt": "2026-07-14T00:00:00.000Z", "submittedOnDailyAt": "2026-07-16T00:00:00.000Z", "title": "Boogu-Image-0.1: Boosting Open-Source Unified Multimodal Understanding and Generation", "submittedOnDailyBy": {"_id": "63a2ca27dca41424cb8387a3", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/ae9bec9c2326184e94faa8d6fd98f2da.svg", "isPro": false, "fullname": "X", "user": "Chufeng", "type": "user", "name": "Chufeng"}, "summary": "We introduce Boogu-Image-0.1, an open-source unified multimodal understanding and generation model family, comprising Base, Turbo, Edit, and Edit-Turbo variants. It delivers competitive performance in high-quality text-to-image generation, fast inference, instruction-based editing, and bilingual (Chinese-English) text rendering. Closed-source multimodal systems like Nano-Banana-Pro and GPT-Image-2 achieve strong performance through system-level integration rather than a single model, yet their internal practices remain largely undisclosed. In this work, we demonstrate that targeted improvements in model understanding, data quality, and training pipelines, coupled with agentic inference-time scaling, can substantially enhance generation and editing performance even under highly constrained compute budgets. Comprehensive evaluations show that Boogu-Image-0.1 consistently matches or surpasses other open-source models across standard benchmarks, and achieves results approaching leading closed-source systems. Notably, this is accomplished with only 208.62 million unique images. The base model's theoretical training cost is only approximately \\$400K. We share practical discussions that we believe are valuable to the broader research community, and release weights, code, and recipes under Apache 2.0 to advance the open ecosystem for unified multimodal understanding and generation. Our code is available here: https://github.com/Boogu-Project/Boogu-Image.", "upvotes": 107, "discussionId": "6a585e7069aa0f8878bddc03", "projectPage": "https://boogu.org/", "githubRepo": "https://github.com/boogu-project/Boogu-Image", "githubRepoAddedBy": "user", "githubStars": 755, "organization": {"_id": "6a2f735add4271ad7948febc", "name": "Boogu", "fullname": "Boogu", "avatar": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/6a2f728163c271161df8f4a7/gRDLtMmEnc3HIVldi5HjH.png"}, "summary_zh": "<ul>\n    <li>\u63a8\u51fa\u4e86Boogu-Image-0.1\uff0c\u8fd9\u662f\u4e00\u4e2a\u5f00\u6e90\u7684\u591a\u6a21\u6001\u7406\u89e3\u548c\u751f\u6210\u6a21\u578b\uff0c\u5305\u542b\u591a\u4e2a\u53d8\u4f53\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u8be5\u6a21\u578b\u5728\u9ad8\u8d28\u91cf\u6587\u672c\u5230\u56fe\u50cf\u751f\u6210\u3001\u5feb\u901f\u63a8\u7406\u548c\u53cc\u8bed\u6587\u672c\u6e32\u67d3\u65b9\u9762\u8868\u73b0\u4f18\u79c0\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u4e0e\u4e00\u4e9b\u5c01\u95ed\u6e90\u7684\u591a\u6a21\u6001\u7cfb\u7edf\u76f8\u6bd4\uff0cBoogu-Image-0.1\u5728\u6807\u51c6\u57fa\u51c6\u6d4b\u8bd5\u4e2d\u8868\u73b0\u51fa\u8272\uff0c\u751a\u81f3\u63a5\u8fd1\u9886\u5148\u7684\u5c01\u95ed\u6e90\u7cfb\u7edf\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u8be5\u6a21\u578b\u7684\u8bad\u7ec3\u6210\u672c\u7ea6\u4e3a40\u4e07\u7f8e\u5143\uff0c\u4f7f\u7528\u4e86\u4ec5208.62\u767e\u4e07\u5f20\u72ec\u7279\u56fe\u50cf\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u63d0\u4f9b\u4e86\u4ee3\u7801\u548c\u6a21\u578b\u6743\u91cd\uff0c\u652f\u6301\u5f00\u653e\u751f\u6001\u7cfb\u7edf\u7684\u53d1\u5c55\uff0c\u4f9b\u7814\u7a76\u793e\u533a\u4f7f\u7528\u3002</li>\n</ul>", "summary_simple": "<ul>\n    <li>Boogu-Image-0.1 is an open-source model for understanding and generating images and text, with different versions like Base, Turbo, Edit, and Edit-Turbo.</li>\n    <li>It performs well in generating high-quality images from text and can handle bilingual text (Chinese-English).</li>\n    <li>The model achieves strong results even with limited computing resources and fewer training images compared to some closed-source models.</li>\n    <li>Boogu-Image-0.1 has a low theoretical training cost of about $400K and consistently outperforms other open-source models.</li>\n    <li>We provide resources like code and model weights to support research in this area, available under the Apache 2.0 license.</li>\n</ul>"}, "publishedAt": "2026-07-13T20:00:00.000Z", "title": "Boogu-Image-0.1: Boosting Open-Source Unified Multimodal Understanding and Generation", "summary": "We introduce Boogu-Image-0.1, an open-source unified multimodal understanding and generation model family, comprising Base, Turbo, Edit, and Edit-Turbo variants. It delivers competitive performance in high-quality text-to-image generation, fast inference, instruction-based editing, and bilingual (Chinese-English) text rendering. Closed-source multimodal systems like Nano-Banana-Pro and GPT-Image-2 achieve strong performance through system-level integration rather than a single model, yet their internal practices remain largely undisclosed. In this work, we demonstrate that targeted improvements in model understanding, data quality, and training pipelines, coupled with agentic inference-time scaling, can substantially enhance generation and editing performance even under highly constrained compute budgets. Comprehensive evaluations show that Boogu-Image-0.1 consistently matches or surpasses other open-source models across standard benchmarks, and achieves results approaching leading closed-source systems. Notably, this is accomplished with only 208.62 million unique images. The base model's theoretical training cost is only approximately \\$400K. We share practical discussions that we believe are valuable to the broader research community, and release weights, code, and recipes under Apache 2.0 to advance the open ecosystem for unified multimodal understanding and generation. Our code is available here: https://github.com/Boogu-Project/Boogu-Image.", "thumbnail": "https://cdn-thumbnails.huggingface.co/social-thumbnails/papers/2607.13125.png", "numComments": 2, "submittedBy": {"_id": "63a2ca27dca41424cb8387a3", "avatarUrl": "/avatars/ae9bec9c2326184e94faa8d6fd98f2da.svg", "fullname": "X", "name": "Chufeng", "type": "user", "isPro": false, "isHf": false, "isHfAdmin": false, "isMod": false, "isUserFollowing": false}, "organization": {"_id": "6a2f735add4271ad7948febc", "name": "Boogu", "fullname": "Boogu", "avatar": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/6a2f728163c271161df8f4a7/gRDLtMmEnc3HIVldi5HjH.png"}, "isAuthorParticipating": false}, {"paper": {"id": "2607.05394", "authors": [{"_id": "6a4f1dad48d70828b718dea7", "name": "Shiyuan Feng", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4f1dad48d70828b718dea8", "name": "Huan-ang Gao", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4f1dad48d70828b718dea9", "name": "Haohan Chi", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4f1dad48d70828b718deaa", "name": "Hanlin Wu", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4f1dad48d70828b718deab", "name": "Zhilong Zhang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4f1dad48d70828b718deac", "name": "Zheng Jiang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4f1dad48d70828b718dead", "name": "Bingxiang He", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4f1dad48d70828b718deae", "name": "Wei-Ying Ma", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4f1dad48d70828b718deaf", "name": "Ya-Qin Zhang", "hidden": false}, {"_id": "6a4f1dad48d70828b718deb0", "name": "Hao Zhou", "hidden": false}], "publishedAt": "2026-07-08T00:00:00.000Z", "submittedOnDailyAt": "2026-07-14T00:00:00.000Z", "title": "Weak-to-Strong Generalization via Direct On-Policy Distillation", "submittedOnDailyBy": {"_id": "64b1303bf460afaefcf922c2", "avatarUrl": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/noauth/0zhdXXravx0CKJLTSVDwU.jpeg", "isPro": false, "fullname": "Huan-ang Gao", "user": "c7w", "type": "user", "name": "c7w"}, "summary": "Reinforcement learning with verifiable rewards (RLVR) is a powerful recipe for improving language-model reasoning, but it is expensive to repeat on every new strong model because the target model must generate many rollouts during training. As models scale, post-training itself becomes a bottleneck. We study a weak-to-strong alternative: run RL on a smaller model where rollouts are cheaper, then reuse what that RL run learned to improve a stronger target model. Directly distilling the post-RL weak teacher is not enough, because the teacher's final policy mixes useful RL gains with the limitations of the smaller model. We propose Direct On-Policy Distillation (Direct-OPD), which transfers the teacher's RL-induced policy shift instead. Direct-OPD compares the post-RL teacher with its own pre-RL reference and treats their log-ratio as a dense implicit reward for the student. In plain terms, the checkpoint pair tells us which actions RL made the weak model more or less likely to take, and Direct-OPD applies that signal on the stronger student's own on-policy states. This directly reuses the weak model's RL supervision signal without running sparse-reward RL on the target model. Empirically, Direct-OPD consistently leverages weaker teachers to improve stronger target models; notably, it boosts Qwen3-1.7B from 48.3% to 58.3% on AIME 2024 in just 4 hours on 8 A100 GPUs. It outperforms step-matched direct RL and enables the sequential composition of multiple policy shifts. Our results show that RL outcomes can be reused across model scales as implicit reward signals, not merely as final models to imitate.", "upvotes": 93, "discussionId": "6a4f1dad48d70828b718deb1", "projectPage": "https://bytedtsinghua-sia.github.io/Direct-OPD/", "ai_summary": "Direct On-Policy Distillation transfers reinforcement learning improvements from smaller to larger models by using the policy shift induced by RL as an implicit reward signal, enabling efficient scaling of training without re-running expensive RL on the target model.", "ai_keywords": ["reinforcement learning", "verifiable rewards", "weak-to-strong transfer", "direct on-policy distillation", "policy shift", "implicit reward", "post-RL reference", "on-policy states", "sequential composition", "AIME 2024"], "ai_summary_model": "Qwen/Qwen2.5-Coder-32B-Instruct", "organization": {"_id": "67d7e43826aaec170a42d8ad", "name": "BytedTsinghua-SIA", "fullname": "BytedTsinghua-SIA", "avatar": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/6341375be5071b0c5cc946a3/GSHXRdrZqDOzqHrfcZ0d5.png"}, "summary_zh": "<ul>\n    <li>\u5f3a\u5316\u5b66\u4e60\u4e0e\u53ef\u9a8c\u8bc1\u5956\u52b1\uff08RLVR\uff09\u80fd\u63d0\u9ad8\u8bed\u8a00\u6a21\u578b\u7684\u63a8\u7406\u80fd\u529b\uff0c\u4f46\u5728\u6bcf\u4e2a\u65b0\u6a21\u578b\u4e0a\u8bad\u7ec3\u6210\u672c\u8f83\u9ad8\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u7814\u7a76\u4e86\u4e00\u79cd\u5f31\u5230\u5f3a\u7684\u66ff\u4ee3\u65b9\u6cd5\uff1a\u5148\u5728\u5c0f\u6a21\u578b\u4e0a\u8fdb\u884cRL\u8bad\u7ec3\uff0c\u518d\u5c06\u5b66\u4e60\u5230\u7684\u77e5\u8bc6\u5e94\u7528\u4e8e\u66f4\u5f3a\u7684\u76ee\u6807\u6a21\u578b\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u63d0\u51fa\u4e86\u76f4\u63a5\u5728\u7ebf\u7b56\u7565\u84b8\u998f\uff08Direct-OPD\uff09\uff0c\u5b83\u8f6c\u79fb\u6559\u5e08\u6a21\u578b\u7684RL\u7b56\u7565\u53d8\u5316\uff0c\u800c\u4e0d\u662f\u76f4\u63a5\u84b8\u998f\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u901a\u8fc7\u6bd4\u8f83\u6559\u5e08\u6a21\u578b\u7684RL\u540e\u548cRL\u524d\u7684\u8868\u73b0\uff0cDirect-OPD\u4e3a\u5b66\u751f\u6a21\u578b\u63d0\u4f9b\u4e86\u9690\u6027\u5956\u52b1\u4fe1\u53f7\u3002</li>\n    <li>\u5b9e\u9a8c\u8bc1\u660e\uff0cDirect-OPD\u80fd\u6709\u6548\u5229\u7528\u5f31\u6559\u5e08\u6539\u5584\u5f3a\u76ee\u6807\u6a21\u578b\uff0c\u5e76\u5728\u77ed\u65f6\u95f4\u5185\u663e\u8457\u63d0\u9ad8\u6a21\u578b\u6027\u80fd\u3002</li>\n</ul>", "summary_simple": "<ul>\n    <li>Reinforcement learning with verifiable rewards (RLVR) helps improve reasoning in language models, but it's costly to implement on every new model.</li>\n    <li>To save resources, researchers suggest training a smaller model first and using its learning to enhance a stronger model.</li>\n    <li>Direct On-Policy Distillation (Direct-OPD) is introduced, which transfers the improvements from the weaker model to the stronger one without directly copying the weaker model's behavior.</li>\n    <li>Direct-OPD uses a comparison of the weaker model's performance before and after reinforcement learning to provide feedback for the stronger model.</li>\n    <li>This method has shown to significantly improve the performance of stronger models in a short time, indicating that reinforcement learning benefits can be reused across different model sizes. </li>\n</ul>"}, "publishedAt": "2026-07-07T20:00:00.000Z", "title": "Weak-to-Strong Generalization via Direct On-Policy Distillation", "summary": "Reinforcement learning with verifiable rewards (RLVR) is a powerful recipe for improving language-model reasoning, but it is expensive to repeat on every new strong model because the target model must generate many rollouts during training. As models scale, post-training itself becomes a bottleneck. We study a weak-to-strong alternative: run RL on a smaller model where rollouts are cheaper, then reuse what that RL run learned to improve a stronger target model. Directly distilling the post-RL weak teacher is not enough, because the teacher's final policy mixes useful RL gains with the limitations of the smaller model. We propose Direct On-Policy Distillation (Direct-OPD), which transfers the teacher's RL-induced policy shift instead. Direct-OPD compares the post-RL teacher with its own pre-RL reference and treats their log-ratio as a dense implicit reward for the student. In plain terms, the checkpoint pair tells us which actions RL made the weak model more or less likely to take, and Direct-OPD applies that signal on the stronger student's own on-policy states. This directly reuses the weak model's RL supervision signal without running sparse-reward RL on the target model. Empirically, Direct-OPD consistently leverages weaker teachers to improve stronger target models; notably, it boosts Qwen3-1.7B from 48.3% to 58.3% on AIME 2024 in just 4 hours on 8 A100 GPUs. It outperforms step-matched direct RL and enables the sequential composition of multiple policy shifts. Our results show that RL outcomes can be reused across model scales as implicit reward signals, not merely as final models to imitate.", "thumbnail": "https://cdn-thumbnails.huggingface.co/social-thumbnails/papers/2607.05394.png", "numComments": 2, "submittedBy": {"_id": "64b1303bf460afaefcf922c2", "avatarUrl": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/noauth/0zhdXXravx0CKJLTSVDwU.jpeg", "fullname": "Huan-ang Gao", "name": "c7w", "type": "user", "isPro": false, "isHf": false, "isHfAdmin": false, "isMod": false, "followerCount": 3, "isUserFollowing": false}, "organization": {"_id": "67d7e43826aaec170a42d8ad", "name": "BytedTsinghua-SIA", "fullname": "BytedTsinghua-SIA", "avatar": "https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/6341375be5071b0c5cc946a3/GSHXRdrZqDOzqHrfcZ0d5.png"}, "isAuthorParticipating": false}]
};
